e=28 November 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><br />[[World War I]]<ref name=\"History\"/><br />[[World War II]]<ref name=\"History\"/><br />[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br />[[Iraq War]]\n| anniversaries = Centennial, 1989\n| decorations = [[File:USPH Presidential Unit Citation.svg|23px|border]] [[Presidential Unit Citation (United States)|Presidential Unit Citation]] (2015)\n| battle_honours = <!-- Commanders -->\n| commander1 = ADM [[Brett Giroir|Brett P. Giroir]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hhs.gov/ash/about-ash/leadership/brett-giroir/index.html|title=ADM Brett P. Giroir, M.D.|date=15 February 2018|website=HHS.gov}}</ref>\n| commander1_label = [[Assistant Secretary for Health]]\n| commander2 = VADM [[Jerome Adams]]\n| commander2_label = [[Surgeon General of the United States|Surgeon General]]\n| commander3 = RADM [[Sylvia Trent-Adams]]\n| commander3_label = Principal Deputy Assistant Secretary for Health\n| commander4 = RADM [[Erica Schwartz|Erica G. Schwartz]]\n| commander4_label = Deputy Surgeon General\n| notable_commanders = {{Ubl\n | ADM [[John O. Agwunobi]]\n | ADM [[Joxel Garc\u00eda]]\n | ADM [[James O. Mason]]\n | ADM [[David Satcher]]\n | VADM [[C. Everett Koop]]\n | VADM [[Julius B. Richmond]]\n}}\n<!-- Insignia -->| identification_symbol =\n| identification_symbol_label =\n| identification_symbol_2 = \n| identification_symbol_3 = \n| identification_symbol_4 = \n| identification_symbol_2_label = \n| identification_symbol_3_label = \n| identification_symbol_4_label = <!-- Aircraft -->\n| aircraft_attack = \n| aircraft_bomber = \n| aircraft_electronic = \n| aircraft_fighter = \n| aircraft_helicopter = \n| aircraft_interceptor = \n| aircraft_patrol = \n| aircraft_recon = \n| aircraft_trainer = \n| aircraft_transport = \n}}\n\nThe '''United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps''' ('''PHSCC'''),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.surgeongeneral.gov/about/corps/index.html|title=U.S. Public Health Service Commissioned Corps|website=Surgeongeneral.gov|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref> also referred to as the '''Commissioned Corps of the United States Public Health Service''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usphs.gov/aboutus/|title=USPHS: About Us|website=www.usphs.gov|accessdate=2 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070710230635/http://www.usphs.gov/aboutus/|archive-date=10 July 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is the federal uniformed service of the [[United States Public Health Service|U.S. Public Health Service]] (PHS), and is one of the eight [[uniformed services of the United States]]. The commissioned corps' primary mission is to the protection, promotion, and advancement of health and safety of the general public.\n\nAlong with the [[NOAA Commissioned Officer Corps]], the Public Health Service Commissioned Corps is one of two uniformed services that consist only of [[commissioned officers]] and has no [[Enlisted rank|enlisted]] or [[Warrant Officer (United States)|warrant officer]] ranks, although warrant officers have been authorized for use within the service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/42/204|title=42 U.S. Code \u00a7 204 - Commissioned Corps and Ready Reserve Corps|website=LII / Legal Information Institute|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref> Officers of the commissioned corps are classified as noncombatants, unless directed to serve as part of the [[United States armed forces|military]] by the [[President of the United States|President]] or detailed to a service branch of the military.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www4.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/10/802|title=10 U.S. Code \u00a7 802 - Art. 2. Persons subject to this chapter|website=LII / Legal Information Institute|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref> Members of the commissioned corps wear the same uniforms as the [[United States Navy]], or the [[United States Coast Guard]] (when assigned to the Coast Guard), with special PHS Commissioned Corps insignia, and hold naval ranks equivalent to officers of the U.S. Navy and U.S. Coast Guard. Commissioned corps officers typically receive their commissions through the commissioned corps's [[Direct commission officer|direct commissioning program]].\n\nAs with its parent division, the Public Health Service, the commissioned corps is under the direction of the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]]. The commissioned corps is led by the [[Surgeon General of the United States|Surgeon General]], who holds the grade of [[Vice admiral (United States)|vice admiral]].<ref name=Uniforms>{{cite web |url=http://www.usphs.gov/AboutUs/uniforms.aspx |title=U.S. Public Health Service Commissioned Corps |publisher=U.S. Department of Health and Human Services |accessdate=24 June 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513175033/http://www.usphs.gov/AboutUs/uniforms.aspx |archive-date=13 May 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Surgeon General reports directly to the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|Department of Health and Human Services]], [[Assistant Secretary for Health]]; the Assistant Secretary of Health may be appointed to the rank of [[Admiral (United States)|admiral]] if he or she is also a serving uniformed officer of the commissioned corps.<ref name=Uniforms/>\n\n==History==\nThe Public Health Service Commissioned Corps had its beginnings with the creation of the Marine Hospital Fund in 1798, which later was reorganized in 1871 as the [[Marine Hospital Service]]. The Marine Hospital Service was charged with the care and maintenance of merchant sailors, but as the country grew, so did the ever-expanding mission of the service. The Marine Hospital Service soon began taking on new expanding health roles that included such health initiatives that protected the commerce and health of America. One such role was [[quarantine]].\n\n[[John Maynard Woodworth]], a famous surgeon of the Union Army who served under General [[William Tecumseh Sherman]], was appointed in 1871 as the Supervising Surgeon. Woodworth's title was later changed to \"Supervising Surgeon General,\" which later became the [[Surgeon General of the United States]]. Woodworth is credited with the formal creation of the Commissioned Corps. Woodworth organized the Marine Hospital Service medical personnel along Army military structure in 1889 to facilitate a mobile force of health professionals that could be moved for the needs of the service and country. He established appointment standards and designed the Marine Hospital Service herald of a [[Foul (nautical)#Fouled anchor|fouled anchor]] and [[Caduceus as a symbol of medicine|caduceus]]. Later that year of 1889, President Grover Cleveland signed an Act into law that formally established the modern Public Health Service Commissioned Corps (then the [[Marine Hospital Service]] under the Supervising Surgeon (later Surgeon General)). At first open only to [[physician]]s, over the course of the twentieth century, the Corps expanded to 11 careers in a wide range of specialties to include veterinarians, [[dentist]]s, engineers, [[pharmacist]]s, [[nurse]]s, environmental health specialists, [[scientist]]s, dietitians, and other [[allied health professional]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://usphs.gov/profession/|title=USPHS: Career & Benefits|website=usphs.gov|access-date=2016-11-06}}</ref>\n\nToday, the commissioned corps is under the [[United States Public Health Service]] (PHS), a major agency now of the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|U.S. Department of Health and Human Services]] (HHS), established by Congress in 1979-1980. It was previously established in 1953 as the [[United States Department of Health, Education and Welfare|U.S. Department of Health, Education and Welfare]] (HEW), and is still led by the [[Surgeon General of the United States|Surgeon General]]. The commissioned corps allocates officers to all seven uniformed services depending on the health or medical needs of the other uniformed services. The commissioned corps was featured in the 1950 motion picture [[Panic in the Streets (film)|''Panic in the Streets'']], in which [[Richard Widmark]] portrayed a Public Health Service physician tracking down a victim of [[pneumonic plague]], an infectious disease that is one of three forms of [[plague]], the other two being [[septicemic plague]] and [[bubonic plague]].\n\n==Purpose==\nThe stated mission of the Commissioned Corps of the U.S. Public Health Service is \"Protecting, promoting, and advancing the health and safety of the Nation\" in accordance with the commissioned corps's four Core Values: Leadership, Excellence, Integrity, and Service. Officers execute the mission of the commissioned corps in the following ways:\n*Help provide healthcare and related services to medically underserved populations: to [[American Indians in the United States|American Indians]], [[Alaska Natives]], and to other population groups with special needs;\n*Prevent and control disease, identify health hazards in the environment and help correct them, and promote healthy lifestyles for the nation's citizens;\n*Improve the nation's mental health; \n*Ensure that drugs and medical devices are safe and effective, food is safe and wholesome, cosmetics are harmless, and that electronic products do not expose users to dangerous amounts of radiation;\n*Conduct and support biomedical, behavioral, and health services research, and communicate research results to health professionals and the public; and\n*Work with other nations and international agencies on global health problems and their solutions.\n\nPlus, the commissioned corps provides officers (Medical Officers, Dental Officers, Therapists, Environmental Health Officers, etc.) to other uniformed services, primarily the [[United States Coast Guard]] and the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Commissioned Officer Corps]] (NOAA Corps). Commissioned corps officers may be detailed to other federal agencies including the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]], [[TRICARE]], [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] ([[Federal Bureau of Prisons]]), [[United States Department of State|State Department]], [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]], and the [[United States Department of the Interior|Department of the Interior]] ([[National Park Service]]). Commissioned corps officers may develop individual memoranda of understanding (MOUs) with other organizations, including state and local health agencies, and even non-governmental organizations (NGOs).\n\nThe Commissioned Corps is often called upon by other federal, state, and local agencies to aid and augment in times when those agencies' resources are overwhelmed. These responses are designated as deployments by the commissioned corps, if the deployment is outside of the officer's \"normal\" duties, and coordinated through the commissioned corps's Readiness and Deployment Operations Group (REDDOG) in the Division of Commissioned Corps Personnel and Readiness (DCCPR).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.usphs.gov/newsroom/features/recent/deployments.aspx|title=Commisisoned Corps Deployments: Public Health Emergency Responders|last=|first=|date=September 19, 2014|website=Usphs.gov|access-date=2016-11-06}}</ref> Deployments may be for technical needs in standard settings, or in the event of disasters, in austere environments.\n\n==Deployments==\nThe commissioned corps is often deployed as part of the [[National Response Framework]] Emergency Support Function #8 \u2013 Public Health and Medical Services, but can be deployed outside of the Framework for various needs to other federal agencies, states, local governments, or even to aid foreign governments. Like all other federal-level responses, commissioned corps officers are deployed only upon request, and upon the recommendation of the [[Surgeon General of the United States|Surgeon General]] and permission of the [[Assistant Secretary for Health]]. During deployments, commissioned corps officers may report to regular office spaces, such as coordinating responses at state-of-the-art emergency operations centers, or into the field in extremely austere environments, such as when responding to a natural disaster. In addition, deployments may either be on an individual basis, such as when specific skill sets are needed, or as part of a team, when large-scale responses are needed.\n\nThe commissioned corps uses a tiered system of response, with Tier 1 response teams ready and able to respond to an event within 12 hours, and Tier 2 teams ready and able to respond within 36 hours. Officers not on Tier 1 or 2 teams are Tier 3 responders, ready and able to respond to an event in 72 hours. Tier 1 teams are primarily made up of Rapid Deployment Force (RDF) teams that are made up of over 100 officers with multiple specialties, and are focused on providing acute clinical care of disaster-exacerbated chronic conditions. Officers who do not work as a clinical care provider on one of these teams are often in support roles, such as logistics, administration/finance, or planning. Tier 2 teams are composed of a smaller, more specialized workforce. Current Tier 2 teams include the Applied Public Health Team (APHT), the Mental Health Team (MHT), and the Services Access Team (SAT). Tier 3 commissioned corps officers not already assigned to one of the Tier 1 and Tier 2 teams are used to augment the Tier 1 and Tier 2 teams in the event of staffing shortages due to availability, or the need to scale up a response.\n\nThey are trained and equipped to respond to public health crises and national emergencies, such as natural disasters, disease outbreaks, or terrorist attacks. The teams are multidisciplinary and are capable of responding to domestic and international humanitarian missions.  Some notable deployments involving the Public Health Service Commissioned Corps include:<ref name=\"emergencyresponse\">US Department of Health and Human Services. [http://www.usphs.gov/AboutUs/emergencyresponse.aspx Emergency Response at Commissioned Corps] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130194950/http://usphs.gov/aboutus/emergencyresponse.aspx|date=2010-11-30}}</ref>\n\n* 1989 \u2013 [[Hurricane Hugo]]; [[1989 Loma Prieta earthquake|Loma Prieta, California, earthquake]].{{citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n* 1992 \u2013 More than 1,000 PHS officers were deployed to [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|South Dade County, Florida]], following [[Hurricane Andrew]].\n* Early 1990s \u2013 Flooding throughout the United States and [[Alaska]].\n* 1994 \u2013 [[1994 Northridge earthquake|Northridge, California, earthquake]].\n* 1995 \u2013 [[Oklahoma City bombing|Bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building]] in [[Oklahoma City|Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]].\n* 1995 \u2013 Hundreds of PHS officers were deployed to the [[United States Virgin Islands|U.S. Virgin Islands]] following [[Hurricane Marilyn]].\n* 1999 \u2013 Hospital center at [[Fort Dix]], New Jersey, for [[Kosovo War|Kosovo Refugees]]\n* 2001 \u2013 More than 1,000 PHS officers were deployed to [[New York City]] after the [[September 11, 2001 attacks|attacks on September 11, 2001]] to aid victims and provide medical and mental health services to responders and rescue workers.\n* 2001 \u2013 [[2001 anthrax attacks]]\n* 2004 \u2013 [[Hurricane Ivan]].\n* 2004 \u2013 [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami]]\n* 2005 \u2013 More than 2,000 PHS officers deployed to set up field hospitals and render aid and assistance to evacuees and responders in the wakes of [[Hurricane Katrina]], [[Hurricane Rita]], and [[Hurricane Wilma]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dcp.psc.gov/ccbulletin/articles/OFRD_112805.htm|title=DCP.PSC.gov|website=Dcp.psc.gov|accessdate=2 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528015937/http://dcp.psc.gov/ccbulletin/articles/OFRD_112805.htm|archive-date=28 May 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2006 \u2013 [[2006 Kiholo Bay earthquake]]<ref name=\"emergencyresponse\" />\n* 2007 \u2013 [[Toxic cough syrup|Medicine Contamination in Panama]]\n* 2008 \u2013 PHS-2 Rapid Deployment Force deployed pre-landfall to [[Louisiana]] in advance of [[Hurricane Gustav]]. It became the first standing PHS team to set up and run a Federal Medical Station. The team and 200 patients rode out the hurricane in [[Alexandria, Louisiana|Alexandria's]] Riverfront Center. RDF-1 and RDF-3 deployed pre-landfall in advance of [[Hurricane Ike]] to set up Federal Medical Stations in [[College Station, Texas]], and [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]], respectively.\n* 2008 \u2013 [[Hurricane Ike]]\n* 2009 \u2013 [[2009 Samoa earthquake and tsunami]]\n* 2010 \u2013 [[2010 Haiti earthquake|Haiti earthquake]]; [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill]] in the [[Gulf of Mexico]].\n* 2011 \u2013 [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami|2011 Japan tsunami and earthquake]]\n* 2012 \u2013 [[Hurricane Sandy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usphs.gov/newsroom/features/hurricane-sandy-response-inside-look.aspx|title=USPHS: Error occurred!|website=www.usphs.gov|accessdate=2 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130318043649/http://www.usphs.gov/newsroom/features/hurricane-sandy-response-inside-look.aspx|archive-date=18 March 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2014 \u2013 [[2014 American immigration crisis]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/06/20/fact-sheet-unaccompanied-children-central-america|title=FACT SHEET: Unaccompanied Children from Central America|date=20 June 2014|publisher=}}</ref> of Unaccompanied Minor Children.\n* 2014\u20132015 \u2013 [[West African Ebola virus epidemic|Ebola outbreak]] response<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/09/16/fact-sheet-us-response-ebola-epidemic-west-africa|title=FACT SHEET: U.S. Response to the Ebola Epidemic in West Africa|date=16 September 2014|website=Whitehouse.gov|accessdate=2 November 2017}}</ref> including [[Ebola virus epidemic in Liberia]]\u2014Ebola field hospital for health workers at [[Harbel]] near [[Monrovia]]<ref name=\"NYT110514\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/06/world/africa/treating-those-treating-ebola-in-liberia.html \"Treating Those Treating Ebola in Liberia]\" article by Sheri Fink in ''[[The New York Times]]'', November 5, 2014</ref>\n* 2016\u2013present \u2013 [[Great Plains]] region of the [[Indian Health Service]].\n* 2017\u2013present \u2013 [[Hurricane Maria]], [[Hurricane Irma]], and [[Hurricane Harvey]]\n* 2019-present - [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\nIn addition to disaster response, the commissioned corps frequently partners with the [[United States Navy]] on their health diplomacy missions. PHS Corps officers have been part of the Navy's [[Pacific Partnership]] (in the Pacific basin) and [[Operation Continuing Promise|Continuing Promise]] (in the Caribbean/west Atlantic) since 2007. Such missions are often carried out on either the US Navy's commissioned hospital ships, the {{USNS|Mercy|T-AH-19}} or {{USNS|Comfort|T-AH-20}}, though other ships, such as the amphibious assault ship {{USS|Bataan|LHD-5}}, have also been used. The command staff of the PHS deployed team(s) is deployed for the entire mission duration (often three months), while operational personnel serve one month aboard, meeting and departing the ships at the ports of call during the mission.\n\nThe commissioned corps, as a uniformed service, may be militarized and considered a branch of the armed forces by an act of Congress, or by executive order by the President of the United States, not only in time of war, but in \"an emergency involving the national defense proclaimed by the President.\" Major militarization of the corps occurred during [[World War II]] and another later during the [[Korean War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dcp.psc.gov/ccbulletin/PDF_docs/Oct01ccb.pdf|title=DCP.PSC.gov|website=Dcp.psc.gov|accessdate=2 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051110005939/http://dcp.psc.gov/ccbulletin/PDF_docs/Oct01ccb.pdf|archive-date=10 November 2005|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Uniforms and insignia==\n{{Multiple image\n|footer    = '''USPHS Commissioned Corps uniforms'''\n|width1    = 125\n|image1    = service dress blues.jpg\n|alt1      = Service Dress Blues\n|caption1  = Service dress blues\n|width2    = 125\n|image2    = summer whites.jpg|130px\n|alt2      = Summer Whites\n|caption2  = Summer whites\n|width3    = 125\n|image3    = Summer khakis.jpg\n|alt3      = Service Khakis\n|caption3  = Service khakis\n|width4    = 263\n|image4    = US Public Health Service Operation United Assistance 2014.jpg\n|alt4      = USCG, NOAA Corps, and USPHS Operational Dress Uniform\n|caption4  = [[Operational Dress Uniform|Operational dress uniform]]\n}}\n{{Multiple image\n|width1    = 126\n|image1    = CAP DEVICE UNMOUNTED PHS.PNG\n|caption1  = PHSCC combination cap device\n|width2    = 122\n|image2    = PHSCC Collar Device.png\n|caption2  = PHSCC cap, collar, and sleeve device\n|width3    = 124\n|image3    = PHSCC Lapel Pin.png\n|caption3  = PHSCC lapel pin ''(for civilian dress)''\n|footer    = '''USPHS Commissioned Corps insignia'''\n}}\nCommissioned Corps officers wear uniforms similar to those of the [[United States Navy]] and the [[United States Coast Guard]] with special Public Health Service insignia. Their service dress blues, summer whites, and their service khakis have been modeled after the Navy's versions, and their operational dress uniform was modeled after the Coast Guard's version. In certain duty situations, a commissioned corps officer can be detailed to work with another [[Uniformed services of the United States|uniformed service]]. For example, the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Commissioned Officer Corps|NOAA Corps]] does not commission medical officers, so the commissioned corps details medical officers to support NOAA Corps officer as needed. The commissioned corps also details a number of officers to support the Coast Guard's medical needs. Because of this close relationship, if a commissioned corps officer is on assignment with the Coast Guard, the officer is required to wear the same service uniforms as commissioned Coast Guard officers, but still bearing PHS Commissioned Corps insignia to identify them. The commissioned corps officer is subject to the grooming standards of the service to which attached for uniform appearance.\n\n== Commissioned officers ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n!colspan=11| '''Commissioned officer ranks, pay grades, titles and abbreviations of the United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps'''\n|-\n![[Ensign (rank)|Ensign]]\n![[Lieutenant (junior grade)|Lieutenant<br/>(junior grade)]]\n![[Lieutenant]]\n![[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant commander]]\n![[Commander (United States)|Commander]]\n![[Captain (USPHCC)|Captain]]\n|-\n!O-1\n!O-2\n!O-3\n!O-4\n!O-5\n!O-6\n|-\n| align=\"center\" width=\"16%\"| [[File:US PHS O1 insignia.svg|60px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"16%\"| [[File:US PHS O2 insignia.svg|60px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"16%\"| [[File:US PHS O-3 insignia.svg|60px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"16%\"| [[File:US PHS O4 insignia.svg|60px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"16%\"| [[File:US PHS O5 insignia.svg|60px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"16%\"| [[File:US PHS O6 insignia.svg|60px]]\n|-\n!Junior assistant\n!Assistant\n!Senior assistant\n!Full\n!Senior\n!Director\n|-\n!ENS\n!LTJG\n!LT\n!LCDR\n!CDR\n!CAPT\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n![[Rear admiral (United States)#Rear admiral (lower half)|Rear admiral (lower half)]]\n![[Rear admiral (United States)#Rear admiral|Rear admiral]]\n![[Vice admiral (United States)|Vice admiral]]\n![[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]]\n|-\n!O-7\n!O-8\n!O-9\n!O-10\n|-\n| align=\"center\" width=\"20%\"| [[File:US PHS O7 insignia.svg|60px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"20%\"| [[File:US PHS O8 insignia.svg|60px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"20%\"| [[File:US PHS O9 insignia.svg|60px]]\n| align=\"center\" width=\"20%\"| [[File:US PHS O10 insignia.svg|60px]]\n|-\n!Assistant surgeon general\n!Deputy surgeon general or<br/>Assistant surgeon general\n![[Surgeon General of the United States|Surgeon general]]\n![[Assistant Secretary for Health]]\n|-\n!RADM<ref>{{cite web|title=HHS Promotion Letter|url=http://www.coausphs.org/docs/news/OSG_Announcement_FlagOfficers_2012.pdf|accessdate=5 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130120035449/http://www.coausphs.org/docs/news/OSG_Announcement_FlagOfficers_2012.pdf|archive-date=20 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n!RADM \n!VADM\n!ADM\n|}\n\n==Officer specialty rates==\n\nThe members of the Commissioned Corps number over 6,000 officers in 11 professional categories: \n*[[Dentist]]\n*[[Dietitian]]\n*[[Engineer]]\n*[[Environmental health officer]]s\n*[[Health service|Health service officers]]\n*[[Nurse]]\n*[[Physician |Medical Officer]]\n*[[Pharmacist]]\n*[[Scientist]]\n*[[Therapist]] (including [[Physical therapy|physical]], [[Occupational therapist|occupational]], [[Speech and language pathology|speech]], [[respiratory]])\n*[[Veterinarian]]\n\nThe Health Services Officer (HSO) category comprises over 50 allied health specialties, including [[audiology]], [[social work]]ers, [[physician assistant]]s, [[optometrist]]s, [[statistician]]s, [[computer scientist]]s, [[dental hygienist]]s, [[medical record]]s administrators, [[medical technologist]]s and others.\n\nThe commissioned corps uses the same commissioned officer [[military rank|rank structure]] as the United States [[United States Navy|Navy]] and [[United States Coast Guard|Coast Guard]]: from [[Ensign (rank)|ensign]] to [[Admiral (United States)|admiral]] (O-1 through O-10).  Commissioned Corps officers are typically appointed via [[Direct commission officer|direct commission]], and receive the same [[United States Military Pay|pay]] and benefits as other members of the [[Uniformed services of the United States|uniformed services]]. They cannot hold a dual commission with another uniformed service but inter-service transfers are permitted.\n\nThe commissioned corps may be militarized by the President. 42 USC 217 states:\n<blockquote><poem>In time of war, or of emergency involving the national defense proclaimed by the President, he may by Executive order declare the commissioned corps of the Service to be a military service. Upon such declaration, and during the period of such war or such emergency or such part thereof as the President shall prescribe, the commissioned corps (a) shall constitute a branch of the land and naval forces of the United States, (b) shall, to the extent prescribed by regulations of the President, be subject to the [[Uniform Code of Military Justice]] [10 U.S.C. 801 et seq.], and (c) shall continue to operate as part of the Service except to the extent that the President may direct as Commander in Chief.</poem></blockquote>\n\n===Warrant officers===\nThe commissioned corps is authorized to use [[Warrant officer (United States)|warrant officer]] ranks W-1 to W-4 under the [[United States Code|U.S. Code of law]],<ref>{{UnitedStatesCode|42|204}} - Commissioned Corps and Ready Reserve Corps<br/>{{UnitedStatesCode|42|207}} - Grades, ranks, and titles of commissioned corps<br/>{{UnitedStatesCode|42|209}} - Appointment of personnel</ref> but does not currently use these ranks.\n\n=== Ready Reserve Corps of the Public Health Service Commissioned Corps ===\nThe Affordable Care Act (ACA), signed by President Obama on 23 March 2010, established the Ready Reserve Corps as the new surge capacity for the Commissioned Corps of the U.S. Public Health Service. In addition, all Reserve Corps officers who were serving on extended active duty on 23 March 2010, were converted to Regular Corps officers. The same legislation also abolished the Inactive Reserve Corps (IRC) on 23 March 2010, and consequently the commissions of the existing 10,000 commissioned corps IRC officers. The Office of Reserve Affairs (ORA) sent letters to those individuals, notifying them of their change of status.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dcp.psc.gov/ccbulletin/articles/Reserve_Update.aspx|title=Ready Reserve Corps Update|last=|first=|date=2 September 2010|website=US Public Health Service Commissioned Corps|publisher=Office of Reserve Affairs, Commissioned Corps E-Bulletin|accessdate=14 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe IRC served as an asset for the commissioned corps. Inactive reservists voluntarily activated to provide over 3,000 active-duty days annually for routine and public health emergencies including during Hurricane Katrina and other emergency response missions and in providing surge capacity for numerous shortages in isolated and hardship underserved areas. Inactive reservists also played roles in the humanitarian shipboard training missions with other uniformed services.\n\nCongress established the Ready Reserve Corps to fulfill the need to have additional commissioned corps personnel available on short notice to assist Regular Corps personnel to meet both routine public health and emergency response missions. The Ready Reserve Corps officers will be available and ready for involuntary calls to active duty during national emergencies and public health crises.\n\nBecause of the changes in the law, a Ready Reserve Corps Working Integrated Project Team (WIPT) was convened in April 2010 to propose policy concepts, a strategic framework, and a budget for the Ready Reserve Corps. The WIPT submitted its final report to the Office of Commissioned Corps Force Management (OCCFM) in June 2010, and OCCFM forwarded the recommendations of the WIPT to the Assistant Secretary for Health for review and approval. As of late 2016, the directives and policies to implement the Ready Reserve await Secretarial decisions needed to implement the 2010 law. \n\nStandards for appointment into the Ready Reserve Corps and related proposed directives and policies remain under review. ORA is not accepting applications for the Ready Reserve Corps at this time, but will begin accepting applications after the Secretary issues the implementing directives. \n\nORA, in collaboration with OCCFM and the Office of Commissioned Corps Operations, will continue to coordinate Ready Reserve Corps initiatives and communications. When information is available on the appointment criteria, policies, and application procedures, updates will appear on the USPHS Web site at https://web.archive.org/web/20090506174822/http://www.usphs.gov/ and the Commissioned Corps Management Information System Web site at http://dcp.psc.gov. As soon as the appointment standards are available, qualified individuals are encouraged to apply for appointment into the Ready Reserve Corps.\n\n==March of the United States Public Health Service==\nLike most other [[U.S. uniformed services]], the U.S. Public Health Service has a march and accompanying lyrics.  Composed by retired [[U.S. Coast Guard]] [[Senior chief petty officer#United States|Senior Chief]] [[List of United States Coast Guard ratings#Administrative and scientific group|Musician]] George King III in the late 1980s,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/exhibition/phs_history/music.dir/music.html|title=Images From the History of the Public Health Service: Supplementary Materials|website=www.nlm.nih.gov|access-date=26 February 2018}}</ref> the lyrics are as follows:\n\n<blockquote><poem>The mission of our service is known the world around\nIn research and in treatment no equal can be found\nIn the silent war against disease no truce is ever seen\nWe serve on the land and the sea for humanity\nThe Public Health Service Team<ref>{{cite web|url=http://videocast.nih.gov/closedcaptions/phs120612.txt|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130107225808/http://videocast.nih.gov/closedcaptions/phs120612.txt|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 January 2013|title=Wayback Machine|date=7 January 2013|access-date=26 February 2018}}</ref></poem></blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Awards and decorations of the Public Health Service]]\n* [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Commissioned Officer Corps]]\n* [[Panic in the Streets (film)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Fitzhugh, Mullan. ''Plagues and Politics: The Story of the United States Public Health Service.'' New York: Basic Books, 1989. {{ISBN|0-465-05779-9}}; {{ISBN|978-0-465-05779-5}}.\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.usphs.gov/|United States Public Health Service}}\n\n{{Uniformed services of the United States}}\n{{HHS agencies}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:United States Public Health Service Commissioned Corps| ]]\n[[Category:1798 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Uniformed services of the United States]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1798]]\n", "name_user": "Cuprum17", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Public_Health_Service_Commissioned_Corps"}
{"title_page": "Francis Lewis High School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n| name               = Francis Lewis High School\n| logo               = flhslogo.jpg\n| logo_alt           = Logo of Francis Lewis High School\n| image              = Francis Lewis High School.jpg\n| alt                = Front entrance to Francis Lewis High School\n| image_size         = 300px\n| motto              = Preparing students for success in college, career, and life\n| school_number      = Q430<ref name= q430>\"[https://www.schools.nyc.gov/schools/Q430 Francis Lewis High School]\". ''New York City Department of Education''. Retrieved February 18, 2019.</ref>\n| district           = 26<ref name= q430/> \n| campus_size        = 1.5 acres<ref>\"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/455465163/ New HS Plans to Be Ready by October 1]\". ''New York Daily News''. Jun 23, 1957. p. 8.</ref> \n| streetaddress      = 58-20 [[Utopia Parkway (Queens)|Utopia Parkway]]\n| city               = [[Fresh Meadows, Queens|Fresh Meadows]]\n| state              = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| zipcode            = 11365\n| country            = United States\n| type               = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n| established        = {{start date and age|1960|09|13}}<br/> (first graduating class 1963)\n| status             = Open\n| principal          = David Marmor<ref>\"[http://www.francislewishs.org/about-us/principals-message Principal's Message]\". ''Francis Lewis High School''. Retrieved June 9, 2017.</ref><ref name= about/>\n| grades             = [[Ninth grade|9]] to [[Twelfth grade|12]]\n| athletics          = [[Baseball]], [[basketball]], [[bowling]], [[cricket]], [[cross country running|cross country]], [[fencing]], [[flag football]], [[golf]], [[American handball|handball]], [[indoor track]], [[outdoor track]], [[ping pong]], [[soccer]], [[softball]], [[swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[tennis]], [[track and field|track]], [[volleyball]], [[wrestling]]<ref name= 26q430/> \n| athletics_conference = [[PSAL]]\n| mascot = Patriots\n| nickname  = Lewis, Franny Lew, Franny\n| team_name = Patriots\n| yearbook  = Galaxy\n| website = {{URL|http://www.francislewishs.org}}\n| school_board = [[New York City Public Schools]]\n| ceeb = 331926<ref>\"[https://www.suny.edu/student/search_highschool/hs_searchaction.cfm?popUp=false&year= Francis Lewis High School]\". ''High School CEED Code Search''. The State University of New York. Retrieved February 3, 2019.</ref>\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|44|27|N|73|47|38|W|region:US-NY|display=inline,title}}\n| students = 4,557<ref name= 26q430>\"[https://tools.nycenet.edu/snapshot/2018/26Q430/HS/ Francis Lewis High School]\". ''2017-18 School Quality Snapshot''. New York City Department of Education. Retrieved February 18, 2019.</ref>\n| faculty = 210<ref name= about>\"[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=sites&srcid=ZGVmYXVsdGRvbWFpbnxmbGhzMTEzNjV8Z3g6MTQzZmY2N2U4MGZiNDg2ZQ School Profile]\". ''Francis Lewis High School''. [[New York City Public Schools]]. Retrieved February 3, 2019.</ref>\n| ratio = 30:1<ref name= about/>\n| colors = {{color box|#B01D30}} {{color box|Black}} {{color box|White}} Red, Black, and White\n| rivals = [[Benjamin N. Cardozo High School]],<br>[[Bayside High School (Queens)|Bayside High School]]<ref name= rebound>Moses, Roxanne B. (November 26, 1989). \"Lewis on the Rebound\". ''Newsday''. p. 15.</ref> \n}}\n'''Francis Lewis High School''' ('''FLHS''') is a selective public [[high school]] located in [[Fresh Meadows, Queens|Fresh Meadows]], in the New York City borough of [[Queens]]. It is the most-applied-to public school in New York City with 9,890 applicants in 2016.{{cn|date=March 2020}} Operated by the [[New York City Department of Education]], the school serves students of grades 9{{ndash}}12. The school is named after [[Francis Lewis]], who signed the [[United States Declaration of Independence]] as a representative of New York. \n\nThe school is well-known for its competitive and high-performing academic programs.{{cn|date=March 2020}} Students are admitted to the school either as Zoned applicants or through these programs, whose acceptance rate are below 3% in the 2019 admissions statistics, some being as low as 1%.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe school has a 93% attendance rate, compared to 89% citywide.<ref name= 26q430/> The school's graduation rate is 88% in four years, compared to 76% citywide.<ref name= 26q430/> Of the graduating class, 82% of graduates enrolled in college or other post-secondary program within six months of graduation, compared to 59% citywide.<ref name= 26q430/>\n\n== Student body ==\nAs one of the most selective and applied to public high schools in New York City,<ref>{{Cite web|title=JAM-PACKED QNS. HS IS CITY KIDS' TOP PICK|url=https://nypost.com/2008/10/12/jam-packed-qns-hs-is-city-kids-top-pick/|website=New York Post|date=2008-10-12|accessdate=2015-09-05|first=Angela|last=Montefinise}}</ref> Francis Lewis is also one of the most overcrowded with an enrollment of approximately 4500 students, exceeding the 2,300 capacity by 176 percent.<ref>{{Cite news|title=1 in 3 city schools overcrowded: audit|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/education/1-3-city-schools-overcrowded-audit-article-1.1859717|accessdate=2015-08-21|location=New York|work=Daily News|date=2014-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=At Francis Lewis High School in Queens, Crowding Signals Success|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/29/nyregion/29crowded.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2009-09-28|access-date = 2015-08-21|issn=0362-4331|first=Jennifer|last=Medina|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nTo ease the over enrollment, the City's School Construction Authority announced the school will be getting 500 new seats and state-of-the-art amenities, such as a culinary arts room, a science lab, a greenhouse, and more. <ref>https://qns.com/story/2017/02/21/francis-lewis-high-school-slated-get-500-new-seats-greenhouse/</ref> \n\nFor the 2019\u20132020 academic year, the student body was 56% [[Asian American|Asian]], 22% [[Hispanic American|Hispanic]], 16% [[White American|Caucasian]], and 6% [[African American]].<ref name= 26q430/> Ten percent of the students were learning English as a second language.<ref name= 26q430/> Fourteen percent of the students had special needs.<ref name= 26q430/>\n\nOn March 2016, Francis Lewis had 9,468 applicants applying for a seat in the school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesledger.com/stories/2016/12/francislewis_2016_03_18_q.html|title=Francis Lewis High School has highest applicant number in city|access-date=2016-09-19}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2019\u20132020 school year, Francis Lewis had 4,418 students enrolled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://flhsnews.com/1808/news/francis-lewis-addresses-student-overcrowding-in-stages/|title=Francis Lewis Addresses Student Overcrowding in Stages|last=Caracciolo|first=Thomas|work=FLHS News|access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref> \n\nThe school has an alumni association for graduates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.francislewishs.org/alumni|title=ALUMNI - Francis Lewis High School|website=www.francislewishs.org|access-date=2018-12-04}}</ref>\n\n==Special programs and enrollment==\nEighth and ninth graders applying to Francis Lewis can be admitted through its specialized academic programs which include the following.\n* The [[Jacob K. Javits]] Law Institute for law studies. Students take semesters studying American law, analyzing the court system, and participating in [[mock trial]]s and [[moot court]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://flhslaw.weebly.com/|title=Jacob Javits Law Academy|website=Jacob Javits Law Academy|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref> The program is a three-year program. The school's team won the New York City Moot Court Championships in December 1997.<ref>\"[https://search.proquest.com/docview/368220120/37ACDBD513347F8PQ/1 Francis Lewis High School 1997 Moot Court Champions]\". ''New York Voice''. January 28, 1998. p. 14.</ref> \n* The University Scholars Program, a program which gives its students an accelerated [[humanities]] program including Mythology for freshman year and Philosophy for sophomore year. Students are required to take AP English Language and Composition during junior year, and they have the choice of taking either Ancient Greek or AP English Literature and Composition during senior year. Students are required to take two foreign languages as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.francislewisenglish.com/courses.html|title=Courses|website=Francis Lewis HS English Language Arts|access-date= September 19, 2016}}</ref> The program is a four-year program.\n* The Math and Science Research Program that offers advanced studies of [[math]], [[science]] and [[statistics]]. Students analyze scientific articles, write scientific papers, design and conduct experiments, and participate in science fairs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://flhsscience.wix.com/research|title=scienceresearch2|access-date= September 19, 2016}}</ref> The program is a four-year program.\n* Math Team is a program that allows students to participate in citywide math competitions in addition to required math courses. In April 1999, the senior math team came in first place in the New York State Interscholastic Math Competition.<ref>\"Class Report Card\". ''New York Daily News''. April 13, 1999. p. 2.</ref> \n* The Robotics and Engineering Program offers students education in engineering. Students learn how to construct and program their own robots and compete in citywide competitions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flhsrobotics.com/|title=FLHS Robotics|website=www.flhsrobotics.com|access-date= September 19, 2016}}</ref> \n* The International Relations Program allows students to take an accelerated class in international relations including conflicts and trade. Students take field trips to the United Nations building to analyze relations between different country leaders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.francislewissocialstudies.com/international-relations.html|title=International Relations|website=www.francislewissocialstudies.com|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n* The Computer Science Program allows students to learn how to code on a computer and improve their programming skills.\n\nThe Science Research Program has garnered various [[Siemens Competition]] and [[Intel Science Talent Search]] finalists and winners.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gustafson|first=Anna|url=http://www.timesledger.com/stories/2010/45/fm_siemens_winners_20101104.html|title=Francis Lewis teens win spot on Siemens list|work=TimesLedger|date=November 10, 2010|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nycprivateschoolsblog.com/scholarships-2/2012-semifinalists-and-regional-finalists-announced-in-the-siemens-competition/10/21/2012/|title=2012 semifinalists and Regional Finalists Announced in the Siemens Competition|publisher=Nycprivateschoolsblog.com|date=October 21, 2012|accessdate=October 3, 2013 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005014649/http://nycprivateschoolsblog.com/scholarships-2/2012-semifinalists-and-regional-finalists-announced-in-the-siemens-competition/10/21/2012/|archivedate=October 5, 2013}}</ref> For example, Francis Lewis had three semifinalists in 2010, more than any other high school in New York City.<ref name= excellence/> \n\nIn May 1995, the debate team won the New York City Championship in the annual Lincoln-Douglas debates for the first time in school history.<ref>Fernandes, Victor; Rubin, Roger (May 21, 1995). \"Sports Notebook\". ''Newsday''. p. A47.</ref>\n\nBefore students enter sophomore year, Francis Lewis High School offers students the chance to switch into different programs. Several three-year programs become available, including the following:\n*The Dance Academy allows students to take a dance class in addition to the physical education class. Students learn how to do classical dances and modern dances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gafran.wixsite.com/flhsdanceacademy|title=Flhsdanceacademy|website=flhsdanceacademy|access-date=December 4, 2018}}</ref> As of the 2018\u20132019 school year, students are able to audition to join the academy in their freshman year through orientation in June.\n*School of Design allows students classes to further their art skills.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmason4.wixsite.com/flhsart|title=flhsart|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref>\n*The Graphic Design Academy allows students to pursue interests in [[graphic design]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://acdurga.wixsite.com/flhsgraphics|title=Home|website=FLHSgraphics|language=en|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref>\n*The [[Journalism]] Academy offers students a classes to better understand news writing, reporting, and production. Students learn to produce a news story, learn to photojournalism skills, and broadcast and report through multimedia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://flhsnews.weebly.com/|title=Francis Lewis High School|website=Francis Lewis High School|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n* The Sports and Medicine Academy teaches students necessary skills for working in the medical field. Students study human anatomy, medicines, and medical conditions.\n*The Music Program allows students to further their music skills with different types of instruments and through voice, taking any of the music electives for most of their high school tenure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://francislewismusic.wix.com/home|title=home|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n* The Virtual Enterprise International Academy allows students to learn the basis of designing and selling a product. Student learn marketing techniques, and they use these skills to try to sell a product to real investors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cpower29.wix.com/virtualenterprise|title=virtualenterprise|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Journalism Academy has garnered several awards at The Newsies, a citywide award ceremony for high school journalism.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://flhsnews.com/1963/news/francis-lewis-wins-big-at-the-2017-newsies/|title=Francis Lewis Wins Big at the 2017 Newsies!|last=Lam|first=Crystal|work=FLHS News|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Virtual Enterprise program has garnered honors with top ranking companies in citywide competitions making nationals.\n\n==Academics==\nIn order to give students high school credit and [[Regents Examinations|Regents]] credit, Francis Lewis offers numerous classes such as integrated [[algebra]], [[geometry]], [[trigonometry]]/algebra II, pre-trigonometry, [[English language|English]], [[Environmental science|living environment]]/[[biology]], [[chemistry]], [[physics]], [[earth science]], [[world history|global history]] and [[geography]], [[History of the United States|U.S. History]] and [[Geography of the United States|geography]], [[Government of the United States|U.S. government]] and [[economics]], [[health education|health]], [[forensic science]], [[sports medicine]], [[literature]], [[music appreciation]], [[art]], and [[graphic design]].\n\nAs [[physical education]] classes, Francis Lewis High School offers [[frisbee]], [[racket sports]], [[soccer]], [[basketball]], [[yoga]] and [[dance]], [[walking]], [[weight training|weight training and conditioning]], and [[volleyball]].\n\nThe school offers music electives including [[choir|chorus]], concert choir, honors [[concert band]], [[jazz ensemble]], [[guitar]], [[electronic keyboard|keyboard]], [[marching band]], and [[string orchestra]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://francislewismusic.wixsite.com/home|title=home|website=home|access-date=December 4, 2018}}</ref> Students may take music electives for as long as their high school tenure. [[Music appreciation]] is offered as a one-year class for art/music credit.\n\n=== Language studies ===\nIn keeping with the school's diversity, Francis Lewis High School teaches several foreign languages, including [[Mandarin Chinese|Chinese (Mandarin)]], [[French language|French]], [[Greek language|Greek]] (for the fourth year of the University Scholars program), [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Latin]], and [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. Classes for native speakers in Chinese, Korean, and Spanish are also available for students satisfying the NYCDOE's foreign language requirement. The school previously taught [[Arabic]] and [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], but those classes ended due to declining interest.\n\nEnglish as New Language (ENL) is also available for English learners.\n\n=== Advanced Placement courses ===\nIn 1978, Francis Lewis High School was the first public high school to achieve certification to the [[International Baccalaureate]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ferretronix.com/flewis/#ib_footnote|title=The first IB class at Francis Lewis High School 1975-1978|publisher=Ferretronix.com|date=|accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nTUjMNjNo3EC&pg=RA1-PA140&lpg=RA1-PA140&dq=international+baccalaureate+francis+lewis#v=onepage&q=international%20baccalaureate%20francis%20lewis&f=false|title=Schools Across Frontiers: The Story of the International Baccalaureate and ... - Alexander Duncan Campbell Peterson - Google Boeken|accessdate=October 3, 2013|isbn=9780812695052|year=2003}}</ref>, but stopped offering it in the 1990s<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ferretronix.com/flewis/|title=The first IB class at Francis Lewis High School 1975-1978|website=ferretronix.com|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref>. [[Advanced Placement]] (AP) courses are also available, offering college credit for work done during high school (based on the final test score).  Students may choose the full program to get a full years' college credit, or simply courses of interest (for credit towards single college courses such as math or humanities). Sixty percent of twelfth graders take at least one Advanced Placement exam at any time during high school; of these, 72% earned at least a 3 on at least one Advanced Placement exam.<ref>\"[https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/new-york/districts/new-york-city-public-schools/francis-lewis-high-school-13354/test-scores Francis Lewis High School: Test Scores]\". ''U.S. News & World Report''. Retrieved February 16, 2020.</ref> \n\nStudents can choose from 20 AP courses offered at Francis Lewis, including [[AP Biology|Biology]], [[AP Calculus#AP Calculus AB|Calculus AB]], [[AP Calculus#AP Calculus BC|Calculus BC]], [[AP Capstone|Capstone]] [[AP Chemistry|Chemistry]], [[AP Chinese Language and Culture|Chinese Language and Culture]], [[AP Computer Science|Computer Science A]], [[AP English Language and Composition|English Language and Composition]], [[AP English Literature and Composition|English Literature and Composition]], [[AP Environmental Science|Environmental Science]], [[AP Japanese Language and Culture|Japanese Language and Culture]], [[AP Latin|Latin]], [[AP Macroeconomics|Macroeconomics]], [[AP Microeconomics|Microeconomics]], [[AP Physics 1|Physics 1]], [[AP Physics 2|Physics 2]], [[AP Physics C: Mechanics]], [[AP Psychology|Psychology]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[AP Statistics|Statistics]], [[AP United States Government and Politics|United States Government and Politics]], [[AP United States History|United States History]], and [[AP World History|World History]].\n\n=== College Now! Courses ===\nFrancis Lewis High School offers several courses from College Now, a program offered by the [[City University of New York]] to allow students access City University of New York classes and earn college credit. Classes are offered at [[Queens College, City University of New York|Queens College]] and [[Queensborough Community College]].\n\nStudents can choose up to six classes including [[astronomy]], [[health education|health]] and [[nutrition]], [[criminal justice]]/[[sociology]], [[Computers|computers in modern society]], [[English language|English]], and [[calculus|pre-calculus]].\n\n==Junior Reserve Officers' Training Corps==\nIn 1994, the US Army [[Junior Reserve Officers' Training Corps]] (JROTC) program was established in the school.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/20/education/20oneducation.html?pagewanted=all&_r=1|work=The New York Times|first=Michael|last=Winerip|title=At High School in Queens, an R.O.T.C. Program's Enduring Influence|date=June 19, 2011|url-access=limited}}</ref> It is the largest in the nation, with more than 1,000 cadets of the 1,725 high school chapters in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/162143/queens-junior-rotc-cadets-put-discipline-on-display |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130216141403/http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/162143/queens-junior-rotc-cadets-put-discipline-on-display |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 16, 2013|title=Queens Junior ROTC Cadets Put Discipline On Display|publisher=NY1|date=May 30, 2012|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref> The battalion is an honor unit with distinction, and it is considered one of the best and well-known US Army JROTC units in the nation.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.qchron.com/editions/north/francis-lewis-hs-jrotc-is-perfection/article_82d2edf1-10aa-58b6-a797-99ecb0f63671.html|title=Francis Lewis HS JROTC is perfection - Queens Chronicle: North/Northeast Queens News|publisher=Qchron.com|date=February 13, 2013|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref> It had a 100% graduation rate from 1992 to 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Bigger is better at 4,000-student strong Francis Lewis High School in Queens|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/education/bigger-better-4-000-student-strong-francis-lewis-high-school-queens-article-1.1483733|accessdate=August 21, 2015|location=New York|work=Daily News|date=October 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThere are six JROTC teams, namely Academic, Choir, Drum Corps, Honor Guard, and Drill Team (Armed and Unarmed). Two teams compete, Academic and Drill Team (Unarmed \u2013 Patriot Pride, Armed \u2013 Patriot Guard). Francis Lewis High School used to have a competing Raiders team (female \u2013 Patriot Strength, male \u2013 Patriot Force).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flhspatriotbattalion.com/index.html|title=FLHS PATRIOT BATTALION JROTC - Francis Lewis Patriot Battalion|publisher=Flhspatriotbattalion.com|date=|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref> In 2018 allegations of hazing (involving sexual and physical assault) from the male Raiders team were made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/11/03/cadet-reveals-junior-rotc-units-disturbing-hazing-ritual/|title=I was scorched with hot iron and sexually assaulted: JROTC cadet|last=Edelman|first=Susan|last2=Dorn|first2=Sara|date=November 3, 2018|website=New York Post|access-date=December 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Patriot Guard were national champions in 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenationals.net/dt-past_champs.htm|title=NHSDTC Masters Level Past Champions - 1987 through the present|work=Sports Network International|date=|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref> 2009\u20132011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenationals.net/dt-results-2009M.pdf|title=National High School Drill Team Championships : Masters Level Event Standings|publisher=Thenationals.net|accessdate=February 21, 2015}}</ref> and placed second in 2012. The Patriot Pride came in second in 2006, 2008 and 2009 and first in 2010 and 2013 National Championships in [[Daytona, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/video/#!/on-air/as-seen-on/National-Drill-Competition-Champions-Winners/208752271|title=Video|publisher=NBC New York|date=September 26, 2013|accessdate=October 3, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402032823/http://www.nbcnewyork.com/video/#!/on-air/as-seen-on/National-Drill-Competition-Champions-Winners/208752271|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe female Raiders were national champions for four consecutive years from 2009 to 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenationals.net/raider-results-female-all.pdf|title=2014 Raider Nationals Overall Score Report Female Division|work=Sports Network International|accessdate=February 21, 2015}}</ref> The male Raiders' most recent first-place title was in 2011, having come in third in the 2012 Nationals and second in the 2013 Nationals.<ref>Tolliver, Rachael (November 4, 2013). \"[http://www.army.mil/article/114427/Campbell__Adairsville__join_Smith_Cotton_as_2013_National_Raider_champs/ Campbell, Adairsville, join Smith-Cotton as 2013 National Raider champs]\". ''United States Army''.</ref>\n\nThe Academic team was awarded first place at the 2015 Leadership Bowl Nationals.<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20150811075303/http://collegeoptionsfoundation.net/2015-jlab-results/ 2015 JROTC Army Leadership Finals]\". ''College Options Foundation''. Archived from [http://collegeoptionsfoundation.net/2015-jlab-results/ the original] on August 11, 2015.</ref> The Academic team placed as finalists in the JROTC Leadership Academic Bowl in 2011, 2012, and 2013.\n\nIn 2010, Francis Lewis had more cadets in the [[United States Military Academy]] than any other public high school in the United States.<ref name= excellence>Ali Shama, Musa (December 21, 2010). \"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/575633716/ Ranking Obscures Fact We Are Committed to Excellence]\". ''Daily News'' (New York, New York). p. 6.</ref> \n\nThe JROTC Program may be chosen as an elective that a student may have in addition to their program. Students enrolled in JROTC are required to partake in weekly physical training, conduct school and community service, wear the Army Service Uniform once a weak, as well as take courses on leadership, nutrition, personal finance, civics, and government.\n\n==Extracurricular Activities==\n\n=== Athletics ===\nFrancis Lewis High School's athletic teams compete in the [[PSAL]]. Student-athletes compete in [[baseball]], [[basketball]], [[bowling]], [[cheerleading]], [[cross country running|cross country]], [[fencing]], [[golf]], [[American handball|handball]], [[soccer]], [[softball]], [[swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[tennis]], [[track and field|track]], [[volleyball]], and [[wrestling]]<ref name= about/>\n\nFrancis Lewis High School's cross country team team won the PSAL championship in 1968.<ref name= rebound/>\n\nThe school's soccer team won the PSAL championship in 1969.<ref name= rebound/>\n\nThe softball team won the PSAL championship in 1975.<ref name= rebound/>\n\nFrancis Lewis High School's girls basketball team won the PSAL Championship in March 1979.<ref name= wagner>{{cite web|title=Lewis Tops Wagner for Girls' Title|website=The New York Times|date=March 11, 1979|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/03/11/archives/lewis-tops-wagner-for-girls-title.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=S7|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The team was undefeated in the regular season that year.<ref name= wagner/>\n\nFrancis Lewis has had a [[cricket]] team since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Michael|title=Uprooted to Brooklyn, and Nourished by Cricket|website=The New York Times|date=October 16, 2016|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/16/sports/uprooted-to-brooklyn-and-nourished-by-cricket.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=SP1|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nThe school's male and female [[American handball]] team won the PSAL championship in the 2018\u20132019 season.\n\nDuring the 1994\u20131995 season, Francis Lewis High School's boys basketball team was undefeated in its division, the first time it had done so since the 1980\u20131981 season.<ref>\"Queens Sports Notebook\". ''Newsday''. March 19, 1995. p. A45.</ref> The team won the PSAL B Championship in March 1995.<ref>\"High School Basketball Previews\". ''Newsday''. December 3, 1995. p. 22.</ref><ref>\"Francis Lewis Captures B Title\". ''Newsday''. March 19, 1995. p. 16.</ref> The team advanced to the New York State Federation Basketball Class A championship in [[Glens Falls]]. It lost to [[Mount Saint Michael Academy]] of the Bronx, knocking it out of the state tournament.<ref>\"Results Plus\". ''The New York Times''. March 26, 1995. p. 813.</ref>\n\nFrancis Lewis High School's athletic field is named for [[Margaret Lambert]], a [[History of the Jews in Germany|German Jewish]] [[track and field]] athlete. During the 1930s, [[Nazi Germany|German]] athletic teams were closed to Jewish athletes, and the [[United States Olympic Committee|United States]] was considering to boycott the [[1936 Summer Olympics|1936 Summer Olympics in Berlin]] in protest of Germany's [[anti-Semitism]]. [[Adolf Hitler]] wanted to avoid a boycott, so he threatened her father to have her train for Germany in order to convince the world that Germany welcomed Jewish athletes to its team if they qualified. She tied the German high jump record at the national trials in [[Stuttgart]], and she trained at the Olympic training camp in [[Ettlingen]].<ref>Jacobson, Steve (May 3, 2015). \"Barred by the Nazis\". ''Newsday''. p. A10.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Margaret Bergmann Lambert, Jewish Athlete Excluded From Berlin Olympics, Dies at 103|website=The New York Times|date=July 25, 2017|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/25/sports/olympics/margaret-bergmann-lambert-dead-barred-from-1936-olympics.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n=== Clubs ===\nFrancis Lewis offers a varying number of clubs approved by the Student Organization (SO). Students may fill out a club registration forms from the SO Office by the late September deadline.\n\nThe 2019\u20132020 school year offers clubs<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=sites&srcid=ZGVmYXVsdGRvbWFpbnxmbGhzMTEzNjV8Z3g6NzQ3NDU3MTY4YTg0ZDJjOA|title=FLHS Clubs 2019.pdf|website=docs.google.com|access-date=November 16, 2019 }}</ref> including [https://nyc.cce.cornell.edu/4-h/ 4H Cornell], [[American Red Cross]] Club, Anime Club, Art Club, Asian Food Culture Club, Baseball Club, [[Calligraphy]] Club, Chess Club, Chinese Chess Club, Chinese Club, Chinese Origami Club, Christian Seekers Fellowship, Creative Writing Club, Cultural Dance Club, Current Events Club, [https://www.deca.org DECA], DIY Club, Double Up (Mentor) Club, [[Dungeons & Dragons|Dungeons and Dragons]], Endangered Species Club, Environmental Club, Fashion Club, Film Club, Fitness Club, Gardening Club, Girls Fall Conditioning, [[Girls Who Code|Girls Who Code (GWC)]], [https://www.glamourgals.org Glamour Gals], [https://thegreenteam.org Green Team], [[Harry Potter]] Club, Hellenic Club, History Club, HS Investment Club (HSIC), Humans of Francis Lewis Magazine, Inspiring Inclusive Leaders, International Education Club, ISS Club, Japanese Club, Jewish Student Union, Journalism Club (FLHS News), [[Junior State of America]] (JSA), [[K-pop]] and Urban Dance Club (KUD), [[Key Club]], Korean Club, [[Korean drum|Korean Drum]] Club, [[Kung Fu]] Club, [[LGBTQ+]] Club, Math Club, Media Production Club, Medical Explorers Club, [[Mindfulness]] + [[Yoga]] Club, [[Model United Nations]], Modern Music Club, Muslim Student Association Club, [[My Brother's Keeper Challenge|My Brother's Keeper]], [https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/signature-programs/no-place-for-hate No Place for Hate], Nu Gamma Psi (male and female [[Stepping (African-American)|step]] teams), One Love Counseling Club, Programmers Initiative Club (PI), Public Speaking for Beginners, Puzzle Club, Science Olympiads, Sikh Student Association, Spanish Club, Students for Climate Action Now, [[Taekwondo]] Club, [[Ted Talk|TED Talk]] Club, Teen Community Service (TCS), Travelers Club, Trivia Club, Ultimate Unity Dance Club, [[UNICEF]], Video Game Club, Visual Arts Club, Women's Empowerment Club, and Workout Club.\n\nFormer clubs include 3D Model Club (2017\u20132018), [[American Civil Liberties Union|ACLU]] (2017\u20132018) African American Club (2018\u20132019), Ancient History Club (2018\u20132019), Animal Humane Society (2017\u20132018), Astronomy Club (2016\u20132017), [https://medschool.ucla.edu/body.cfm?id=1158&action=detail&ref=602 Big Sib-Little Sib] (2017\u20132018), Books for Baddies (2018\u20132019), Bookworms (2017\u20132018), Caribbean Club (2017\u20132018), Comedy Club (2018\u20132019), Comic Book Club (2016\u20132017), Conscious Club (2018\u20132019), Conservation Club (2017\u20132018), Dancer Dynasty Club (2018\u20132019), Debate Club (2018\u20132019), eSport Club (2018\u20132019), Filipino Club, FLNBC (2015\u20132016), Food Appreciation Club (2017\u20132018), Game Club (2017\u20132018), Gamer's Connect (2018\u20132019), Game Development and Design Club (2018\u20132019), Glee Club (2015\u20132018), Global Advocates Club (2017\u20132019), Interconnected Club (2017\u20132018), International Club (2017\u20132018), International Pop Club (2017\u20132018), [[Latin]] Club (2017\u20132018), Latinos Unidos (2018\u20132019), Make-Up Club (2017\u20132018), Mental Health Club (2018\u20132019), Music Cover Club (2018\u20132019), Music Creation (2018\u20132019), One Neutron Extra (ONE, 2016\u20132017), [https://operationcareinternational.org Operation CARE Team] (2017\u20132019), Philosophy Club (2018\u20132019), Photography Club, Pre-Med Club, Social Activist Club (2018\u20132019), SPEAK (2018\u20132019), STEMP Club (2018\u20132019), Video Game Club (2017\u20132018), and Youth Civic Engagement (YCE, 2018\u20132019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BaM0rkKgUTQ/|title=Francis Lewis Class Of 2018! on Instagram: \"Club list is out! \ud83d\udc4c\ud83c\udffc\ud83d\udc4c\ud83c\udffc\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=sites&srcid=ZGVmYXVsdGRvbWFpbnxmbGhzMTEzNjV8Z3g6MjEwODExOWI2NzBjNTY4MQ|title=FLHS Club Charters 2018\u20132019.pdf|website=docs.google.com|access-date=November 16, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1952, the Northeast Queens Council for Schools advocated for a northeast Queens high school because of severe overcrowding at [[Bayside High School (Queens)|Bayside High School]], [[Flushing High School]], [[Andrew Jackson High School (Queens)|Andrew Jackson High School]], and [[Jamaica High School]].<ref name= sotw>Morales, Tina (March 18, 1990). \"School of the Week: Francis Lewis H.S.\" ''Newsday''.</ref>\n\nIn December 1955, the [[New York City Board of Education]] approved the building of a new high school, called Northeast Queens High School, near the intersection of [[Utopia Parkway (Queens)|Utopia Parkway]] and 59th Avenue, with a capacity of 3,000 students.<ref name= 25schools>{{cite web|title=25 Schools in City Planned for 1956|website=The New York Times|date=December 12, 1955|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/12/12/archives/25-schools-in-city-planned-for-1956-board-also-lists-4-additions.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=1|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The city bought 11 acres of land, and the City Planning Commission agreed that the high school was needed, but the Commission did not approve the allocation of money to build the school in the capital budget.<ref name= sotw/><ref name= mayorasks>{{cite web|title=Mayor Asks Schools: Bids Plan Board Provide One in Queens, One in Brooklyn|website=The New York Times|date=October 8, 1956|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/10/08/archives/mayor-asks-schools-bids-plan-board-provide-one-in-queens-one-in.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=29|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name= beg>{{cite web|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|title=Parents Beg City for More Schools: Hundreds Flock to Budget Hearings, Mostly From Brooklyn and Queens|website=The New York Times|date=October 10, 1956|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/10/10/archives/parents-beg-city-for-more-schools-hundreds-flock-to-budget-hearings.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=41|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1956, the city approved the hiring of the firm of [[Eggers & Higgins]] to be the architect of the building, although the budget to actually build the high school was not yet approved.<ref name= franklin>\"Ben Franklin To Open As Co-ed High School\". ''New York Amsterdam News''. September 10, 1960. p. 6.</ref><ref name= beg/>\n\nIn October 1956, [[Mayor of New York City|Mayor]] [[Robert F. Wagner Jr.]] wrote a letter to the City Planning Commission asking it to include the construction of Northeast Queens High School in its capital budget.<ref name= mayorasks/> The construction was included in the capital budget in 1957.<ref>\"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/455688307/ School Council to Map Goals for Next Year]\". ''Daily News'' (New York, New York). December 2, 1956. p. 35B.</ref> \n\nIn March 1958, the Board of Education approved a contract to build the high school.<ref name=\"boardvotes\">{{cite web|title=Board Votes a New Junior High School As Albany Moves to Abolish Them Here|website=The New York Times|date=March 21, 1958|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/03/21/archives/board-votes-a-new-junior-high-school-as-albany-moves-to-abolish.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=11|url-access=subscription}}</ref> A $4,229,000 contract was awarded to the lowest bidder, Caristo Construction Company.<ref name= boardvotes/> The ground-breaking happened that same year. A group of parents tried to have an indoor swimming pool built in the high school, but they were not successful.<ref>\"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/418934421/ Renew Drive for HS Pool]\". ''New York Daily News''. November 5, 1959. p. 7.</ref> The high school ended up costing $6,100,000 to build.<ref name= franklin/>\n\nFrancis Lewis High School opened on September 13, 1960.<ref name= topschool>\"[https://search.proquest.com/docview/225502540/610527BA513C44D6PQ/1 Segregation Still A Top School Problem]\". ''New York Amsterdam News''. September 10, 1960. p. 17.</ref> The school was named after [[Francis Lewis]], a resident of [[Whitestone, Queens|Whitestone]] who signed the [[United States Declaration of Independence]].<ref name= sotw/> Vincent McGarrett was the first principal.<ref name= newcollege/> Herman Wolf was the first basketball coach.<ref>Hurley, Ed (March 20, 1960). \"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/420678342/ Wolf at Door of Lewis HS on Rebound]\". ''New York Daily News''. p. 49.</ref> [[Queensborough Community College]] held some of its classes at Francis Lewis High School that year because its own campus was still under construction.<ref name= newcollege>\"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/459102744/ New College Borrows Rms. For Sept. Bow]\". ''New York Daily News''. July 24, 1960. p. 19.</ref> \n\nFrancis Lewis High School was built for a capacity of 2,700 students.<ref name= topschool/> The school was overcrowded as of the 1962\u20131963 school year.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hechinger|first=Fred M.|title=Schools Reopen; Rolls Up 19,618|website=The New York Times|date=September 11, 1962|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/09/11/archives/schools-reopen-rolls-up-19618-crowding-still-widespread-hereparents.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=1|url-access=subscription}}</ref> [[Benjamin N. Cardozo High School|Cardozo High School]] was built in 1967 in order to relieve overcrowding at Francis Lewis.<ref>\"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/576187420/ Future Public Hearings Set]\". ''The Williamsburg Times'' (Brooklyn, New York). April 12, 1963. p. 6.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/460025817/ Golf Course Tract]\". ''New York Daily News''. August 18, 1963. p. 46.</ref> \n\nIn 1965, [[Queensborough Community College]] held some of its evening classes at Francis Lewis High School due to overcrowding at Queensborough.<ref>{{cite web|title=Buses to be Used as Classrooms; Students at Queensborough College Forced Into Mobile Quarters for a Week|website=The New York Times|date=October 23, 1965|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/10/23/archives/buses-to-be-used-for-classrooms-students-at-queensborough-college.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=33|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn 1978, Francis Lewis High School graduated [[International Baccalaureate]] diploma students, the first public high school in the United States to do so.<ref>Isger, Sonja (September 6, 2015). \"How IB program came to U.S.: West Palm retiree says bad weather helped\". ''TCA Regional News'' (Chicago, Illinois).</ref> It terminated in the 1990s.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Mashama Bailey]] - chef\n* [[Steve Dorff]] (1968) \u2013 composer/music producer{{citation needed|reason=lacks a reliable source confirming attendance|date=February 2019}}\n* [[Rob Echeverria]]<ref>Slattery, Denis (September 28, 2014). \"Hardcore boro Band invents 'Sick' new meaning for Bronx\". ''New York Daily News''. p. 39.</ref> \u2013 American musician who has worked as the guitarist of [[Biohazard (band)|Biohazard]], [[Helmet (band)|Helmet]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Billboard |date=21 August 1999 |page=82}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Phillips |first1=William |title=Encyclopedia of Heavy Metal Music}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rotondi |first1=James |title=Dropped D-Day: Helmet Levels Metaldom |url=http://www.bluecricket.com/helmet/interviews/gp892.html |accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Suarez |first1=Gary |title=Why Helmet decided to take an album that wasn't a best-seller on tour, two decades later |url=https://www.indyweek.com/indyweek/why-helmet-decided-to-take-an-album-that-wasnt-a-best-seller-on-tour-two-decades-later/Content?oid=4344695 |accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=REYES-KULKARNI |first1=SABY |title=HOW HELMET BROADENED THEIR SOUND ON 'BETTY' |url=http://diffuser.fm/21-years-ago-helmet-release-betty/ |website=[[Townsquare Media|Diffuser]] |accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref> Rest in Pieces, and [[Straight Ahead (band)|Straight Ahead]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alva |first1=Freddy |title=Rob Echeverria (Straight Ahead, Rest in Pieces, Biohazard, Helmet) |url=http://www.noecho.net/interviews/rob-echeverria-straight-ahead-rest-in-pieces-biohazard-helmet |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=BUKSZPAN |first1=DANIEL |title=The Z Review Playlist: CBGB's 1984-1986 by Musician Rob Echeverria |url=https://thezreview.com/2018/06/29/the-z-review-playlist-cbgbs-1984-1986-by-musician-rob-echeverria/ |accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Rick Elice]] (1973) \u2013 actor, writer{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n* [[David Gordon]] (2006) \u2013 theater critic, President of the Outer Critics Circle\n* [[Steve Greenberg (record producer)|Steve Greenberg]] (1978) \u2013 record producer, former President of Columbia Records{{citation needed|reason=lacks a reliable source confirming attendance|date=February 2019}}\n* [[Sebasti\u00e1n Guenzatti]] \u2013  [[association football|soccer]] player for the [[Tampa Bay Rowdies]] of the [[United Soccer League]]<ref>Gavin, Mike (September 14, 2013). \"Guenzatti enjoying his role in history\". ''Newsday''. September 14, 2013. p. A30.</ref>\n* [[Peter Guttman (photographer)|Peter Guttman]] (1972) \u2013 travel journalist, lecturer, and author{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n* [[Heejun Han]] (2007) \u2013 finalist on [[American Idol]], [[American Idol (season 11)|season 11]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/heejun-han-false-idol-article-1.1027844|title='American Idol' star in the making: NYC's Heejun Han makes final 24|date=February 23, 2012|accessdate=March 4, 2012|location=New York|work=Daily News}}</ref>\n* [[Albie Hecht]] \u2013 former president of [[Nickelodeon]], founder of [[Spike TV]]<ref>Hayes, Dade (Dec 1 2008). \"Can TV titan work wonders on Web? Hecht, yeah\". ''Variety'' (Los Angeles, California). Vol. 413. Iss. 3. p. 26.</ref> \n* [[Mike Jorgensen]] (1966) \u2013 drafted by the [[New York Mets]];<ref>{{cite web|last=Durso|first=Joseph|title=Team Is Confident After Successful Spring Training|website=The New York Times|date=April 4, 1970|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/04/04/archives/team-is-confident-after-successful-spring-training.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=47|url-access=subscription}}</ref> played for the New York Mets, [[Montreal Expos]], [[Oakland Athletics]], [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], [[Atlanta Braves]], and [[St. Louis Cardinals]]; managed the Cardinals<ref>{{cite web|title=Mets Sign Dyer and Two Rookies: Matlack and Jorgensen Lift Total Under Contract to 18|website=The New York Times|date=January 1, 1970|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/01/archives/mets-sign-dyer-and-two-rookies-matlack-and-jorgensen-lift-total.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=S2|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n* [[Paul Joskow]] \u2014 American economist and professor<ref>Joskow, Paul L. (September 29, 2009). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/03/opinion/l03school.html Boom Times at Francis Lewis High]\". ''The New York Times''.</ref>\n* [[Peter Marino]] \u2013 American [[architect]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Hamilton|first=William L.|title=The Palace Maker|website=The New York Times|date=February 5, 2004|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/05/garden/the-palace-maker.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=F1|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n* [[Mark Miloscia]] \u2013 [[Washington State Senator]]<ref>\"Education Funding Leads Statewide Issues\". ''Spokesman Review'' (Spokane, Washington). October 11, 2016. p. T5.</ref> \n* [[Jonathan Pontell]] \u2013  television director, producer, and editor{{citation needed|reason=lacks a reliable source confirming attendance|date=February 2019}}\n* [[Craig Setari]] \u2013 American musician and former competitive boxer who is currently active as the bass player in [[Sick of It All]] \u2013 [[hardcore punk]] band<ref>{{cite web |last1=Slattery |first1=Denis |title=New York hardcore legends invents 'Sick' new meaning for Bronx |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/queens/sick-ready-bronx-article-1.1954445 |website=nydailynews.com |accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Ron Shandler]] (1974) \u2013 national baseball analyst, author of ''Baseball Forecaster'', founder of BaseballHQ.com, columnist for [[USA Today]]{{citation needed|reason=lacks a reliable source confirming attendance|date=February 2019}}\n* [[Dennis Walcott]] \u2013 former chancellor of the [[New York City Department of Education]], president and CEO of the [[Queens Borough Public Library]] system<ref>Enis, Matt; Peet, Lisa (March 15, 2016). \"Dennis Walcott Named CEO of Queens Library\". ''Library Journal'' (New York). Vol. 141, Iss. 5.</ref>\n* [[Chris Welty]] (1981) \u2013 computer scientist{{citation needed|reason=lacks a reliable source confirming attendance|date=February 2019}}\n* [[Airis Jin(\u91d1\u5b50\u6db5)]] (1999) \u2013 singer\n\n==In fiction==\n* In ''[[The Yards]]'', [[Joaquin Phoenix]] plays a character who graduated from Francis Lewis High School.<ref name=gray>Hirschon, Nicholas (December 23, 2011). \"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/583044098/ James Gray's Films Explore Underdog Living in Qns.]\" ''Daily News'' (New York, New York). p. p. 35.</ref> The film's director, [[James Gray (director)|James Gray]], grew up in [[Flushing, Queens|Flushing]].<ref name=gray/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.francislewishs.org}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/20/education/20oneducation.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all At High School in Queens, R.O.T.C.\u2019s Enduring Influence]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/29/nyregion/29crowded.html At School in Queens, Success Draws Crowd - New York Times]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150402032823/http://www.nbcnewyork.com/video/#!/on-air/as-seen-on/National-Drill-Competition-Champions-Winners/208752271 National Drill Competition- Champions Interview- NBC]\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in Queens, New York]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n| name               = Francis Lewis High School\n| logo               = flhslogo.jpg\n| logo_alt           = Logo of Francis Lewis High School\n| image              = Francis Lewis High School.jpg\n| alt                = Front entrance to Francis Lewis High School\n| image_size      