h School]\". ''High School CEED Code Search''. The State University of New York. Retrieved February 3, 2019.</ref>\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|44|27|N|73|47|38|W|region:US-NY|display=inline,title}}\n| students = 4,557<ref name= 26q430>\"[https://tools.nycenet.edu/snapshot/2018/26Q430/HS/ Francis Lewis High School]\". ''2017-18 School Quality Snapshot''. New York City Department of Education. Retrieved February 18, 2019.</ref>\n| faculty = 210<ref name= about>\"[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=sites&srcid=ZGVmYXVsdGRvbWFpbnxmbGhzMTEzNjV8Z3g6MTQzZmY2N2U4MGZiNDg2ZQ School Profile]\". ''Francis Lewis High School''. [[New York City Public Schools]]. Retrieved February 3, 2019.</ref>\n| ratio = 30:1<ref name= about/>\n| colors = {{color box|#B01D30}} {{color box|Black}} {{color box|White}} Red, Black, and White\n| rivals = [[Benjamin N. Cardozo High School]],<br>[[Bayside High School (Queens)|Bayside High School]]<ref name= rebound>Moses, Roxanne B. (November 26, 1989). \"Lewis on the Rebound\". ''Newsday''. p. 15.</ref> \n}}\n'''Francis Lewis High School''' ('''FLHS''') is a selective public [[high school]] located in [[Fresh Meadows, Queens|Fresh Meadows]], in the New York City borough of [[Queens]]. It is the most-applied-to public school in New York City with 9,890 applicants in 2016.{{cn|date=March 2020}} Operated by the [[New York City Department of Education]], the school serves students of grades 9{{ndash}}12. The school is named after [[Francis Lewis]], who signed the [[United States Declaration of Independence]] as a representative of New York. \n\nThe school is well-known for its competitive and high-performing academic programs.{{cn|date=March 2020}} Students are admitted to the school either as Zoned applicants or through these programs, whose acceptance rate are below 3% in the 2019 admissions statistics, some being as low as 1%.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe school has a 93% attendance rate, compared to 89% citywide.<ref name= 26q430/> The school's graduation rate is 88% in four years, compared to 76% citywide.<ref name= 26q430/> Of the graduating class, 82% of graduates enrolled in college or other post-secondary program within six months of graduation, compared to 59% citywide.<ref name= 26q430/>\n\n== Student body ==\nAs one of the most selective and applied to public high schools in New York City,<ref>{{Cite web|title=JAM-PACKED QNS. HS IS CITY KIDS' TOP PICK|url=https://nypost.com/2008/10/12/jam-packed-qns-hs-is-city-kids-top-pick/|website=New York Post|date=2008-10-12|accessdate=2015-09-05|first=Angela|last=Montefinise}}</ref> Francis Lewis is also one of the most overcrowded with an enrollment of approximately 4500 students, exceeding the 2,300 capacity by 176 percent.<ref>{{Cite news|title=1 in 3 city schools overcrowded: audit|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/education/1-3-city-schools-overcrowded-audit-article-1.1859717|accessdate=2015-08-21|location=New York|work=Daily News|date=2014-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=At Francis Lewis High School in Queens, Crowding Signals Success|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/29/nyregion/29crowded.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2009-09-28|access-date = 2015-08-21|issn=0362-4331|first=Jennifer|last=Medina|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nTo ease the over enrollment, the City's School Construction Authority announced the school will be getting 500 new seats and state-of-the-art amenities, such as a culinary arts room, a science lab, a greenhouse, and more. <ref>https://qns.com/story/2017/02/21/francis-lewis-high-school-slated-get-500-new-seats-greenhouse/</ref> \n\nFor the 2019\u20132020 academic year, the student body was 56% [[Asian American|Asian]], 22% [[Hispanic American|Hispanic]], 16% [[White American|Caucasian]], and 6% [[African American]].<ref name= 26q430/> Ten percent of the students were learning English as a second language.<ref name= 26q430/> Fourteen percent of the students had special needs.<ref name= 26q430/>\n\nOn March 2016, Francis Lewis had 9,468 applicants applying for a seat in the school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesledger.com/stories/2016/12/francislewis_2016_03_18_q.html|title=Francis Lewis High School has highest applicant number in city|access-date=2016-09-19}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2019\u20132020 school year, Francis Lewis had 4,418 students enrolled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://flhsnews.com/1808/news/francis-lewis-addresses-student-overcrowding-in-stages/|title=Francis Lewis Addresses Student Overcrowding in Stages|last=Caracciolo|first=Thomas|work=FLHS News|access-date=2018-01-12}}</ref> \n\nThe school has an alumni association for graduates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.francislewishs.org/alumni|title=ALUMNI - Francis Lewis High School|website=www.francislewishs.org|access-date=2018-12-04}}</ref>\n\n==Special programs and enrollment==\nEighth and ninth graders applying to Francis Lewis can be admitted through its specialized academic programs which include the following.\n* The [[Jacob K. Javits]] Law Institute for law studies. Students take semesters studying American law, analyzing the court system, and participating in [[mock trial]]s and [[moot court]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://flhslaw.weebly.com/|title=Jacob Javits Law Academy|website=Jacob Javits Law Academy|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref> The program is a three-year program. The school's team won the New York City Moot Court Championships in December 1997.<ref>\"[https://search.proquest.com/docview/368220120/37ACDBD513347F8PQ/1 Francis Lewis High School 1997 Moot Court Champions]\". ''New York Voice''. January 28, 1998. p. 14.</ref> \n* The University Scholars Program, a program which gives its students an accelerated [[humanities]] program including Mythology for freshman year and Philosophy for sophomore year. Students are required to take AP English Language and Composition during junior year, and they have the choice of taking either Ancient Greek or AP English Literature and Composition during senior year. Students are required to take two foreign languages as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.francislewisenglish.com/courses.html|title=Courses|website=Francis Lewis HS English Language Arts|access-date= September 19, 2016}}</ref> The program is a four-year program.\n* The Math and Science Research Program that offers advanced studies of [[math]], [[science]] and [[statistics]]. Students analyze scientific articles, write scientific papers, design and conduct experiments, and participate in science fairs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://flhsscience.wix.com/research|title=scienceresearch2|access-date= September 19, 2016}}</ref> The program is a four-year program.\n* Math Team is a program that allows students to participate in citywide math competitions in addition to required math courses. In April 1999, the senior math team came in first place in the New York State Interscholastic Math Competition.<ref>\"Class Report Card\". ''New York Daily News''. April 13, 1999. p. 2.</ref> \n* The Robotics and Engineering Program offers students education in engineering. Students learn how to construct and program their own robots and compete in citywide competitions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flhsrobotics.com/|title=FLHS Robotics|website=www.flhsrobotics.com|access-date= September 19, 2016}}</ref> \n* The International Relations Program allows students to take an accelerated class in international relations including conflicts and trade. Students take field trips to the United Nations building to analyze relations between different country leaders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.francislewissocialstudies.com/international-relations.html|title=International Relations|website=www.francislewissocialstudies.com|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n* The Computer Science Program allows students to learn how to code on a computer and improve their programming skills.\n\nThe Science Research Program has garnered various [[Siemens Competition]] and [[Intel Science Talent Search]] finalists and winners.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gustafson|first=Anna|url=http://www.timesledger.com/stories/2010/45/fm_siemens_winners_20101104.html|title=Francis Lewis teens win spot on Siemens list|work=TimesLedger|date=November 10, 2010|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nycprivateschoolsblog.com/scholarships-2/2012-semifinalists-and-regional-finalists-announced-in-the-siemens-competition/10/21/2012/|title=2012 semifinalists and Regional Finalists Announced in the Siemens Competition|publisher=Nycprivateschoolsblog.com|date=October 21, 2012|accessdate=October 3, 2013 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005014649/http://nycprivateschoolsblog.com/scholarships-2/2012-semifinalists-and-regional-finalists-announced-in-the-siemens-competition/10/21/2012/|archivedate=October 5, 2013}}</ref> For example, Francis Lewis had three semifinalists in 2010, more than any other high school in New York City.<ref name= excellence/> \n\nIn May 1995, the debate team won the New York City Championship in the annual Lincoln-Douglas debates for the first time in school history.<ref>Fernandes, Victor; Rubin, Roger (May 21, 1995). \"Sports Notebook\". ''Newsday''. p. A47.</ref>\n\nBefore students enter sophomore year, Francis Lewis High School offers students the chance to switch into different programs. Several three-year programs become available, including the following:\n*The Dance Academy allows students to take a dance class in addition to the physical education class. Students learn how to do classical dances and modern dances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gafran.wixsite.com/flhsdanceacademy|title=Flhsdanceacademy|website=flhsdanceacademy|access-date=December 4, 2018}}</ref> As of the 2018\u20132019 school year, students are able to audition to join the academy in their freshman year through orientation in June.\n*School of Design allows students classes to further their art skills.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmason4.wixsite.com/flhsart|title=flhsart|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref>\n*The Graphic Design Academy allows students to pursue interests in [[graphic design]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://acdurga.wixsite.com/flhsgraphics|title=Home|website=FLHSgraphics|language=en|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref>\n*The [[Journalism]] Academy offers students a classes to better understand news writing, reporting, and production. Students learn to produce a news story, learn to photojournalism skills, and broadcast and report through multimedia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://flhsnews.weebly.com/|title=Francis Lewis High School|website=Francis Lewis High School|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n* The Sports and Medicine Academy teaches students necessary skills for working in the medical field. Students study human anatomy, medicines, and medical conditions.\n*The Music Program allows students to further their music skills with different types of instruments and through voice, taking any of the music electives for most of their high school tenure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://francislewismusic.wix.com/home|title=home|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n* The Virtual Enterprise International Academy allows students to learn the basis of designing and selling a product. Student learn marketing techniques, and they use these skills to try to sell a product to real investors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cpower29.wix.com/virtualenterprise|title=virtualenterprise|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Journalism Academy has garnered several awards at The Newsies, a citywide award ceremony for high school journalism.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://flhsnews.com/1963/news/francis-lewis-wins-big-at-the-2017-newsies/|title=Francis Lewis Wins Big at the 2017 Newsies!|last=Lam|first=Crystal|work=FLHS News|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Virtual Enterprise program has garnered honors with top ranking companies in citywide competitions making nationals.\n\n==Academics==\nIn order to give students high school credit and [[Regents Examinations|Regents]] credit, Francis Lewis offers numerous classes such as integrated [[algebra]], [[geometry]], [[trigonometry]]/algebra II, pre-trigonometry, [[English language|English]], [[Environmental science|living environment]]/[[biology]], [[chemistry]], [[physics]], [[earth science]], [[world history|global history]] and [[geography]], [[History of the United States|U.S. History]] and [[Geography of the United States|geography]], [[Government of the United States|U.S. government]] and [[economics]], [[health education|health]], [[forensic science]], [[sports medicine]], [[literature]], [[music appreciation]], [[art]], and [[graphic design]].\n\nAs [[physical education]] classes, Francis Lewis High School offers [[frisbee]], [[racket sports]], [[soccer]], [[basketball]], [[yoga]] and [[dance]], [[walking]], [[weight training|weight training and conditioning]], and [[volleyball]].\n\nThe school offers music electives including [[choir|chorus]], concert choir, honors [[concert band]], [[jazz ensemble]], [[guitar]], [[electronic keyboard|keyboard]], [[marching band]], and [[string orchestra]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://francislewismusic.wixsite.com/home|title=home|website=home|access-date=December 4, 2018}}</ref> Students may take music electives for as long as their high school tenure. [[Music appreciation]] is offered as a one-year class for art/music credit.\n\n=== Language studies ===\nIn keeping with the school's diversity, Francis Lewis High School teaches several foreign languages, including [[Mandarin Chinese|Chinese (Mandarin)]], [[French language|French]], [[Greek language|Greek]] (for the fourth year of the University Scholars program), [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Korean language|Korean]], [[Latin]], and [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. Classes for native speakers in Chinese, Korean, and Spanish are also available for students satisfying the NYCDOE's foreign language requirement. The school previously taught [[Arabic]] and [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], but those classes ended due to declining interest.\n\nEnglish as New Language (ENL) is also available for English learners.\n\n=== Advanced Placement courses ===\nIn 1978, Francis Lewis High School was the first public high school to achieve certification to the [[International Baccalaureate]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ferretronix.com/flewis/#ib_footnote|title=The first IB class at Francis Lewis High School 1975-1978|publisher=Ferretronix.com|date=|accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nTUjMNjNo3EC&pg=RA1-PA140&lpg=RA1-PA140&dq=international+baccalaureate+francis+lewis#v=onepage&q=international%20baccalaureate%20francis%20lewis&f=false|title=Schools Across Frontiers: The Story of the International Baccalaureate and ... - Alexander Duncan Campbell Peterson - Google Boeken|accessdate=October 3, 2013|isbn=9780812695052|year=2003}}</ref>, but stopped offering it in the 1990s<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ferretronix.com/flewis/|title=The first IB class at Francis Lewis High School 1975-1978|website=ferretronix.com|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref>. [[Advanced Placement]] (AP) courses are also available, offering college credit for work done during high school (based on the final test score).  Students may choose the full program to get a full years' college credit, or simply courses of interest (for credit towards single college courses such as math or humanities). Sixty percent of twelfth graders take at least one Advanced Placement exam at any time during high school; of these, 72% earned at least a 3 on at least one Advanced Placement exam.<ref>\"[https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/new-york/districts/new-york-city-public-schools/francis-lewis-high-school-13354/test-scores Francis Lewis High School: Test Scores]\". ''U.S. News & World Report''. Retrieved February 16, 2020.</ref> \n\nStudents can choose from 20 AP courses offered at Francis Lewis, including [[AP Biology|Biology]], [[AP Calculus#AP Calculus AB|Calculus AB]], [[AP Calculus#AP Calculus BC|Calculus BC]], [[AP Capstone|Capstone]] [[AP Chemistry|Chemistry]], [[AP Chinese Language and Culture|Chinese Language and Culture]], [[AP Computer Science|Computer Science A]], [[AP English Language and Composition|English Language and Composition]], [[AP English Literature and Composition|English Literature and Composition]], [[AP Environmental Science|Environmental Science]], [[AP Japanese Language and Culture|Japanese Language and Culture]], [[AP Latin|Latin]], [[AP Macroeconomics|Macroeconomics]], [[AP Microeconomics|Microeconomics]], [[AP Physics 1|Physics 1]], [[AP Physics 2|Physics 2]], [[AP Physics C: Mechanics]], [[AP Psychology|Psychology]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[AP Statistics|Statistics]], [[AP United States Government and Politics|United States Government and Politics]], [[AP United States History|United States History]], and [[AP World History|World History]].\n\n=== College Now! Courses ===\nFrancis Lewis High School offers several courses from College Now, a program offered by the [[City University of New York]] to allow students access City University of New York classes and earn college credit. Classes are offered at [[Queens College, City University of New York|Queens College]] and [[Queensborough Community College]].\n\nStudents can choose up to six classes including [[astronomy]], [[health education|health]] and [[nutrition]], [[criminal justice]]/[[sociology]], [[Computers|computers in modern society]], [[English language|English]], and [[calculus|pre-calculus]].\n\n==Junior Reserve Officers' Training Corps==\nIn 1994, the US Army [[Junior Reserve Officers' Training Corps]] (JROTC) program was established in the school.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/20/education/20oneducation.html?pagewanted=all&_r=1|work=The New York Times|first=Michael|last=Winerip|title=At High School in Queens, an R.O.T.C. Program's Enduring Influence|date=June 19, 2011|url-access=limited}}</ref> It is the largest in the nation, with more than 1,000 cadets of the 1,725 high school chapters in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/162143/queens-junior-rotc-cadets-put-discipline-on-display |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130216141403/http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/162143/queens-junior-rotc-cadets-put-discipline-on-display |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 16, 2013|title=Queens Junior ROTC Cadets Put Discipline On Display|publisher=NY1|date=May 30, 2012|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref> The battalion is an honor unit with distinction, and it is considered one of the best and well-known US Army JROTC units in the nation.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.qchron.com/editions/north/francis-lewis-hs-jrotc-is-perfection/article_82d2edf1-10aa-58b6-a797-99ecb0f63671.html|title=Francis Lewis HS JROTC is perfection - Queens Chronicle: North/Northeast Queens News|publisher=Qchron.com|date=February 13, 2013|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref> It had a 100% graduation rate from 1992 to 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Bigger is better at 4,000-student strong Francis Lewis High School in Queens|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/education/bigger-better-4-000-student-strong-francis-lewis-high-school-queens-article-1.1483733|accessdate=August 21, 2015|location=New York|work=Daily News|date=October 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThere are six JROTC teams, namely Academic, Choir, Drum Corps, Honor Guard, and Drill Team (Armed and Unarmed). Two teams compete, Academic and Drill Team (Unarmed \u2013 Patriot Pride, Armed \u2013 Patriot Guard). Francis Lewis High School used to have a competing Raiders team (female \u2013 Patriot Strength, male \u2013 Patriot Force).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flhspatriotbattalion.com/index.html|title=FLHS PATRIOT BATTALION JROTC - Francis Lewis Patriot Battalion|publisher=Flhspatriotbattalion.com|date=|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref> In 2018 allegations of hazing (involving sexual and physical assault) from the male Raiders team were made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/11/03/cadet-reveals-junior-rotc-units-disturbing-hazing-ritual/|title=I was scorched with hot iron and sexually assaulted: JROTC cadet|last=Edelman|first=Susan|last2=Dorn|first2=Sara|date=November 3, 2018|website=New York Post|access-date=December 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Patriot Guard were national champions in 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenationals.net/dt-past_champs.htm|title=NHSDTC Masters Level Past Champions - 1987 through the present|work=Sports Network International|date=|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref> 2009\u20132011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenationals.net/dt-results-2009M.pdf|title=National High School Drill Team Championships : Masters Level Event Standings|publisher=Thenationals.net|accessdate=February 21, 2015}}</ref> and placed second in 2012. The Patriot Pride came in second in 2006, 2008 and 2009 and first in 2010 and 2013 National Championships in [[Daytona, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnewyork.com/video/#!/on-air/as-seen-on/National-Drill-Competition-Champions-Winners/208752271|title=Video|publisher=NBC New York|date=September 26, 2013|accessdate=October 3, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402032823/http://www.nbcnewyork.com/video/#!/on-air/as-seen-on/National-Drill-Competition-Champions-Winners/208752271|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe female Raiders were national champions for four consecutive years from 2009 to 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenationals.net/raider-results-female-all.pdf|title=2014 Raider Nationals Overall Score Report Female Division|work=Sports Network International|accessdate=February 21, 2015}}</ref> The male Raiders' most recent first-place title was in 2011, having come in third in the 2012 Nationals and second in the 2013 Nationals.<ref>Tolliver, Rachael (November 4, 2013). \"[http://www.army.mil/article/114427/Campbell__Adairsville__join_Smith_Cotton_as_2013_National_Raider_champs/ Campbell, Adairsville, join Smith-Cotton as 2013 National Raider champs]\". ''United States Army''.</ref>\n\nThe Academic team was awarded first place at the 2015 Leadership Bowl Nationals.<ref>\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20150811075303/http://collegeoptionsfoundation.net/2015-jlab-results/ 2015 JROTC Army Leadership Finals]\". ''College Options Foundation''. Archived from [http://collegeoptionsfoundation.net/2015-jlab-results/ the original] on August 11, 2015.</ref> The Academic team placed as finalists in the JROTC Leadership Academic Bowl in 2011, 2012, and 2013.\n\nIn 2010, Francis Lewis had more cadets in the [[United States Military Academy]] than any other public high school in the United States.<ref name= excellence>Ali Shama, Musa (December 21, 2010). \"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/575633716/ Ranking Obscures Fact We Are Committed to Excellence]\". ''Daily News'' (New York, New York). p. 6.</ref> \n\nThe JROTC Program may be chosen as an elective that a student may have in addition to their program. Students enrolled in JROTC are required to partake in weekly physical training, conduct school and community service, wear the Army Service Uniform once a weak, as well as take courses on leadership, nutrition, personal finance, civics, and government.\n\n==Extracurricular Activities==\n\n=== Athletics ===\nFrancis Lewis High School's athletic teams compete in the [[PSAL]]. Student-athletes compete in [[baseball]], [[basketball]], [[bowling]], [[cheerleading]], [[cross country running|cross country]], [[fencing]], [[golf]], [[American handball|handball]], [[soccer]], [[softball]], [[swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[tennis]], [[track and field|track]], [[volleyball]], and [[wrestling]]<ref name= about/>\n\nFrancis Lewis High School's cross country team team won the PSAL championship in 1968.<ref name= rebound/>\n\nThe school's soccer team won the PSAL championship in 1969.<ref name= rebound/>\n\nThe softball team won the PSAL championship in 1975.<ref name= rebound/>\n\nFrancis Lewis High School's girls basketball team won the PSAL Championship in March 1979.<ref name= wagner>{{cite web|title=Lewis Tops Wagner for Girls' Title|website=The New York Times|date=March 11, 1979|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/03/11/archives/lewis-tops-wagner-for-girls-title.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=S7|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The team was undefeated in the regular season that year.<ref name= wagner/>\n\nFrancis Lewis has had a [[cricket]] team since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Michael|title=Uprooted to Brooklyn, and Nourished by Cricket|website=The New York Times|date=October 16, 2016|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/16/sports/uprooted-to-brooklyn-and-nourished-by-cricket.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=SP1|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nThe school's male and female [[American handball]] team won the PSAL championship in the 2018\u20132019 season.\n\nDuring the 1994\u20131995 season, Francis Lewis High School's boys basketball team was undefeated in its division, the first time it had done so since the 1980\u20131981 season.<ref>\"Queens Sports Notebook\". ''Newsday''. March 19, 1995. p. A45.</ref> The team won the PSAL B Championship in March 1995.<ref>\"High School Basketball Previews\". ''Newsday''. December 3, 1995. p. 22.</ref><ref>\"Francis Lewis Captures B Title\". ''Newsday''. March 19, 1995. p. 16.</ref> The team advanced to the New York State Federation Basketball Class A championship in [[Glens Falls]]. It lost to [[Mount Saint Michael Academy]] of the Bronx, knocking it out of the state tournament.<ref>\"Results Plus\". ''The New York Times''. March 26, 1995. p. 813.</ref>\n\nFrancis Lewis High School's athletic field is named for [[Margaret Lambert]], a [[History of the Jews in Germany|German Jewish]] [[track and field]] athlete. During the 1930s, [[Nazi Germany|German]] athletic teams were closed to Jewish athletes, and the [[United States Olympic Committee|United States]] was considering to boycott the [[1936 Summer Olympics|1936 Summer Olympics in Berlin]] in protest of Germany's [[anti-Semitism]]. [[Adolf Hitler]] wanted to avoid a boycott, so he threatened her father to have her train for Germany in order to convince the world that Germany welcomed Jewish athletes to its team if they qualified. She tied the German high jump record at the national trials in [[Stuttgart]], and she trained at the Olympic training camp in [[Ettlingen]].<ref>Jacobson, Steve (May 3, 2015). \"Barred by the Nazis\". ''Newsday''. p. A10.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Margaret Bergmann Lambert, Jewish Athlete Excluded From Berlin Olympics, Dies at 103|website=The New York Times|date=July 25, 2017|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/25/sports/olympics/margaret-bergmann-lambert-dead-barred-from-1936-olympics.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n=== Clubs ===\nFrancis Lewis offers a varying number of clubs approved by the Student Organization (SO). Students may fill out a club registration forms from the SO Office by the late September deadline.\n\nThe 2019\u20132020 school year offers clubs<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=sites&srcid=ZGVmYXVsdGRvbWFpbnxmbGhzMTEzNjV8Z3g6NzQ3NDU3MTY4YTg0ZDJjOA|title=FLHS Clubs 2019.pdf|website=docs.google.com|access-date=November 16, 2019 }}</ref> including [https://nyc.cce.cornell.edu/4-h/ 4H Cornell], [[American Red Cross]] Club, Anime Club, Art Club, Asian Food Culture Club, Baseball Club, [[Calligraphy]] Club, Chess Club, Chinese Chess Club, Chinese Club, Chinese Origami Club, Christian Seekers Fellowship, Creative Writing Club, Cultural Dance Club, Current Events Club, [https://www.deca.org DECA], DIY Club, Double Up (Mentor) Club, [[Dungeons & Dragons|Dungeons and Dragons]], Endangered Species Club, Environmental Club, Fashion Club, Film Club, Fitness Club, Gardening Club, Girls Fall Conditioning, [[Girls Who Code|Girls Who Code (GWC)]], [https://www.glamourgals.org Glamour Gals], [https://thegreenteam.org Green Team], [[Harry Potter]] Club, Hellenic Club, History Club, HS Investment Club (HSIC), Humans of Francis Lewis Magazine, Inspiring Inclusive Leaders, International Education Club, ISS Club, Japanese Club, Jewish Student Union, Journalism Club (FLHS News), [[Junior State of America]] (JSA), [[K-pop]] and Urban Dance Club (KUD), [[Key Club]], Korean Club, [[Korean drum|Korean Drum]] Club, [[Kung Fu]] Club, [[LGBTQ+]] Club, Math Club, Media Production Club, Medical Explorers Club, [[Mindfulness]] + [[Yoga]] Club, [[Model United Nations]], Modern Music Club, Muslim Student Association Club, [[My Brother's Keeper Challenge|My Brother's Keeper]], [https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/signature-programs/no-place-for-hate No Place for Hate], Nu Gamma Psi (male and female [[Stepping (African-American)|step]] teams), One Love Counseling Club, Programmers Initiative Club (PI), Public Speaking for Beginners, Puzzle Club, Science Olympiads, Sikh Student Association, Spanish Club, Students for Climate Action Now, [[Taekwondo]] Club, [[Ted Talk|TED Talk]] Club, Teen Community Service (TCS), Travelers Club, Trivia Club, Ultimate Unity Dance Club, [[UNICEF]], Video Game Club, Visual Arts Club, Women's Empowerment Club, and Workout Club.\n\nFormer clubs include 3D Model Club (2017\u20132018), [[American Civil Liberties Union|ACLU]] (2017\u20132018) African American Club (2018\u20132019), Ancient History Club (2018\u20132019), Animal Humane Society (2017\u20132018), Astronomy Club (2016\u20132017), [https://medschool.ucla.edu/body.cfm?id=1158&action=detail&ref=602 Big Sib-Little Sib] (2017\u20132018), Books for Baddies (2018\u20132019), Bookworms (2017\u20132018), Caribbean Club (2017\u20132018), Comedy Club (2018\u20132019), Comic Book Club (2016\u20132017), Conscious Club (2018\u20132019), Conservation Club (2017\u20132018), Dancer Dynasty Club (2018\u20132019), Debate Club (2018\u20132019), eSport Club (2018\u20132019), Filipino Club, FLNBC (2015\u20132016), Food Appreciation Club (2017\u20132018), Game Club (2017\u20132018), Gamer's Connect (2018\u20132019), Game Development and Design Club (2018\u20132019), Glee Club (2015\u20132018), Global Advocates Club (2017\u20132019), Interconnected Club (2017\u20132018), International Club (2017\u20132018), International Pop Club (2017\u20132018), [[Latin]] Club (2017\u20132018), Latinos Unidos (2018\u20132019), Make-Up Club (2017\u20132018), Mental Health Club (2018\u20132019), Music Cover Club (2018\u20132019), Music Creation (2018\u20132019), One Neutron Extra (ONE, 2016\u20132017), [https://operationcareinternational.org Operation CARE Team] (2017\u20132019), Philosophy Club (2018\u20132019), Photography Club, Pre-Med Club, Social Activist Club (2018\u20132019), SPEAK (2018\u20132019), STEMP Club (2018\u20132019), Video Game Club (2017\u20132018), and Youth Civic Engagement (YCE, 2018\u20132019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BaM0rkKgUTQ/|title=Francis Lewis Class Of 2018! on Instagram: \"Club list is out! \ud83d\udc4c\ud83c\udffc\ud83d\udc4c\ud83c\udffc\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=sites&srcid=ZGVmYXVsdGRvbWFpbnxmbGhzMTEzNjV8Z3g6MjEwODExOWI2NzBjNTY4MQ|title=FLHS Club Charters 2018\u20132019.pdf|website=docs.google.com|access-date=November 16, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1952, the Northeast Queens Council for Schools advocated for a northeast Queens high school because of severe overcrowding at [[Bayside High School (Queens)|Bayside High School]], [[Flushing High School]], [[Andrew Jackson High School (Queens)|Andrew Jackson High School]], and [[Jamaica High School]].<ref name= sotw>Morales, Tina (March 18, 1990). \"School of the Week: Francis Lewis H.S.\" ''Newsday''.</ref>\n\nIn December 1955, the [[New York City Board of Education]] approved the building of a new high school, called Northeast Queens High School, near the intersection of [[Utopia Parkway (Queens)|Utopia Parkway]] and 59th Avenue, with a capacity of 3,000 students.<ref name= 25schools>{{cite web|title=25 Schools in City Planned for 1956|website=The New York Times|date=December 12, 1955|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/12/12/archives/25-schools-in-city-planned-for-1956-board-also-lists-4-additions.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=1|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The city bought 11 acres of land, and the City Planning Commission agreed that the high school was needed, but the Commission did not approve the allocation of money to build the school in the capital budget.<ref name= sotw/><ref name= mayorasks>{{cite web|title=Mayor Asks Schools: Bids Plan Board Provide One in Queens, One in Brooklyn|website=The New York Times|date=October 8, 1956|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/10/08/archives/mayor-asks-schools-bids-plan-board-provide-one-in-queens-one-in.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=29|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name= beg>{{cite web|last=Bennett|first=Charles G.|title=Parents Beg City for More Schools: Hundreds Flock to Budget Hearings, Mostly From Brooklyn and Queens|website=The New York Times|date=October 10, 1956|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1956/10/10/archives/parents-beg-city-for-more-schools-hundreds-flock-to-budget-hearings.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=41|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1956, the city approved the hiring of the firm of [[Eggers & Higgins]] to be the architect of the building, although the budget to actually build the high school was not yet approved.<ref name= franklin>\"Ben Franklin To Open As Co-ed High School\". ''New York Amsterdam News''. September 10, 1960. p. 6.</ref><ref name= beg/>\n\nIn October 1956, [[Mayor of New York City|Mayor]] [[Robert F. Wagner Jr.]] wrote a letter to the City Planning Commission asking it to include the construction of Northeast Queens High School in its capital budget.<ref name= mayorasks/> The construction was included in the capital budget in 1957.<ref>\"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/455688307/ School Council to Map Goals for Next Year]\". ''Daily News'' (New York, New York). December 2, 1956. p. 35B.</ref> \n\nIn March 1958, the Board of Education approved a contract to build the high school.<ref name=\"boardvotes\">{{cite web|title=Board Votes a New Junior High School As Albany Moves to Abolish Them Here|website=The New York Times|date=March 21, 1958|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1958/03/21/archives/board-votes-a-new-junior-high-school-as-albany-moves-to-abolish.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=11|url-access=subscription}}</ref> A $4,229,000 contract was awarded to the lowest bidder, Caristo Construction Company.<ref name= boardvotes/> The ground-breaking happened that same year. A group of parents tried to have an indoor swimming pool built in the high school, but they were not successful.<ref>\"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/418934421/ Renew Drive for HS Pool]\". ''New York Daily News''. November 5, 1959. p. 7.</ref> The high school ended up costing $6,100,000 to build.<ref name= franklin/>\n\nFrancis Lewis High School opened on September 13, 1960.<ref name= topschool>\"[https://search.proquest.com/docview/225502540/610527BA513C44D6PQ/1 Segregation Still A Top School Problem]\". ''New York Amsterdam News''. September 10, 1960. p. 17.</ref> The school was named after [[Francis Lewis]], a resident of [[Whitestone, Queens|Whitestone]] who signed the [[United States Declaration of Independence]].<ref name= sotw/> Vincent McGarrett was the first principal.<ref name= newcollege/> Herman Wolf was the first basketball coach.<ref>Hurley, Ed (March 20, 1960). \"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/420678342/ Wolf at Door of Lewis HS on Rebound]\". ''New York Daily News''. p. 49.</ref> [[Queensborough Community College]] held some of its classes at Francis Lewis High School that year because its own campus was still under construction.<ref name= newcollege>\"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/459102744/ New College Borrows Rms. For Sept. Bow]\". ''New York Daily News''. July 24, 1960. p. 19.</ref> \n\nFrancis Lewis High School was built for a capacity of 2,700 students.<ref name= topschool/> The school was overcrowded as of the 1962\u20131963 school year.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hechinger|first=Fred M.|title=Schools Reopen; Rolls Up 19,618|website=The New York Times|date=September 11, 1962|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/09/11/archives/schools-reopen-rolls-up-19618-crowding-still-widespread-hereparents.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=1|url-access=subscription}}</ref> [[Benjamin N. Cardozo High School|Cardozo High School]] was built in 1967 in order to relieve overcrowding at Francis Lewis.<ref>\"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/576187420/ Future Public Hearings Set]\". ''The Williamsburg Times'' (Brooklyn, New York). April 12, 1963. p. 6.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/460025817/ Golf Course Tract]\". ''New York Daily News''. August 18, 1963. p. 46.</ref> \n\nIn 1965, [[Queensborough Community College]] held some of its evening classes at Francis Lewis High School due to overcrowding at Queensborough.<ref>{{cite web|title=Buses to be Used as Classrooms; Students at Queensborough College Forced Into Mobile Quarters for a Week|website=The New York Times|date=October 23, 1965|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1965/10/23/archives/buses-to-be-used-for-classrooms-students-at-queensborough-college.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=33|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn 1978, Francis Lewis High School graduated [[International Baccalaureate]] diploma students, the first public high school in the United States to do so.<ref>Isger, Sonja (September 6, 2015). \"How IB program came to U.S.: West Palm retiree says bad weather helped\". ''TCA Regional News'' (Chicago, Illinois).</ref> It terminated in the 1990s.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Mashama Bailey]] - chef\n* [[Steve Dorff]] (1968) \u2013 composer/music producer{{citation needed|reason=lacks a reliable source confirming attendance|date=February 2019}}\n* [[Rob Echeverria]]<ref>Slattery, Denis (September 28, 2014). \"Hardcore boro Band invents 'Sick' new meaning for Bronx\". ''New York Daily News''. p. 39.</ref> \u2013 American musician who has worked as the guitarist of [[Biohazard (band)|Biohazard]], [[Helmet (band)|Helmet]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Billboard |date=21 August 1999 |page=82}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Phillips |first1=William |title=Encyclopedia of Heavy Metal Music}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rotondi |first1=James |title=Dropped D-Day: Helmet Levels Metaldom |url=http://www.bluecricket.com/helmet/interviews/gp892.html |accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Suarez |first1=Gary |title=Why Helmet decided to take an album that wasn't a best-seller on tour, two decades later |url=https://www.indyweek.com/indyweek/why-helmet-decided-to-take-an-album-that-wasnt-a-best-seller-on-tour-two-decades-later/Content?oid=4344695 |accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=REYES-KULKARNI |first1=SABY |title=HOW HELMET BROADENED THEIR SOUND ON 'BETTY' |url=http://diffuser.fm/21-years-ago-helmet-release-betty/ |website=[[Townsquare Media|Diffuser]] |accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref> Rest in Pieces, and [[Straight Ahead (band)|Straight Ahead]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alva |first1=Freddy |title=Rob Echeverria (Straight Ahead, Rest in Pieces, Biohazard, Helmet) |url=http://www.noecho.net/interviews/rob-echeverria-straight-ahead-rest-in-pieces-biohazard-helmet |accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=BUKSZPAN |first1=DANIEL |title=The Z Review Playlist: CBGB's 1984-1986 by Musician Rob Echeverria |url=https://thezreview.com/2018/06/29/the-z-review-playlist-cbgbs-1984-1986-by-musician-rob-echeverria/ |accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Rick Elice]] (1973) \u2013 actor, writer{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n* [[David Gordon]] (2006) \u2013 theater critic, President of the Outer Critics Circle\n* [[Steve Greenberg (record producer)|Steve Greenberg]] (1978) \u2013 record producer, former President of Columbia Records{{citation needed|reason=lacks a reliable source confirming attendance|date=February 2019}}\n* [[Sebasti\u00e1n Guenzatti]] \u2013  [[association football|soccer]] player for the [[Tampa Bay Rowdies]] of the [[United Soccer League]]<ref>Gavin, Mike (September 14, 2013). \"Guenzatti enjoying his role in history\". ''Newsday''. September 14, 2013. p. A30.</ref>\n* [[Peter Guttman (photographer)|Peter Guttman]] (1972) \u2013 travel journalist, lecturer, and author{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n* [[Heejun Han]] (2007) \u2013 finalist on [[American Idol]], [[American Idol (season 11)|season 11]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/heejun-han-false-idol-article-1.1027844|title='American Idol' star in the making: NYC's Heejun Han makes final 24|date=February 23, 2012|accessdate=March 4, 2012|location=New York|work=Daily News}}</ref>\n* [[Albie Hecht]] \u2013 former president of [[Nickelodeon]], founder of [[Spike TV]]<ref>Hayes, Dade (Dec 1 2008). \"Can TV titan work wonders on Web? Hecht, yeah\". ''Variety'' (Los Angeles, California). Vol. 413. Iss. 3. p. 26.</ref> \n* [[Mike Jorgensen]] (1966) \u2013 drafted by the [[New York Mets]];<ref>{{cite web|last=Durso|first=Joseph|title=Team Is Confident After Successful Spring Training|website=The New York Times|date=April 4, 1970|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/04/04/archives/team-is-confident-after-successful-spring-training.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=47|url-access=subscription}}</ref> played for the New York Mets, [[Montreal Expos]], [[Oakland Athletics]], [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], [[Atlanta Braves]], and [[St. Louis Cardinals]]; managed the Cardinals<ref>{{cite web|title=Mets Sign Dyer and Two Rookies: Matlack and Jorgensen Lift Total Under Contract to 18|website=The New York Times|date=January 1, 1970|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/01/archives/mets-sign-dyer-and-two-rookies-matlack-and-jorgensen-lift-total.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=S2|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n* [[Paul Joskow]] \u2014 American economist and professor<ref>Joskow, Paul L. (September 29, 2009). \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/03/opinion/l03school.html Boom Times at Francis Lewis High]\". ''The New York Times''.</ref>\n* [[Peter Marino]] \u2013 American [[architect]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Hamilton|first=William L.|title=The Palace Maker|website=The New York Times|date=February 5, 2004|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/05/garden/the-palace-maker.html|access-date=March 4, 2019|page=F1|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n* [[Mark Miloscia]] \u2013 [[Washington State Senator]]<ref>\"Education Funding Leads Statewide Issues\". ''Spokesman Review'' (Spokane, Washington). October 11, 2016. p. T5.</ref> \n* [[Jonathan Pontell]] \u2013  television director, producer, and editor{{citation needed|reason=lacks a reliable source confirming attendance|date=February 2019}}\n* [[Craig Setari]] \u2013 American musician and former competitive boxer who is currently active as the bass player in [[Sick of It All]] \u2013 [[hardcore punk]] band<ref>{{cite web |last1=Slattery |first1=Denis |title=New York hardcore legends invents 'Sick' new meaning for Bronx |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/queens/sick-ready-bronx-article-1.1954445 |website=nydailynews.com |accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Ron Shandler]] (1974) \u2013 national baseball analyst, author of ''Baseball Forecaster'', founder of BaseballHQ.com, columnist for [[USA Today]]{{citation needed|reason=lacks a reliable source confirming attendance|date=February 2019}}\n* [[Dennis Walcott]] \u2013 former chancellor of the [[New York City Department of Education]], president and CEO of the [[Queens Borough Public Library]] system<ref>Enis, Matt; Peet, Lisa (March 15, 2016). \"Dennis Walcott Named CEO of Queens Library\". ''Library Journal'' (New York). Vol. 141, Iss. 5.</ref>\n* [[Chris Welty]] (1981) \u2013 computer scientist{{citation needed|reason=lacks a reliable source confirming attendance|date=February 2019}}\n\n==In fiction==\n* In ''[[The Yards]]'', [[Joaquin Phoenix]] plays a character who graduated from Francis Lewis High School.<ref name=gray>Hirschon, Nicholas (December 23, 2011). \"[https://www.newspapers.com/image/583044098/ James Gray's Films Explore Underdog Living in Qns.]\" ''Daily News'' (New York, New York). p. p. 35.</ref> The film's director, [[James Gray (director)|James Gray]], grew up in [[Flushing, Queens|Flushing]].<ref name=gray/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.francislewishs.org}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/20/education/20oneducation.html?_r=1&pagewanted=all At High School in Queens, R.O.T.C.\u2019s Enduring Influence]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/29/nyregion/29crowded.html At School in Queens, Success Draws Crowd - New York Times]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150402032823/http://www.nbcnewyork.com/video/#!/on-air/as-seen-on/National-Drill-Competition-Champions-Winners/208752271 National Drill Competition- Champions Interview- NBC]\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in Queens, New York]]\n", "name_user": "59.149.181.220", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNotable alumni)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Lewis_High_School"}
{"title_page": "Indian rock", "text_new": " \n{{Distinguish|Raga rock}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2010}}\n{{infobox music genre|name= Indian rock\n|color=black\n|bgcolor=lavender\n|font color=\"blue\"\n|stylistic_origins=[[South Asian]]<br>[[Indian music]]\n|cultural_origins= [[India]], [[Bengal]]\n|instruments=[[Singing|Vocals]], [[Gramophone record|Gramophone]], [[Jazz]], [[Indian musical instruments]], [[Electric guitar]], [[Bass guitar]], [[Drums]], [[Keyboard instrument|Keyboard]], [[Electric sitar]]\n|popularity=India\n|subgenres=\n|regional_scenes=\n|other_topics=\n}}\n{{Indian music|expanded=Genres}}\n\n'''Indian rock''' is a [[music genre]] in [[India]] that incorporates elements of [[Music of India|Indian music]] with [[rock music]], and is often topically India-centric. While India is more often known for its ([[Hindustani classical music|northern]] and [[Carnatic music|southern]]) [[Indian classical music|classical music]], [[filmi]], [[Bollywood music]], [[Indi-pop]], and [[Bhangra (music)|Bhangra]], the Indian rock scene has also produced numerous bands and artists.\n\n==Early history==\nIndia, in the 1950s and 1960s, had a record industry in the Gramophone Company of India (an RCA/HMV/EMI subsidiary), and [[Long playing records|LPs]], [[Extended play|EPs]], and [[45rpm]] records were freely available, including those of [[rock and roll]] acts from the US and Britain, but also of contemporary pioneering Indian rock bands. The president of the firm, [[Bhaskar Menon]] (who later became the President of [[Capitol Records]] in the United States) was the leading promoter of Western pop music in India. Later in 1970, [[Polydor]], the German Label, began an India label distributing rock music.\n\nOf these mid-1960s to early 70s [[Beat music|beat]] groups, as they was then termed, one of the most notable were the [[Mystiks]] from [[Mumbai|Bombay]], the [[Beat-X]] from [[Chennai|Madras]], and the Flintstone from [[Kolkata|Calcutta]], who composed and played both early [[British Invasion]] influenced songs, and post-''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band|Sgt. Pepper]]'' [[hard rock]]. During this period from Delhi there were The Thunderbirds (featuring singer Ashwani Bali), and WAFWOT (also with Ashwani on vocals, with organist Mark Spevak, from the U.S.) These bands played regularly on the Indian university and college music circuits, and some had successful EP and LP releases. Also notable from this period (1964\u20131970) was the female [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]  singer, Usha Iyer, now [[Usha Uthup]], who had successful covers of \"[[Jambalaya (On the Bayou)|Jambalaya]]\" and [[The Kingston Trio]] song, \"Greenback Dollar\". A notable compilation LP titled \"Simla Beat '70\" was released during this period, from a contest of the same name. The winning bands recorded their versions of Western hard rock of the time. This tradition of covering Western rock would continue until the 1980s when it was more common to compose original songs.\n\nThe rock n' roll scene was also closely followed by ''[[The Statesman (India)|Junior Statesman]]'' (or ''JS''), a magazine started in 1965 contemporaneously with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine in the US and [[NME]] in the UK.\n\n{{Listen\n| filename    = \n| title       = \"Ae Naujawan Hai Sab Kuchh Yahan\"\n| description = [[Asha Bhosle]]'s \"Ae Naujawan Hai Sab Kuch Yahan\" from the film ''[[Apradh]]'' (1972)\n| pos         = right\n}}\n\nLike Western rock musicians at the time, Indian musicians also began fusing rock with traditional Indian music from the mid-1960s onwards. Many of these songs were often ''[[filmi]]'' songs produced for popular [[Bollywood]] films, which often overshadowed the country's independent rock scene. Some of the more well known early rock songs (including styles such as [[funk rock]], [[pop rock]], [[psychedelic rock]], [[raga rock]], and [[soft rock]]) from Bollywood films include [[Mohammed Rafi]]'s \"[[Jaan Pehechan Ho]]\" in ''[[Gumnaam]]'' (1965), [[Kishore Kumar]]'s \"O Saathi Re\" in ''[[Muqaddar Ka Sikandar]]'' (1978), and [[Asha Bhosle]] songs such as \"[[Dum Maro Dum (song)|Dum Maro Dum]]\" in ''[[Hare Rama Hare Krishna (1971 film)|Hare Rama Hare Krishna]]'' (1971), \"Ae Naujawan Hai Sab\" in ''[[Apradh]]'' (1972), and \"Yeh Mera Dil Pyar Ka Diwana\" in ''[[Don (1978 film)|Don]]'' (1978).\n\n===Indian influence on Western music===\n{{See also|Raga rock|Psychedelic rock|The Beatles in India}}\n\nIn the 1960s, renowned [[Western world|Western]] acts such as [[The Yardbirds]], [[The Beatles]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[The Doors]] and [[The Byrds]] were notably influenced by [[Indian classical music]] as a way of reinforcing the [[Psychedelic music|psychedelia]] in their music. While [[jazz]] musicians, notably [[John Coltrane]], had ventured into Indian music and spiritualism (see [[Indo jazz]], [[Sitar in jazz]], and [[Jazz in India]]), the influence of Indian classical music on 1960s rock began in earnest with [[George Harrison]]'s [[Ravi Shankar]] inspired [[raga rock]] song \"[[Norwegian Wood (This Bird Has Flown)]]\" in 1965 and The Beatles' very public sojourn with the [[Maharishi Mahesh Yogi]] at his [[ashram]] in [[Rishikesh]] in 1968, following the release of ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' in 1967. Raga rock led to the development of [[psychedelic rock]], which in turn laid the foundations for [[heavy metal music]].\n\nThe Indian rock scene would later give rise to one of the world's most famous rock stars, [[Freddie Mercury]], born Farrokh Bulsara. One of his formative musical influences was the Bollywood singer [[Lata Mangeshkar]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Liam|title=Farrokh Bulsara|url=http://www.time.com/time/asia/2006/heroes/at_bulsara.html|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=28 April 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523230337/http://www.time.com/time/asia/2006/heroes/at_bulsara.html|archivedate=23 May 2011|year=2006}}</ref> He began his music career as a teenager in [[Mumbai|Bombay]] with the rock band, [[The Hectics]], which was founded in 1958 and often performed [[cover version]]s of Western [[rock and roll]] artists such as [[Little Richard]] and [[Cliff Richard]].<ref>{{citation|last=Hodkinson|first=Mark|year=2004|title=Queen: The Early Years|place=London|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=1-84449-012-2|pages=2 & 61}}</ref> After leaving the band in 1962, he moved to England, where he later led the rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]] (formed in 1971), which went on to become one of the world's most famous rock bands.\n\nThe Indian rock scene also gave rise to one of the pioneers of [[disco]] music, [[Biddu]],<ref name=\"metro_biddu\">{{cite web|title=Biddu|author=James Ellis|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/interviews/412-biddu|accessdate=17 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Listener, Volumes 100-101|work=[[The Listener (magazine)|The Listener]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|year=1978|page=216|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6tRBAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=21 June 2011|quote=Tony Palmer knocked off a film account of someone called Biddu (LWT), who appears to have been mad enough to invent disco music.}}</ref> who originally began his career in an Indian rock band called The Trojans. It was India's first English-speaking band,<ref name=\"times_2004\">{{cite web|date=20 August 2004|title=It's a big step from disco to Sanskrit chants, but Biddu has made it|author=Malika Browne|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/article471655.ece|accessdate=30 May 2011}}</ref> and found success producing cover versions of [[The Beatles]],<ref name=\"jones_kantonen\">{{cite book|title=Saturday night forever: the story of disco|author=Alan Jones & Jussi Kantonen|publisher=A Cappella Books|year=2000|isbn=1-55652-411-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ok0UAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=7 June 2011}}</ref> [[The Rolling Stones]],<ref name=\"gopal_moorti_99\">{{cite book|title=Global Bollywood: travels of Hindi song and dance|author=Sangita Gopal & Sujata Moorti|publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]]|year=2008|isbn=0-8166-4579-5|page=99|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=19JBf6oDOy0C&pg=PA99|accessdate=7 June 2011}}</ref> [[Trini Lopez]], and other Western hits of the day, in the clubs of [[Bangalore]], [[Kolkata|Calcutta]], and Bombay. After the band broke up, he moved in 1967 to England, where he later found breakthrough success after producing \"[[Kung Fu Fighting]]\" for [[Carl Douglas]].\n\n==1980s and 1990s==\n\nWhile the [[orientalism|orientalist]] trend of the 60s and 70s was by the 80s and 90s largely over, India itself continued to produce bands in various styles of rock music, from soft [[rock and roll]] and [[pop rock]], to [[hard rock]] and [[Heavy metal music|metal]]. In the early 1980s, however, rock was largely overshadowed by [[disco]], which dominated [[Indian pop]] music up until the mid-1980s.\n\nWith the arrival of [[MTV]], tastes rapidly changed, encouraging bands to harden their style and focus more on underground styles such as [[death metal]], [[alternative rock|alternative metal]], and [[progressive rock]]. The 1990s saw the rise of a much larger following of various harder styles for this reason. Bands that had formed in the 80s, such as Rock Machine (who would later be known as [[Indus Creed]]) - (including Mahesh Tinnaikar, Uday Benegal, etc.)...altered their style with the influx of newer techniques and influences from the west. Notable suburban metal-blues bands with 1960s and 1970s metal influences included IIT Powaii based Axecalibre, fronted by Oliver Pinto, Prashant Nair and covered flamboyant guitar-based blues and hardcore metal including ballads. Contemporaries of the time were Easy Meat from Pune and Bands such as Holocaust, Morgue (fronted by vocalist Mrinal Das, Drummer Neeraj Kakoty, Ambar Das and Raju Seal on Twin Attack Guitars, Manas Chowdhury on Bass), Dorian Platonic from Guwahati, Assam, Grassroots Revival, Postmark, The Cannibals, Phoenix,Phynyx and Drixian Empire/Dark Crusader from Manipur. \n\nOthers formed in the 1990s with harder styles influenced by the growing split between popular rock, such as [[Britpop]], alternative styles, such as [[punk rock|punk]], and metal styles, such as [[thrash metal|thrash]]. The Indian subgenre of fusion, which encourages a similar blend of ancient Indian musical traditions with rock music to [[raga rock]], was also carried forward, and is perhaps the most unusual Indian style of rock. Needless to say the rise of Sanskrit Rock Band (The Army of Narasimha Dev) had sprung to instant success in no time, founded by Lead vocalist Biju Gangadharan from ISKCON background, is a Sanskrit scholar and a highly talented Master in composing Sanskrit mantras into modern age rock music. Biju Gangadharan is considered as Sanskrit Rock Guru with a stunning performance in 33 countries up his shoulder. His guitarist, Chandresh Kudwa, is the most successful lead guitarist in India, and his percussionist, Nishadh Chandra, turned out to be the busiest music programmer in Bollywood. It was during this time that [[Palash Sen]]'s Euphoria surfaced in the Indian scene as a straight ahead English rock band. The band later started writing in Hindi, and gave birth to what is now known as \"Hindi Rock\". Euphoria went on to become India's most popular, successful and commercially accepted Independent act.\n\n==2000s==\n\nThe current Indian rock scene has a larger following than ever (although it is still marginalized compared to Indian film music, particularly the [[filmi]] soundtracks of [[Bollywood]]) and may soon become recognized in the international arena, as various South American and Japanese bands have become. Recent entries into the rock music scene are increasingly becoming comparable in their production quality to Western bands, and have been compared favorably to other internationally recognized acts. Now digital technology is making it easier than ever for these bands to distribute and sell their music. Some British bands of South Asian origin, such as [[Swami (band)|Swami]] have, like their [[hip-hop]] counterparts, tried to enter the Indian market in addition to maintaining the traditional fanbase of non-resident Indians in United Kingdom, [[Indo-Canadians|Canada]] and the [[Indian American|United States]]. Others, such as [[Rudra (band)|Rudra]], have emerged from Indian communities in other Asian countries. Progress is certain for the Indian rock scene with the advent of entities that support this genre. [[Rock Street Journal]] and Rolling Stone India<ref>{{cite web|title=Rolling stone|url=http://rollingstoneindia.com/|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> are the two major publications that have been promoting Indian rock bands. The scene has also been transformed by the online medium, and the subsequent rise of a number of online portals promoting Indian rock, most notably the indie music website NH7,<ref>{{cite web|title=NH7 Radio|url=http://nh7.in/|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> Headbangers India,<ref>{{cite web|title=HeadBangers India|url=http://www.headbangers.in/|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> IndianMusicMug,<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with UFO\u2019s guitarist Vinnie Moore|url=http://indianmusicmug.com/|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> Unholy Maunder, IndianMusicRevolution, Indian Metal Scene etc.<ref>{{cite web|title=IMR|url=http://www.indianmusicrevolution.com/|accessdate=6 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105043221/http://indianmusicrevolution.com/|archive-date=5 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> and Metal Spree.\n\n== Sub-genres ==\n\n=== Raga rock ===\n{{Main article|Raga rock}}\n{{See also|Psychedelic rock}}\n\nIn the West, some groups, such as [[The Beatles]], traveled to India and incorporated aspects of Indian music, especially classical instruments such as the [[sitar]], into their music, often as a way of conjuring [[Psychedelic music|psychedelic]] 'Eastern' feelings. The term for this was [[raga rock]], and examples of it are [[The Beatles]] \"[[Love You To]]\", \"[[The Inner Light (song)|The Inner Light]]\",\"[[Across the Universe]]\",\"[[Norwegian Wood (This Bird Has Flown)]]\", \"[[Tomorrow Never Knows]]\", \"[[Strawberry Fields Forever]]\" and \"[[Within You Without You]]\"; [[The Rolling Stones]]' \"[[Paint it, Black]]\"; [[The Kinks]]' \"Fancy\"; [[The Doors]]' \"[[The End (The Doors song)|The End]]\" and [[The Byrds]]' \"[[Eight Miles High]]\". A number of prolific Indian classical musicians such as [[Ravi Shankar]] aligned themselves with this trend, collaborating with Western artists. Indian bands themselves mainly covered early rock songs by pioneers of rock and roll in the United Kingdom and [[United States|America]], and only achieved recognition in popular culture by supporting film scores and Indian pop.\n\n=== Indian fusion ===\n{{main article|Indian fusion}}\n\nAn Indian subgenre of rock exists that focuses on blending traditional Indian styles of music with rock music. The term for non-Indian bands using Indian instrumentals and vocal in rock is [[raga rock]]. However, Indian fusion also encompasses attempts by Indian pop musicians and film composers to incorporate rock music into their work, starting in the 70s with film scores like those of the [[Amitabh Bachchan]] classics. The [[Brown Indian Band]] features accomplished Indian classical musicians in concert with jazz virtuosos. More recently the multi-cultural British band [[Botown]] have taken elements of Bollywood and fused them with soul and funk to great success. The New Delhi Based Band 'Ojapali' is also doing a lots of experiments with Electronica Fusion music and Folk music of the Assam Region.\nThe Kochi-based band [[Motherjane]] typifies bands producing this genre of music. [[Motherjane]] guitarist [[Baiju Dharmajan]] is a pioneer of introducing the guitar music style known as carnatic shredding. Bangalore based carnatic rock band [[Agam (band)|Agam]] and fusion rock outfit Divine Raaga, Kaav, Veenar are other examples of mature songmakers in the country.<ref>[http://www.musicmalt.com/2011/12/eastern-fare-rocks-trinity-guild-hall.html Bangalore - Music Malt]</ref>\nKarnatriix is another band which has defined a new genre of fusion music labelled 'New-age World music'. Their ever-evolving sound today registers as ideally in sync with the 21st century's pan-cultural landscape. The name 'KARNATRIIX' which is a word play, meaning 'Aural Trickery', openly defines their music. Mellifluous melodies and sophisticated phrases deep-rooted in Blues music with an Indian Classical touch, combined with raw percussion and electronically produced subtle beats, voices and effects, form the core essence of the Karnatriix's musical nature. Indian Guitarist [[Kapil Srivastava]] composed Rock and Raga Fusion music in his Indian Guitaroo Volume 1.<ref>{{cite news|title=ZeeNews|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/musicindia/kapil-srivastava-cuts-his-new-album-indian-guitaroo_91243.html|accessdate=5 February 2015|newspaper=ZeeNews}}</ref>. [[The_Iyer_Project_(band)|The Iyer Project]] is another Delhi based band that blends Carnatic style vocals and guitar playing influenced by Baiju Dharmajan and [[R. Prasanna]] with rock and roll and progressive rock.\n\n=== Indian funk ===\nIndian [[funk]] is a loose term describing the style of rock and roll which is sometimes blurred into the realms of pop and other genres. Whereas Indian fusion may only incorporate Indian styles into rock, or rock into Indian forms of music, Indian funk can be broadly defined as what rap-metal is to heavy metal - an infusion of elements from rap, reggae, pop and dance genres that some might consider to not be 'true' rock. Groups originating in South Asian communities in Western countries like Britain are noted for this style, with bands such as [[Swami (band)|Swami]] and [[Asian Dub Foundation]] using elements of [[UK garage]], [[Bhangra (music)|UK bhangra]] and [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]], such as synthesizers, rap vocals and [[phonograph|turntables]]. Also based in the UK, [[Botown]] take an approach inspired by [[Funkadelic]] with a large lineup of live musicians to blend Bollywood music with [[Soul music|soul]] and [[funk]]. Few rock bands such as Silent Echo (Delhi) and Psycho Frequency (Delhi) use a wide range of samples and mechanically evolved sounds. [https://web.archive.org/web/20160217145035/http://www.swastiktheband.com/ Swastik The Band],<ref>https://www.facebook.com/swastiktheband</ref> founded in 2005 ([[Chandigarh]] Based band) is upcoming band which brings the blend of [[Hindustani Culture]] and the core essence of [[Culture of India|Indian]] culture twined with various other cultures, Swastik the band aims to designing [[Indian music]] on western rhythms with a pinch of [[Folk music|Folk]] And [[Sufi Music]] to add flavor to their compositions. Rohit Joshi, Founder and the Lead Guitars/vocals of Swastik the band believes on lines by [[John Green (author)|John Green]] \"Some people have lives; some people have music\".\n\n=== Rock and roll ===\n[[File:Hundred Octane unplugged- live in Hard Rock Cafe, Mumbai.jpg|thumb|200px|Hundred Octane performing at [[Hard Rock Cafe]] in Mumbai]]\nIndia has produced many rock bands, some of whom have made it into mainstream Indian music and achieved some international recognition.\nRLC66 one of the upcoming acts from Mumbai trying to combine various genres from western music. Their main influences are Porcupine Tree, Tool, Dream Theater. The song \"Abrupt\" is earning some good number of fans in Mumbai underground scene. Indian Guitar Player [[Kapil Srivastava]] has composed Rock and Roll fusion in his Indian Guitaroo Volume 2.<ref>{{cite news|title=RadioandMusic|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/content/editorial/news-releases/indian-guitaroo-album-vol-2-release-kapil-srivastava|accessdate=5 February 2015|newspaper=RnMNewsDesk}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Mumbai based Rock & Roll Bassist [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304122017/http://www.sweetwinemusic.com/vivekdate.html Vivek Date] released his Rock & Roll Album \"Wrapping Paper\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Wrapping Paper {{!}} Debut album by Bassist Vivek Date|url = http://www.sweetwinemusic.com/wrapping-paper.html|website = Vivek Date|accessdate = 2015-10-29|language = en-IN|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304093743/http://www.sweetwinemusic.com/wrapping-paper.html|archive-date = 4 March 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref> The album received a warm response from the audience and a good critique from the reviewers with some tipping it as a gift to the Rock & Roll scene of 2015 in India<ref>{{Cite web|title = Wrapping Paper \u2013 Vivek Date|url = https://artistaloud.wordpress.com/2015/09/21/wrapping-paper-vivek-date/|website = ArtistAloud.com|accessdate = 2015-10-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Hard rock and heavy metal ===\n[[File:Nicotine_(Metal_Band_from_Indore)_playing_at_the_Hard_Rock_Cafe_in_Hyderabad,_India.jpg|thumb|[[Nicotine (band)|Nicotine]] playing at the [[Hard Rock Cafe]], in Hyderabad, India in 2016. The band is widely known for being the pioneers of Metal Music in Central India.]]\n\n===Vedic metal===\nThe heavy metal band M.A.I.D.S (Metal Aliens in Devil's Soul) laid the foundation of heavy metal and rock in South India, Madras in the early 90s. Singaporean band [[Rudra (band)|Rudra]] initially got their worldwide push from major heavy metal label Sonic Wave International. With their style of 'Vedic metal' based around Hindu themes, the band have gained some fame in South East Asia, fusing heavy metal with Indian traditional music, in the vein of Brazil's [[Sepultura]], although they do not use avant-garde instruments such as them. Many international critics from the United States, Germany, and other countries have given the band's albums rave reviews.\n\nSince the genre was pioneered by Rudra in the late 1990s, it has grown in popularity. Bands like Wingz of Vayraag (India), [[Aryadeva]] (Ukraine), Symmetry (Indonesia), Warriors of Peace (India), Asura (India), Advaita (India), The Aryan March (India), [[Bhairav (band)|Bhairav]] (India), Madhavas Rock Band (India), Narasimha (Singapore), Kaliyuga (Singapore), Azrael (Australia), Dying Out Flame (Nepal), Blue River (Sri Lanka), Punarjanma (India), and Kartikeya (Russia) have done pioneering work in the subgenre. Often, along with Vedic lyrics, the music has shades of [[Indian classical music]]. With the introduction of new subgenre of heavy metal, the Vedic-core bands like, Antim-Yuddha, [[Roktobeej]] are contributing to the rising Indian underground rock culture. The definitive album of this genre [[Rudra (band)|Rudra]]\u2019s [[The Aryan Crusade]] (2001). In addition, India has produced many heavy metal bands that combine ethnic-[[folk music]] with various forms of heavy metal to create other [[folk metal]] bands. Indian rock has been influenced by some notable cultural trends, and has in turn produced influences of its own. Indian musicians have also collaborated with other musicians from across the globe.\n\n====Heavy metal====\n\nMillennium was formed in 1988 as one of the first Indian metal bands, and it laid the foundation for the Indian heavy metal scene. [[Demonic Resurrection]] laid the foundation for Indian extreme metal early in 2000 when extreme metal in India was a scarce minority, since then it has garnered popularity especially in the underground scene and spawned many bands such as Corroded Dreams, Escher's Knot, Crypted, Bestial Murder, and some bands have adapted to black metal driven sound with a rawer sound and [[Satanism|satanic]] lyrics. Bands such as Dark Desolation from Bengaluru and [[Fortified Destruction]] from Chennai have gone down that path. Many prolific extreme metal bands have spawned from the Chennai local scenes like Siva from [[Crypted]], Abhijit Rao from Escher's Knot, Vyas \"Hex\" Manalan from Fortified Destruction who are all frontmen of their respective bands and all known for their extreme vocal capabilities and the addition of guitar in the case of Hex. With many extreme metal bands from other countries, such as Behemoth, Gojira, and Cradle of Filth are setting foot on the India. Some of the most popular heavy metal bands in India are Undying INC, Zygnema, Bhayanak Maut, Albatros, Noiseware, Abraxas, Devoid, Sceptre, Kryptos, The Down Troddence, Crypted, Halakuah, Inner Sanctum, Scribe, and Cosmic Infusion. New emerging bands from India are now focused on spreading heavy metal and extreme metal music to the masses; there are frequent heavy metal gigs across India; though it is a niche in the genre, more and more people are becoming aware of the genre and bands like Orcus, Carnage INC, Primitiv, Eternal Returns, Killchain to name a few. From Central India, [[Nicotine (Metal band)|Nicotine]], a band based in [[Indore]], is widely credited of being the one of the pioneers of [[heavy metal music]] in the region. In recent years, the a wave of Indian extreme metal bands are growing in popularity with bands like [[Brazen Molok]], being the flag bearer of this new wave.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dnasyndication.com/dna/article/DNIND3926|title=Does Indore have the mettle for metal?|work=dnasyndication.com|accessdate=18 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506213402/http://dnasyndication.com/dna/article/DNIND3926|archive-date=6 May 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.educationinsider.net/detail_news.php?id=731|title=Metal mania|work=educationinsider.net|accessdate=18 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315111040/http://www.educationinsider.net/detail_news.php?id=731|archive-date=15 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaper.dnaindia.com/story.aspx?id=42518&boxid=63886&ed_date=2014-01-06&ed_code=820076&ed_page=1|title=Indore has a bandtastic time!|work=dnaindia.com|accessdate=18 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305021734/http://epaper.dnaindia.com/story.aspx?id=42518&boxid=63886&ed_date=2014-01-06&ed_code=820076&ed_page=1|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sinlung.com/2011/01/10-famous-rock-bands-of-india.html|title=The 10 Famous Rock Bands of India - Sinlung|work=sinlung.com|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaonline.in/About/Culture/Best-Rock-Bands-In-India.html|title=Best Rock Bands In India|work=indiaonline.in|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkthroughindia.com/hot-trends/the-10-famous-rock-bands-of-india/|title=The 10 Famous Rock Bands of India|work=walkthroughindia.com|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youthkiawaaz.com/2013/07/almost-there-6-awesome-indian-music-bands-to-look-forward-to/|title=Almost There: 6 Awesome Indian Music Bands To Look Forward To|work=Youth Ki Awaaz|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.witty9.com/list-of-top-10-famous-rock-bands-who-gave-a-new-defination-to-the-music/|title=# 12 Prominent Indian Rock Bands Who Gave a New Definition To The Music .|work=Witty9|accessdate=18 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913222425/http://www.witty9.com/list-of-top-10-famous-rock-bands-who-gave-a-new-defination-to-the-music/|archive-date=13 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://travel.india.com/articles/12-cities-home-awesome-bands-probably-dint-know/|title=12 Cities That are Home to Awesome Bands and You Probably Din't Know It!|work=Travel India|accessdate=18 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041806/http://travel.india.com/articles/12-cities-home-awesome-bands-probably-dint-know/|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toplisthub.com/top-10-rock-bands-in-india/|title=Top 10 Rock Bands in India|author=Neelima K|work=Top List Hub|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaper.dnaindia.com/epapermain.aspx?pgNo=4&edcode=820076&eddate=2013-6-26|title=DNA E-Paper - Daily News & Analysis -Mumbai,India|work=dnaindia.com|accessdate=18 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319152138/http://epaper.dnaindia.com/epapermain.aspx?pgNo=4&edcode=820076&eddate=2013-6-26|archive-date=19 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Regional music scenes ==\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{or section|date=April 2019}}\n{{Cleanup|date=September 2019|reason=[[WP:LAUNDRY]]; excessively detailed|section}}\n}}\nMany cities and regions have produced collections of bands large enough to be classified as a scene within Indian rock.\n[[Shillong]], [[Chennai]], [[Mumbai]] and [[Bangalore]] have long been one of the principal founts of Indian rock and continues to produce bands regularly.<ref>[http://www.musicmalt.com/2015/04/16-rock-bands-from-north-east-india.html 16 Rock Bands from North-East India you don't want to miss], ''Music Malt''</ref>\n\n=== Bangalore scene ===\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = vertical\n | footer    = Heavy Metal group [[Iron Maiden]] performing live in Bangalore (top) and [[Kryptos (band)|Kryptos]] performing at Harley Rock Riders Season III. (bottom)\n | image1    = Ironmaiden Bangalore RNI.jpg\n | width1    = 210\n | image2    = Kryptos at Harley Rock Riders Season III in Bangalore, India (Jim Ankan Deka photography).jpg\n | width2    = 210\n}}\nThe dominant music genres in urban [[Bangalore]] are rock and metal music. All subgenres of rock, varying from classic rock n' roll to extreme metal can be heard in [[Bangalore]]. The underground scenario in Bangalore is highly acclaimed, and though Shillong is called the Rock/Metal capital of India but that day is not far when Bangalore can take the fame away from Shillong. Notable bands from Bangalore include Eunoia Soulscape, Maun, [[Manoj George|ManojGeorge4Strings]], [[Raghu Dixit Project]], Divine Raaga, Arha, Thermal and a quarter (TAAQ), [[Girish and The Chronicles]] (GATC), [[Kryptos (band)|Kryptos]], [[The Down Troddence|The Down troddence(TDT)]] (originally from Kannur, Kerala), Culminant, Dark Light, Alternative Ties, Neolithic Silence, Abandoned Agony, [[Theorized (band)|Theorized]], [[SvarAmrita (band)|SvarAmrita]], [[Inner Sanctum (band)|Inner Sanctum]], [[Agam (band)|Agam]], Slain, Clown With a Frown, allegro fudge, Black Sun, [[All the Fat Children]], J3, The Bicycle Days, Pralayh, The Usual Suspects, Final Surrender,Crash TV, Eccentric Pendulum, Crossroads, Orchid, Hungry(band), [https://www.facebook.com/BufferZoneTheBand Buffer Zone], Perfect Strangers, Ek, [[Swarathma]], [[Eastern Fare]] and Galeej Gurus. [[Rock 'n India]], Great Indian Rock and more recently Deccan Rock are the primitive rock festivals in India. Bangalore was also the first city in India where internationally popular rock groups [[Opeth]], [[Iron Maiden]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[Scorpions (band)|Scorpions]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Aerosmith]], [[Elton John]], [[Deep Purple]], [[Metallica]], [[Slayer]], [[Megadeth]], among various other heavy metal groups performed live for the first time in India.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.efi-news.com/2011/08/metallica-in-india.html |title=Metallica in India - EF News International |access-date=16 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509054908/http://www.efi-news.com/2011/08/metallica-in-india.html |archive-date=9 May 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nRecent restrictions on live music in Bangalore's bars has affected the rock music culture of the city but is slowly recovering with pubs like Kyra, B Flat and Legends of Rock hosting more live bands.<ref>[http://www.hindu.com/2008/08/04/stories/2008080461100400.htm Karnataka \u2013 The Hindu]</ref> Festivals like [[Rock 'n India]], Rock Ethos, Great Indian Rock and more recently Wrath Fest at Raipur and Deccan Rock continue to take place in Bangalore, a popular destination for international acts like [[Iron Maiden]], [[Lamb of God (band)|Lamb of God]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[Scorpions (band)|Scorpions]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Aerosmith]], [[Megadeth]], [[Elton John]], [[Metallica]] and [[Deep Purple]].\n\n=== Chennai scene ===\nAnother major Indian rock festival is the June Rock Out, organised by the Unwind Centre in [[Adyar (Tamil Nadu)|Adyar]], [[Chennai]].\nThere are also other smaller rock/metal festivals happening regularly in Bangalore and Chennai, like \"Euphony\", the \"September Underground\", \"Last Band Standing\", and the weekly \"Live 101.\" The Bands Association of Chennai (BAC) is an organisation which actively promotes the cause of original music by Chennai bands such as Requiem Injustice, Grasshopper Green and Namma Ooru Boy Band (NOBB).\n\n=== Delhi scene ===\n[[Delhi]]'s music circuit has seen its share of ups and downs, but has held on largely due to the local presence of ''[[Rock Street Journal]]''. Delhi being the operational home of the Allahabad-based magazine, local bands have benefited by the proximity to India's first dedicated to stories and features based around rock and metal. The Great Indian Rock festival was mostly held in Delhi, now foraying into [[Kolkata]], [[Mumbai]] and [[Bangalore]], [[North-East India]] and [[Pune]] has exposed the upcoming musicians of India to a wider variety of musicians.<ref>[http://gnews.com/music-education-is-hitting-the-high-notes-in-bangalore-03200933095517/ Bangalore - G-News] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101124002108/http://gnews.com/music-education-is-hitting-the-high-notes-in-bangalore-03200933095517/ |date=24 November 2010 }}</ref> Notable bands from Delhi include Orange Street, [[Parikrama (band)|Parikrama]], Hundred Octane, [[Indian Ocean (band)|Indian Ocean]], [[Them Clones]], [[Menwhopause]], [[Bandish]], [[Advaita]], Faridkot, [[AntarDhvani]], [[Punkh]],<ref>http://www.mtv.com/artists/punkh/</ref><ref>http://www.nme.in/punkh-set-to-soar-with-new-album/</ref> [[Midival Punditz]], [[Undying Inc.]], [[Mrigya (band)|Mrigya]], [[Guillotine (band)|Guillotine]], [[The Iyer Project (band)]].\n\n=== Hyderabad scene ===\nIn Hyderabad bands like Sledge, Wreckage, Native Tongue has paved for upcoming bands by taking it to the nationals. They have won major rock and metal competitions such as campus rock idols 2004, 2005 and 2006 and headlining gigs across all major IT festivals in India taking charge of the Indian rock scene.\n\n=== Indore scene ===\n[[File:Nicotine Metal Band Indore.jpg|thumb|[[Nicotine (band)|Nicotine]] playing at 'Pedal To The Metal', TDS, Indore, India in 2014.]]\n\nThe [[Indore]] scene (in Central India) initially ignored by the mainstream Rock/Metal fraternity has been emerging as the 'Dark Horse' of Indian Rock and Metal Scene since the mid-2000s. Though [[Metal]] dominates the scene, the city has produced bands from all kinds of the genre (Classic Rock, Alternative, Hard Rock, Death Metal).\n\n[[Nicotine (band)]] which was formed in December 2006, is widely credited for being the pioneers of Metal music, not just in the Indore but in Central India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaper.dnaindia.com/story.aspx?id=27256&boxid=11558&ed_date=2013-06-26&ed_code=820076&ed_page=4|title=All hail the headbangers, They are in Indore's Hall of Fame|work=DNA E-Paper, Daily News & Analysis, Mumbai, India, dnaindia.com|accessdate=26 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320055640/http://epaper.dnaindia.com/story.aspx?id=27256&boxid=11558&ed_date=2013-06-26&ed_code=820076&ed_page=4|archive-date=20 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkthroughindia.com/hot-trends/the-10-famous-rock-bands-of-india/|title=The 10 Famous Rock Bands of India|work=walkthroughindia.com|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liveinstyle.com/nightlife/party-calendar/thursday-live-metal-mania-feat-dirge-and-nicotine-hard-rock-cafe-hyderabad|title=Metal Mania feat Nicotine & Dirge at Hard Rock Cafe, Hyderabad|work=liveinstyle.com|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trendingtop5.com/interview-nicotine-top-metal-rock-band-india/|title=An interview with Nicotine, One of the top Metal bands of India|work=trendingtop5.com|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref>\nZero Gravity, another Metal band from the city, released their full-length album called 'Holocaust Awaits' in 2014.<ref>https://www.discogs.com/Zero-Gravity-Holocaust-Awaits-/release/7431887</ref>\n\n[[Nicotine (band)|Nicotine]], Grim Reapers and Bliss are the only 3 bands to have qualified from the Central Zone of the 'Campus Rock Idols' Competition.\nCeaseless Juncture and Perception as Reality are some of the existing active bands. There were bands like Avalanche, Auxiliary Triangle, Assault, Overdrive, Blindfolds which are now disbanded but won competitions outside the city.\nThough it is an independent scene, major bands from outside the city like BLAKC, Zygnema, [[Demonic Resurrection]], Undying Inc, Albatross, etc. have performed in Indore.\n\n=== Kerala scene ===\nThe state of Kerala gave India one of the first and successful rock bands ever - [[13AD (band)|13 A.D]].\nKerala has produced some of the finest bands and musicians : [[Motherjane]], [[Avial (band)|Avial]], [[The Down Troddence]], [[Thaikkudam Bridge]], [[Evergreen (band)|Evergreen]], [[Manoj George|ManojGeorge4Strings]], [[Sumit (Guitarist)]], [[Sanjeev Thomas (Guitarist)]], [[Baiju Dharmajan]], [[Rex Vijayan]] to name a few.<ref>[[Avial (band)|Avial]]</ref>\n\n=== Calcutta Scene ===\n{{See also|Rock music of West Bengal}}\nBands from Kolkata that pioneered original music in English include [[Krosswindz]], Cassini's Division, Skinny Alley, The Supersonics, [[Five Little Indians]],and Span. There is also a massive regional rock scene and also some bands formed locally with international views in Kolkata that includes bands like [[Fossils (band)|Fossils]], [[Cactus (Indian band)|Cactus]], [[Chandrabindoo (band)|Chandrabindoo]], [[Krosswindz]], [[Bhoomi (band)|Bhoomi]], [[Lakkhichhara (band)|Lakkhichhara]], [[Alienz]], [[Cross Theory - India (Indian Band)|Cross Theory - India]], [[Fakira (band)|Fakira]], [[AGNISH (band)|AGNISH]], [[PRITHIBI (band)|PRITHIBI]], [[METALLOIDZ - INDIA (India band)|METALLOIDZ - INDIA]].\n\nIn [[Calcutta]], the underground Metal Bands organise an Event called The Pit at Tapan Theatre in Kalighat. In 2009, 3 editions of The Pit were successfully organised. It is being seen now that more events are being organised, like the metal events held by KOSMA ( Kolkata Old School Metal Association). Other fests include 'Abomination', 'Order Of The Heretical Trident Festival', 'Kolkata Open Air'. [[Bengali language|Bengali]] metal gigs attract huge crowds and are sponsored by various organisations. Kolkata also hosts an annual musical festival, The NH7 Weekender since 2013.<ref>[http://www.telegraphindia.com/1090430/jsp/entertainment/story_10894415.jsp The Telegraph \u2013 Calcutta]</ref>\n\n[[Moheener Ghoraguli]], a [[Bengali language|Bengali]] independent music group from [[Kolkata]], is arguably India's and [[Bengal]]'s first popular rock band.<ref>{{cite news |title=Song of the stallion|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-06-21/kolkata/28166934_1_composers-song-author-and-friend |work= The Times of India|date=21 June 2009 }}</ref><ref>[[Moheener Ghoraguli]]</ref>\n\n=== Mumbai scene ===\n{{multiple image\n | align     = left\n | direction = vertical\n | footer    = [[Bhayanak Maut]] performing at the 2010 Independence Rock XXV (top) and [[Demonic Resurrection]] performing live at Brutal Assault 2010. (bottom)\n | image1    = Bhayanak-Maut.jpg\n | width1    = 200\n | image2    = Demonic Resurrection.jpg\n | width2    = 200\n}}\nSome of the most notable contemporary rock bands from Mumbai are [[Pentagram (Indian band)|Pentagram]], Tough on Tobacco, [[Bhayanak Maut]], [[Demonic Resurrection]], Split, Sridhar/Thayil, [[Scribe (band)|Scribe]], and Goddess Gagged. The recent reunion of Indian rock pioneers [[Indus Creed]] was received with great enthusiasm,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/index.aspx?page=article&sectid=135&contentid=2010100520101005023954211a4c8f328 |title=Archived copy |access-date=28 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714133216/http://www.mumbaimirror.com/index.aspx?page=article&sectid=135&contentid=2010100520101005023954211a4c8f328 |archive-date=14 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> especially with regard to their plans to produce a new album in 2011.\n\nMumbai's longest-running festival has been the [[Independence Rock Festival]]. 2010 saw I-Rock, as it is popularly known, celebrate its 25th year. Independence Rock XXV paid tribute to the city that has hosted the festival by featuring a spate of local bands. The recently reunited Indus Creed headlined the festival, which included other local favourites like Bhayanak Maut, Scribe, Demonic Resurrection and Pralay, as well as stalwart musicians like Dhruv Ghanekar, Warren Mendonsa, Loy Mendonsa, Ehsaan Noorani, Farhad Wadia (the festival's founder and promoter), Ravi Iyer, Chandresh Kudwa, Shazneen Arethna and Sidd Coutto.\n\n=== Pune scene ===\nA relatively recent entry into the Indian Rock circuit is the city of Pune has been the home of bands over the years and off late there has been a new surge with notable genre-defining acts like Silver, Strange Brew, Jazz Mates, Nothing as Now and more. The live music scene of the twin cities Mumbai and Pune has been on a steep rise since 2005 with major International acts like [[Meshuggah]], [[Tesseract (band)|Tesseract]], [[Satyricon (band)|Satyricon]], Freak Kitchen, [[Sahg]]. Pune plays host to an annual musical festival, The NH7 Weekender, which takes place in the month of November and showcases international (mostly British) acts like [[Imogen Heap]], [[The Magic Numbers]], [[Asian Dub Foundation]] and [[Reverend Soundsystem]] to name a few.\n\n=== Ranchi scene ===\n[[File:John receiving the Best Drummer award at Hornbill Festival in 2017..jpg|thumb|right|[[Highway 69 (band) | Highway 69's drummer]] receiving the Best Drummer award from [[Uday Benegal]] at Hornbill International Rock Contest 2017 in [[Nagaland]].]]\nHailing from a small place quite unknown to the rest of the country, the bands of Ranchi from Jharkhand state had to face discrimination and hardships. Over the years, this city has produced some of the finest rock and metal music bands but they have always gone unnoticed because of being from a small town. In the 1990s, bands like Genesis, Kaalmantra and Sparsh<ref name=\"The Times of India for 'Sparsh'\">{{cite web |title=Ranchi rock band to perform today|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/pune/Ranchi-rock-band-to-perform-today/articleshow/2639039.cms|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref> have been considered as the pioneers to rock and metal music in Jharkhand. The city has had various music festivals being organized since the 2000s and a few of them are still organized today with the biggest one being [[Thunderstrock Festival]]<ref name=\"The Telegraph for 'Thunderstrock Festival'\">{{cite web |title=Rock concert next month|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/jharkhand/rock-concert-next-month/cid/1310535|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref> and other notable festivals are like Rock Jatra and Rhapsody. The band Sparsh was aired live on CNN-IBN<ref name=\"YouTube for 'Sparsh'\">{{cite web |title=Sparsh on CNN-IBN|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4Ckosjl-7iw|publisher=YouTube}}</ref> cheering up for the [[India national cricket team]] during the [[2011 Cricket World Cup]]. The band 4 Degrees of Freedom<ref name=\"Rolling Stones India for HIRC 2013\">{{cite web |title=Hornbill International Rock Contest 2013|url=https://rollingstoneindia.com/review-hornbill-international-rock-contest-2013/|publisher=Rolling Stones India}}</ref> were the finalists of Hornbill International Rock Contest 2013, followed by [[Highway 69 (band)]] being twice the finalists at Hornbill International Rock Contest for 2017, 2018 along with their drummer winning the best drummer award in 2017 and Vikrit and Existence also being the finalists in 2018. The bands of Ranchi have been touring and performing across the country with currently [[Highway 69 (band)]] being the most notable one as it has performed extensively all over the country and has evolved with a huge fan base, followed by other bands like Reciprocal<ref name=\"The Avenue Mail\">{{cite web |title=Local rock bands ready to rock for voters\u2019 awareness in Ranchi|url=https://www.avenuemail.in/jamshedpur/local-rock-bands-ready-to-rock-for-voters-awareness-in-ranchi/132565/|publisher=The Avenue Mail}}</ref>, Existence, Vikrit, Iris 13 etc. Other active and notable bands from the 2010s were Genesis, Kaalmantra, Sparsh, 4 Degrees of Freedom, Conflicting Resonance etc.\n\n== Independent record labels ==\nMainstream record labels in India often ignore rock, with a few exceptions. Album sales range between a few hundred copies to a few thousand. They are rarely, if at all, affiliated to the Indian music industry, and sales are not usually monitored. Songs of Bollywood usually gain more popularity as compared to the songs of bands. This is a huge set back. Bands also fail to sell their songs throughout the country even after making it available to major music stores, this is only due to lack of interest of people in rock bands. There are only a few bands that have become successful in selling their songs throughout the country. People who enjoy rock get the songs of their favorite bands, just by a click from any music website (sometimes their songs are uploaded by website administrators just after the day of release, this is illegal as per copyright law, but even then no action is taken). Hence, overall sales become less than expected. Bands in India mostly perform live shows with low priced tickets (as low as Rs. 100 or even less). Probably, the growing and the upcoming generation will have interest in Indian Rock and Metal. But care has to be taken to retain the copyright of the music.\n\nThe future looks encouraging thanks to entities such as Green Ozone, [[DogmaTone]] Records, [[Cochym]] and [[Eastern Fare Music Foundation]], [[Infestdead Records]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tntmagazine.in/tnt-y-news/northeast-gets-its-first-metal-label-signs-savage-uk/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827041640/http://tntmagazine.in/tnt-y-news/northeast-gets-its-first-metal-label-signs-savage-uk/ |archive-date=27 August 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>http://www.metal-rules.com/metalnews/2012/08/23/india-gets-a-new-metal-label-signs-nwobhm-legend-savage-uk/</ref> that are dedicated to promoting and supporting Indian rock.\n\n==Documentary on Indian rock==\n\nIn 2008, music journalist Abhimanyu Kukreja directed Rockumentary - Becoming of Indian rock that was produced by NewsX and had a national TV release. The documentary is arguably the first of its kind on Indian rock that showcases the evolution of rock music in India starting from the 1960s. The documentary features popular and classic Indian bands like The Great Bear, High, The Great Society, Shiva, Indus Creed, Millennium and Parikrama. The documentary is available for free viewing on YouTube.<ref>{{cite web|title=Documentary by Abhimanyu Kukreja|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XSjSS1Zw58o|publisher=Newsx}}</ref> ''\n\n[[Leaving Home \u2013 the Life & Music of Indian Ocean]]'' (2010) directed by [[Jaideep Varma]] was about fusion rock band, [[Indian Ocean (band)|Indian Ocean]]. Thus it became the first band ever in India to be subject of a documentary.<ref name=ndtv>{{cite web | title = Indian Ocean co-founder Susmit Sen quits band |work= NDTV | url = http://movies.ndtv.com/music/indian-ocean-co-founder-susmit-sen-quits-band-612287 |date=12 June 2013| accessdate = 2014-11-17 }}</ref> At the [[58th National Film Awards]], the documentary went on to win the [[National Film Award for Best Arts/Cultural Film|Award for Best Arts/Cultural Film]].<ref name=\"58thaward\">{{cite web|url=http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm58NFAAward.aspx|title=58th National Film Awards|publisher=[[International Film Festival of India]]|accessdate=29 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414003922/http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm58NFAAward.aspx|archive-date=14 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"58thawardPDF\">{{cite web|url=http://dff.nic.in/2011/58_NFA.pdf|title=58th National Film Awards (PDF)|publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]]|accessdate=29 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Issues faced==\nAn all-girl rock band [[Pragash Band]] from Srinagar, Kashmir decided to call it quits after constant hate mails and death threats on the internet, apart from the severe criticism and opposition from the religious leaders of Kashmir and other hardliner political parties.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Demonic Resurrection]]\n*[[Pin Drop Violence]]\n*[[Kryptos (band)]]\n*[[Nicotine (Metal Band)]]\n*[[Inner Sanctum (band)]]\n*[[Scribe (band)]]\n*[[Rusty Moe]]\n*[[Bhayanak Maut]]\n*[[Asian Underground]]\n*[[Rock music of West Bengal]] popularly known as Bangla rock\n*[[Psychedelic music]]\n*[[Psychedelic rock]]\n*[[Raga rock]]\n*[[The Vinyl Records]]\n*[[Life in a... Metro]]\n*[[Rock On!!]]\n*[[Highway 69 (band)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite web|title=KAAV-MyOPUSRADIO |url=http://www.myopusradio.com/platformnews/article/big-fish-for-october-kaav|accessdate=10 October 2012}}\n* {{cite web|title=KAAV-INDIAN EXPRESS |url=http://epaper.indianexpress.com/50382/Indian-Express/04-August-2012#page/21/3|accessdate=10 October 2012}}\n* {{cite web|title=KAAV-INDIANROCKMP3|url=http://www.indianrockmp3.com/2012/09/24/a-fine-debut-with-a-unique-sound/|accessdate=10 October 2012}}\n* {{cite news|title=KARNATRIIX-THE HINDU|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/music/article3785202.ece|accessdate=10 October 2012 | location=Chennai, India|work=The Hindu|first=Saraswathy|last=Nagarajan|date=17 August 2012}}\n* {{cite web|title=BAIJUDHARMAJAN-Timesofindia|url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=MIRRORNEW&BaseHref=BGMIR/2012/08/07&PageLabel=20&EntityId=Ar01901&ViewMode=HTML|accessdate=10 October 2012}}\n* {{cite news|title=BAIJUDHARMAJAN-THE HINDU|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/music/article3550720.ece|accessdate=10 October 2012 | location=Chennai, India|work=The Hindu|date=20 June 2012}}\n* {{cite web|title=BAIJUDHARMAJAN-ibnlive|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/crossing-over-to-a-new-beginning/261533-60-122.html|accessdate=10 October 2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{dmoz|/Regional/Asia/India/Arts_and_Entertainment/Music/Bands_and_Artists/}}\n\n{{World rock}}\n\n[[Category:Indian rock music| ]]\n", "text_old": " \n{{Distinguish|Raga rock}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2010}}\n{{infobox music genre|name= Indian rock\n|color=black\n|bgcolor=lavender\n|font color=\"blue\"\n|stylistic_origins=[[South Asian]]<br>[[Indian music]]\n|cultural_origins= [[India]], [[Bengal]]\n|instruments=[[Singing|Vocals]], [[Gramophone record|Gramophone]], [[Jazz]], [[Indian musical instruments]], [[Electric guitar]], [[Bass guitar]], [[Drums]], [[Keyboard instrument|Keyboard]], [[Electric sitar]]\n|popularity=India\n|subgenres=\n|regional_scenes=\n|other_topics=\n}}\n{{Indian music|expanded=Genres}}\n\n'''Indian rock''' is a [[music genre]] in [[India]] that incorporates elements of [[Music of India|Indian music]] with [[rock music]], and is often topically India-centric. While India is more often known for its ([[Hindustani classical music|northern]] and [[Carnatic music|southern]]) [[Indian classical music|classical music]], [[filmi]], [[Bollywood music]], [[Indi-pop]], and [[Bhangra (music)|Bhangra]], the Indian rock scene has also produced numerous bands and artists.\n\n==Early history==\nIndia, in the 1950s and 1960s, had a record industry in the Gramophone Company of India (an RCA/HMV/EMI subsidiary), and [[Long playing records|LPs]], [[Extended play|EPs]], and [[45rpm]] records were freely available, including those of [[rock and roll]] acts from the US and Britain, but also of contemporary pioneering Indian rock bands. The president of the firm, [[Bhaskar Menon]] (who later became the President of [[Capitol Records]] in the United States) was the leading promoter of Western pop music in India. Later in 1970, [[Polydor]], the German Label, began an India label distributing rock music.\n\nOf these mid-1960s to early 70s [[Beat music|beat]] groups, as they was then termed, one of the most notable were the [[Mystiks]] from [[Mumbai|Bombay]], the [[Beat-X]] from [[Chennai|Madras]], and the Flintstone from [[Kolkata|Calcutta]], who composed and played both early [[British Invasion]] influenced songs, and post-''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band|Sgt. Pepper]]'' [[hard rock]]. During this period from Delhi there were The Thunderbirds (featuring singer Ashwani Bali), and WAFWOT (also with Ashwani on vocals, with organist Mark Spevak, from the U.S.) These bands played regularly on the Indian university and college music circuits, and some had successful EP and LP releases. Also notable from this period (1964\u20131970) was the female [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]  singer, Usha Iyer, now [[Usha Uthup]], who had successful covers of \"[[Jambalaya (On the Bayou)|Jambalaya]]\" and [[The Kingston Trio]] song, \"Greenback Dollar\". A notable compilation LP titled \"Simla Beat '70\" was released during this period, from a contest of the same name. The winning bands recorded their versions of Western hard rock of the time. This tradition of covering Western rock would continue until the 1980s when it was more common to compose original songs.\n\nThe rock n' roll scene was also closely followed by ''[[The Statesman (India)|Junior Statesman]]'' (or ''JS''), a magazine started in 1965 contemporaneously with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine in the US and [[NME]] in the UK.\n\n{{Listen\n| filename    = \n| title       = \"Ae Naujawan Hai Sab Kuchh Yahan\"\n| description = [[Asha Bhosle]]'s \"Ae Naujawan Hai Sab Kuch Yahan\" from the film ''[[Apradh]]'' (1972)\n| pos         = right\n}}\n\nLike Western rock musicians at the time, Indian musicians also began fusing rock with traditional Indian music from the mid-1960s onwards. Many of these songs were often ''[[filmi]]'' songs produced for popular [[Bollywood]] films, which often overshadowed the country's independent rock scene. Some of the more well known early rock songs (including styles such as [[funk rock]], [[pop rock]], [[psychedelic rock]], [[raga rock]], and [[soft rock]]) from Bollywood films include [[Mohammed Rafi]]'s \"[[Jaan Pehechan Ho]]\" in ''[[Gumnaam]]'' (1965), [[Kishore Kumar]]'s \"O Saathi Re\" in ''[[Muqaddar Ka Sikandar]]'' (1978), and [[Asha Bhosle]] songs such as \"[[Dum Maro Dum (song)|Dum Maro Dum]]\" in ''[[Hare Rama Hare Krishna (1971 film)|Hare Rama Hare Krishna]]'' (1971), \"Ae Naujawan Hai Sab\" in ''[[Apradh]]'' (1972), and \"Yeh Mera Dil Pyar Ka Diwana\" in ''[[Don (1978 film)|Don]]'' (1978).\n\n===Indian influence on Western music===\n{{See also|Raga rock|Psychedelic rock|The Beatles in India}}\n\nIn the 1960s, renowned [[Western world|Western]] acts such as [[The Yardbirds]], [[The Beatles]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[The Doors]] and [[The Byrds]] were notably influenced by [[Indian classical music]] as a way of reinforcing the [[Psychedelic music|psychedelia]] in their music. While [[jazz]] musicians, notably [[John Coltrane]], had ventured into Indian music and spiritualism (see [[Indo jazz]], [[Sitar in jazz]], and [[Jazz in India]]), the influence of Indian classical music on 1960s rock began in earnest with [[George Harrison]]'s [[Ravi Shankar]] inspired [[raga rock]] song \"[[Norwegian Wood (This Bird Has Flown)]]\" in 1965 and The Beatles' very public sojourn with the [[Maharishi Mahesh Yogi]] at his [[ashram]] in [[Rishikesh]] in 1968, following the release of ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' in 1967. Raga rock led to the development of [[psychedelic rock]], which in turn laid the foundations for [[heavy metal music]].\n\nThe Indian rock scene would later give rise to one of the world's most famous rock stars, [[Freddie Mercury]], born Farrokh Bulsara. One of his formative musical influences was the Bollywood singer [[Lata Mangeshkar]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Liam|title=Farrokh Bulsara|url=http://www.time.com/time/asia/2006/heroes/at_bulsara.html|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=28 April 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523230337/http://www.time.com/time/asia/2006/heroes/at_bulsara.html|archivedate=23 May 2011|year=2006}}</ref> He began his music career as a teenager in [[Mumbai|Bombay]] with the rock band, [[The Hectics]], which was founded in 1958 and often performed [[cover version]]s of Western [[rock and roll]] artists such as [[Little Richard]] and [[Cliff Richard]].<ref>{{citation|last=Hodkinson|first=Mark|year=2004|title=Queen: The Early Years|place=London|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=1-84449-012-2|pages=2 & 61}}</ref> After leaving the band in 1962, he moved to England, where he later led the rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]] (formed in 1971), which went on to become one of the world's most famous rock bands.\n\nThe Indian rock scene also gave rise to one of the pioneers of [[disco]] music, [[Biddu]],<ref name=\"metro_biddu\">{{cite web|title=Biddu|author=James Ellis|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/interviews/412-biddu|accessdate=17 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Listener, Volumes 100-101|work=[[The Listener (magazine)|The Listener]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|year=1978|page=216|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6tRBAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=21 June 2011|quote=Tony Palmer knocked off a film account of someone called Biddu (LWT), who appears to have been mad enough to invent disco music.}}</ref> who originally began his career in an Indian rock band called The Trojans. It was India's first English-speaking band,<ref name=\"times_2004\">{{cite web|date=20 August 2004|title=It's a big step from disco to Sanskrit chants, but Biddu has made it|author=Malika Browne|work=[[The Sunday Times]]|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/article471655.ece|accessdate=30 May 2011}}</ref> and found success producing cover versions of [[The Beatles]],<ref name=\"jones_kantonen\">{{cite book|title=Saturday night forever: the story of disco|author=Alan Jones & Jussi Kantonen|publisher=A Cappella Books|year=2000|isbn=1-55652-411-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ok0UAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=7 June 2011}}</ref> [[The Rolling Stones]],<ref name=\"gopal_moorti_99\">{{cite book|title=Global Bollywood: travels of Hindi song and dance|author=Sangita Gopal & Sujata Moorti|publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]]|year=2008|isbn=0-8166-4579-5|page=99|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=19JBf6oDOy0C&pg=PA99|accessdate=7 June 2011}}</ref> [[Trini Lopez]], and other Western hits of the day, in the clubs of [[Bangalore]], [[Kolkata|Calcutta]], and Bombay. After the band broke up, he moved in 1967 to England, where he later found breakthrough success after producing \"[[Kung Fu Fighting]]\" for [[Carl Douglas]].\n\n==1980s and 1990s==\n\nWhile the [[orientalism|orientalist]] trend of the 60s and 70s was by the 80s and 90s largely over, India itself continued to produce bands in various styles of rock music, from soft [[rock and roll]] and [[pop rock]], to [[hard rock]] and [[Heavy metal music|metal]]. In the early 1980s, however, rock was largely overshadowed by [[disco]], which dominated [[Indian pop]] music up until the mid-1980s.\n\nWith the arrival of [[MTV]], tastes rapidly changed, encouraging bands to harden their style and focus more on underground styles such as [[death metal]], [[alternative rock|alternative metal]], and [[progressive rock]]. The 1990s saw the rise of a much larger following of various harder styles for this reason. Bands that had formed in the 80s, such as Rock Machine (who would later be known as [[Indus Creed]]) - (including Mahesh Tinnaikar, Uday Benegal, etc.)...altered their style with the influx of newer techniques and influences from the west. Notable suburban metal-blues bands with 1960s and 1970s metal influences included IIT Powaii based Axecalibre, fronted by Oliver Pinto, Prashant Nair and covered flamboyant guitar-based blues and hardcore metal including ballads. Contemporaries of the time were Easy Meat from Pune and Bands such as Holocaust, Morgue (fronted by vocalist Mrinal Das, Drummer Neeraj Kakoty, Ambar Das and Raju Seal on Twin Attack Guitars, Manas Chowdhury on Bass), Dorian Platonic from Guwahati, Assam, Grassroots Revival, Postmark, The Cannibals, Phoenix,Phynyx and Drixian Empire/Dark Crusader from Manipur. \n\nOthers formed in the 1990s with harder styles influenced by the growing split between popular rock, such as [[Britpop]], alternative styles, such as [[punk rock|punk]], and metal styles, such as [[thrash metal|thrash]]. The Indian subgenre of fusion, which encourages a similar blend of ancient Indian musical traditions with rock music to [[raga rock]], was also carried forward, and is perhaps the most unusual Indian style of rock. Needless to say the rise of Sanskrit Rock Band (The Army of Narasimha Dev) had sprung to instant success in no time, founded by Lead vocalist Biju Gangadharan from ISKCON background, is a Sanskrit scholar and a highly talented Master in composing Sanskrit mantras into modern age rock music. Biju Gangadharan is considered as Sanskrit Rock Guru with a stunning performance in 33 countries up his shoulder. His guitarist, Chandresh Kudwa, is the most successful lead guitarist in India, and his percussionist, Nishadh Chandra, turned out to be the busiest music programmer in Bollywood. It was during this time that [[Palash Sen]]'s Euphoria surfaced in the Indian scene as a straight ahead English rock band. The band later started writing in Hindi, and gave birth to what is now known as \"Hindi Rock\". Euphoria went on to become India's most popular, successful and commercially accepted Independent act.\n\n==2000s==\n\nThe current Indian rock scene has a larger following than ever (although it is still marginalized compared to Indian film music, particularly the [[filmi]] soundtracks of [[Bollywood]]) and may soon become recognized in the international arena, as various South American and Japanese bands have become. Recent entries into the rock music scene are increasingly becoming comparable in their production quality to Western bands, and have been compared favorably to other internationally recognized acts. Now digital technology is making it easier than ever for these bands to distribute and sell their music. Some British bands of South Asian origin, such as [[Swami (band)|Swami]] have, like their [[hip-hop]] counterparts, tried to enter the Indian market in addition to maintaining the traditional fanbase of non-resident Indians in United Kingdom, [[Indo-Canadians|Canada]] and the [[Indian American|United States]]. Others, such as [[Rudra (band)|Rudra]], have emerged from Indian communities in other Asian countries. Progress is certain for the Indian rock scene with the advent of entities that support this genre. [[Rock Street Journal]] and Rolling Stone India<ref>{{cite web|title=Rolling stone|url=http://rollingstoneindia.com/|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> are the two major publications that have been promoting Indian rock bands. The scene has also been transformed by the online medium, and the subsequent rise of a number of online portals promoting Indian rock, most notably the indie music website NH7,<ref>{{cite web|title=NH7 Radio|url=http://nh7.in/|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> Headbangers India,<ref>{{cite web|title=HeadBangers India|url=http://www.headbangers.in/|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> IndianMusicMug,<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with UFO\u2019s guitarist Vinnie Moore|url=http://indianmusicmug.com/|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> Unholy Maunder, IndianMusicRevolution, Indian Metal Scene etc.<ref>{{cite web|title=IMR|url=http://www.indianmusicrevolution.com/|accessdate=6 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105043221/http://indianmusicrevolution.com/|archive-date=5 January 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> and Metal Spree.\n\n== Sub-genres ==\n\n=== Raga rock ===\n{{Main article|Raga rock}}\n{{See also|Psychedelic rock}}\n\nIn the West, some groups, such as [[The Beatles]], traveled to India and incorporated aspects of Indian music, especially classical instruments such as the [[sitar]], into their music, often as a way of conjuring [[Psychedelic music|psychedelic]] 'Eastern' feelings. The term for this was [[raga rock]], and examples of it are [[The Beatles]] \"[[Love You To]]\", \"[[The Inner Light (song)|The Inner Light]]\",\"[[Across the Universe]]\",\"[[Norwegian Wood (This Bird Has Flown)]]\", \"[[Tomorrow Never Knows]]\", \"[[Strawberry Fields Forever]]\" and \"[[Within You Without You]]\"; [[The Rolling Stones]]' \"[[Paint it, Black]]\"; [[The Kinks]]' \"Fancy\"; [[The Doors]]' \"[[The End (The Doors song)|The End]]\" and [[The Byrds]]' \"[[Eight Miles High]]\". A number of prolific Indian classical musicians such as [[Ravi Shankar]] aligned themselves with this trend, collaborating with Western artists. Indian bands themselves mainly covered early rock songs by pioneers of rock and roll in the United Kingdom and [[United States|America]], and only achieved recognition in popular culture by supporting film scores and Indian pop.\n\n=== Indian fusion ===\n{{main article|Indian fusion}}\n\nAn Indian subgenre of rock exists that focuses on blending traditional Indian styles of music with rock music. The term for non-Indian bands using Indian instrumentals and vocal in rock is [[raga rock]]. However, Indian fusion also encompasses attempts by Indian pop musicians and film composers to incorporate rock music into their work, starting in the 70s with film scores like those of the [[Amitabh Bachchan]] classics. The [[Brown Indian Band]] features accomplished Indian classical musicians in concert with jazz virtuosos. More recently the multi-cultural British band [[Botown]] have taken elements of Bollywood and fused them with soul and funk to great success. The New Delhi Based Band 'Ojapali' is also doing a lots of experiments with Electronica Fusion music and Folk music of the Assam Region.\nThe Kochi-based band [[Motherjane]] typifies bands producing this genre of music. [[Motherjane]] guitarist [[Baiju Dharmajan]] is a pioneer of introducing the guitar music style known as carnatic shredding. Bangalore based carnatic rock band [[Agam (band)|Agam]] and fusion rock outfit Divine Raaga, Kaav, Veenar are other examples of mature songmakers in the country.<ref>[http://www.musicmalt.com/2011/12/eastern-fare-rocks-trinity-guild-hall.html Bangalore - Music Malt]</ref>\nKarnatriix is another band which has defined a new genre of fusion music labelled 'New-age World music'. Their ever-evolving sound today registers as ideally in sync with the 21st century's pan-cultural landscape. The name 'KARNATRIIX' which is a word play, meaning 'Aural Trickery', openly defines their music. Mellifluous melodies and sophisticated phrases deep-rooted in Blues music with an Indian Classical touch, combined with raw percussion and electronically produced subtle beats, voices and effects, form the core essence of the Karnatriix's musical nature. Indian Guitarist [[Kapil Srivastava]] composed Rock and Raga Fusion music in his Indian Guitaroo Volume 1.<ref>{{cite news|title=ZeeNews|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/musicindia/kapil-srivastava-cuts-his-new-album-indian-guitaroo_91243.html|accessdate=5 February 2015|newspaper=ZeeNews}}</ref>. [[The_Iyer_Project_(band)|The Iyer Project]] is another Delhi based band that blends Carnatic style vocals and guitar playing influenced by Baiju Dharmajan and [[R. Prasanna]] with rock and roll and progressive rock.\n\n=== Indian funk ===\nIndian [[funk]] is a loose term describing the style of rock and roll which is sometimes blurred into the realms of pop and other genres. Whereas Indian fusion may only incorporate Indian styles into rock, or rock into Indian forms of music, Indian funk can be broadly defined as what rap-metal is to heavy metal - an infusion of elements from rap, reggae, pop and dance genres that some might consider to not be 'true' rock. Groups originating in South Asian communities in Western countries like Britain are noted for this style, with bands such as [[Swami (band)|Swami]] and [[Asian Dub Foundation]] using elements of [[UK garage]], [[Bhangra (music)|UK bhangra]] and [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]], such as synthesizers, rap vocals and [[phonograph|turntables]]. Also based in the UK, [[Botown]] take an approach inspired by [[Funkadelic]] with a large lineup of live musicians to blend Bollywood music with [[Soul music|soul]] and [[funk]]. Few rock bands such as Silent Echo (Delhi) and Psycho Frequency (Delhi) use a wide range of samples and mechanically evolved sounds. [https://web.archive.org/web/20160217145035/http://www.swastiktheband.com/ Swastik The Band],<ref>https://www.facebook.com/swastiktheband</ref> founded in 2005 ([[Chandigarh]] Based band) is upcoming band which brings the blend of [[Hindustani Culture]] and the core essence of [[Culture of India|Indian]] culture twined with various other cultures, Swastik the band aims to designing [[Indian music]] on western rhythms with a pinch of [[Folk music|Folk]] And [[Sufi Music]] to add flavor to their compositions. Rohit Joshi, Founder and the Lead Guitars/vocals of Swastik the band believes on lines by [[John Green (author)|John Green]] \"Some people have lives; some people have music\".\n\n=== Rock and roll ===\n[[File:Hundred Octane unplugged- live in Hard Rock Cafe, Mumbai.jpg|thumb|200px|Hundred Octane performing at [[Hard Rock Cafe]] in Mumbai]]\nIndia has produced many rock bands, some of whom have made it into mainstream Indian music and achieved some international recognition.\nRLC66 one of the upcoming acts from Mumbai trying to combine various genres from western music. Their main influences are Porcupine Tree, Tool, Dream Theater. The song \"Abrupt\" is earning some good number of fans in Mumbai underground scene. Indian Guitar Player [[Kapil Srivastava]] has composed Rock and Roll fusion in his Indian Guitaroo Volume 2.<ref>{{cite news|title=RadioandMusic|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/content/editorial/news-releases/indian-guitaroo-album-vol-2-release-kapil-srivastava|accessdate=5 February 2015|newspaper=RnMNewsDesk}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Mumbai based Rock & Roll Bassist [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304122017/http://www.sweetwinemusic.com/vivekdate.html Vivek Date] released his Rock & Roll Album \"Wrapping Paper\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Wrapping Paper {{!}} Debut album by Bassist Vivek Date|url = http://www.sweetwinemusic.com/wrapping-paper.html|website = Vivek Date|accessdate = 2015-10-29|language = en-IN|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304093743/http://www.sweetwinemusic.com/wrapping-paper.html|archive-date = 4 March 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref> The album received a warm response from the audience and a good critique from the reviewers with some tipping it as a gift to the Rock & Roll scene of 2015 in India<ref>{{Cite web|title = Wrapping Paper \u2013 Vivek Date|url = https://artistaloud.wordpress.com/2015/09/21/wrapping-paper-vivek-date/|website = ArtistAloud.com|accessdate = 2015-10-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Hard rock and heavy metal ===\n[[File:Nicotine_(Metal_Band_from_Indore)_playing_at_the_Hard_Rock_Cafe_in_Hyderabad,_India.jpg|thumb|[[Nicotine (band)|Nicotine]] playing at the [[Hard Rock Cafe]], in Hyderabad, India in 2016. The band is widely known for being the pioneers of Metal Music in Central India.]]\n\n===Vedic metal===\nThe heavy metal band M.A.I.D.S (Metal Aliens in Devil's Soul) laid the foundation of heavy metal and rock in South India, Madras in the early 90s. Singaporean band [[Rudra (band)|Rudra]] initially got their worldwide push from major heavy metal label Sonic Wave International. With their style of 'Vedic metal' based around Hindu themes, the band have gained some fame in South East Asia, fusing heavy metal with Indian traditional music, in the vein of Brazil's [[Sepultura]], although they do not use avant-garde instruments such as them. Many international critics from the United States, Germany, and other countries have given the band's albums rave reviews.\n\nSince the genre was pioneered by Rudra in the late 1990s, it has grown in popularity. Bands like Wingz of Vayraag (India), [[Aryadeva]] (Ukraine), Symmetry (Indonesia), Warriors of Peace (India), Asura (India), Advaita (India), The Aryan March (India), [[Bhairav (band)|Bhairav]] (India), Madhavas Rock Band (India), Narasimha (Singapore), Kaliyuga (Singapore), Azrael (Australia), Dying Out Flame (Nepal), Blue River (Sri Lanka), Punarjanma (India), and Kartikeya (Russia) have done pioneering work in the subgenre. Often, along with Vedic lyrics, the music has shades of [[Indian classical music]]. With the introduction of new subgenre of heavy metal, the Vedic-core bands like, Antim-Yuddha, [[Roktobeej]] are contributing to the rising Indian underground rock culture. The definitive album of this genre [[Rudra (band)|Rudra]]\u2019s [[The Aryan Crusade]] (2001). In addition, India has produced many heavy metal bands that combine ethnic-[[folk music]] with various forms of heavy metal to create other [[folk metal]] bands. Indian rock has been influenced by some notable cultural trends, and has in turn produced influences of its own. Indian musicians have also collaborated with other musicians from across the globe.\n\n====Heavy metal====\n\nMillennium was formed in 1988 as one of the first Indian metal bands, and it laid the foundation for the Indian heavy metal scene. [[Demonic Resurrection]] laid the foundation for Indian extreme metal early in 2000 when extreme metal in India was a scarce minority, since then it has garnered popularity especially in the underground scene and spawned many bands such as Corroded Dreams, Escher's Knot, Crypted, Bestial Murder, and some bands have adapted to black metal driven sound with a rawer sound and [[Satanism|satanic]] lyrics. Bands such as Dark Desolation from Bengaluru and [[Fortified Destruction]] from Chennai have gone down that path. Many prolific extreme metal bands have spawned from the Chennai local scenes like Siva from [[Crypted]], Abhijit Rao from Escher's Knot, Vyas \"Hex\" Manalan from Fortified Destruction who are all frontmen of their respective bands and all known for their extreme vocal capabilities and the addition of guitar in the case of Hex. With many extreme metal bands from other countries, such as Behemoth, Gojira, and Cradle of Filth are setting foot on the India. Some of the most popular heavy metal bands in India are Undying INC, Zygnema, Bhayanak Maut, Albatros, Noiseware, Abraxas, Devoid, Sceptre, Kryptos, The Down Troddence, Crypted, Halakuah, Inner Sanctum, Scribe, and Cosmic Infusion. New emerging bands from India are now focused on spreading heavy metal and extreme metal music to the masses; there are frequent heavy metal gigs across India; though it is a niche in the genre, more and more people are becoming aware of the genre and bands like Orcus, Carnage INC, Primitiv, Eternal Returns, Killchain to name a few. From Central India, [[Nicotine (Metal band)|Nicotine]], a band based in [[Indore]], is widely credited of being the one of the pioneers of [[heavy metal music]] in the region. In recent years, the a wave of Indian extreme metal bands are growing in popularity with bands like [[Brazen Molok]], being the flag bearer of this new wave.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dnasyndication.com/dna/article/DNIND3926|title=Does Indore have the mettle for metal?|work=dnasyndication.com|accessdate=18 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506213402/http://dnasyndication.com/dna/article/DNIND3926|archive-date=6 May 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.educationinsider.net/detail_news.php?id=731|title=Metal mania|work=educationinsider.net|accessdate=18 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315111040/http://www.educationinsider.net/detail_news.php?id=731|archive-date=15 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaper.dnaindia.com/story.aspx?id=42518&boxid=63886&ed_date=2014-01-06&ed_code=820076&ed_page=1|title=Indore has a bandtastic time!|work=dnaindia.com|accessdate=18 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305021734/http://epaper.dnaindia.com/story.aspx?id=42518&boxid=63886&ed_date=2014-01-06&ed_code=820076&ed_page=1|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sinlung.com/2011/01/10-famous-rock-bands-of-india.html|title=The 10 Famous Rock Bands of India - Sinlung|work=sinlung.com|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaonline.in/About/Culture/Best-Rock-Bands-In-India.html|title=Best Rock Bands In India|work=indiaonline.in|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkthroughindia.com/hot-trends/the-10-famous-rock-bands-of-india/|title=The 10 Famous Rock Bands of India|work=walkthroughindia.com|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youthkiawaaz.com/2013/07/almost-there-6-awesome-indian-music-bands-to-look-forward-to/|title=Almost There: 6 Awesome Indian Music Bands To Look Forward To|work=Youth Ki Awaaz|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.witty9.com/list-of-top-10-famous-rock-bands-who-gave-a-new-defination-to-the-music/|title=# 12 Prominent Indian Rock Bands Who Gave a New Definition To The Music .|work=Witty9|accessdate=18 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913222425/http://www.witty9.com/list-of-top-10-famous-rock-bands-who-gave-a-new-defination-to-the-music/|archive-date=13 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://travel.india.com/articles/12-cities-home-awesome-bands-probably-dint-know/|title=12 Cities That are Home to Awesome Bands and You Probably Din't Know It!|work=Travel India|accessdate=18 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304041806/http://travel.india.com/articles/12-cities-home-awesome-bands-probably-dint-know/|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toplisthub.com/top-10-rock-bands-in-india/|title=Top 10 Rock Bands in India|author=Neelima K|work=Top List Hub|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaper.dnaindia.com/epapermain.aspx?pgNo=4&edcode=820076&eddate=2013-6-26|title=DNA E-Paper - Daily News & Analysis -Mumbai,India|work=dnaindia.com|accessdate=18 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160319152138/http://epaper.dnaindia.com/epapermain.aspx?pgNo=4&edcode=820076&eddate=2013-6-26|archive-date=19 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Regional music scenes ==\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{or section|date=April 2019}}\n{{Cleanup|date=September 2019|reason=[[WP:LAUNDRY]]; excessively detailed|section}}\n}}\nMany cities and regions have produced collections of bands large enough to be classified as a scene within Indian rock.\n[[Shillong]], [[Chennai]], [[Mumbai]] and [[Bangalore]] have long been one of the principal founts of Indian rock and continues to produce bands regularly.<ref>[http://www.musicmalt.com/2015/04/16-rock-bands-from-north-east-india.html 16 Rock Bands from North-East India you don't want to miss], ''Music Malt''</ref>\n\n=== Bangalore scene ===\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = vertical\n | footer    = Heavy Metal group [[Iron Maiden]] performing live in Bangalore (top) and [[Kryptos (band)|Kryptos]] performing at Harley Rock Riders Season III. (bottom)\n | image1    = Ironmaiden Bangalore RNI.jpg\n | width1    = 210\n | image2    = Kryptos at Harley Rock Riders Season III in Bangalore, India (Jim Ankan Deka photography).jpg\n | width2    = 210\n}}\nThe dominant music genres in urban [[Bangalore]] are rock and metal music. All subgenres of rock, varying from classic rock n' roll to extreme metal can be heard in [[Bangalore]]. The underground scenario in Bangalore is highly acclaimed, and though Shillong is called the Rock/Metal capital of India but that day is not far when Bangalore can take the fame away from Shillong. Notable bands from Bangalore include Eunoia Soulscape, Maun, [[Manoj George|ManojGeorge4Strings]], [[Raghu Dixit Project]], Divine Raaga, Arha, Thermal and a quarter (TAAQ), [[Girish and The Chronicles]] (GATC), [[Kryptos (band)|Kryptos]], [[The Down Troddence|The Down troddence(TDT)]] (originally from Kannur, Kerala), Culminant, Dark Light, Alternative Ties, Neolithic Silence, Abandoned Agony, [[Theorized (band)|Theorized]], [[SvarAmrita (band)|SvarAmrita]], [[Inner Sanctum (band)|Inner Sanctum]], [[Agam (band)|Agam]], Slain, Clown With a Frown, allegro fudge, Black Sun, [[All the Fat Children]], J3, The Bicycle Days, Pralayh, The Usual Suspects, Final Surrender,Crash TV, Eccentric Pendulum, Crossroads, Orchid, Hungry(band), [https://www.facebook.com/BufferZoneTheBand Buffer Zone], Perfect Strangers, Ek, [[Swarathma]], [[Eastern Fare]] and Galeej Gurus. [[Rock 'n India]], Great Indian Rock and more recently Deccan Rock are the primitive rock festivals in India. Bangalore was also the first city in India where internationally popular rock groups [[Opeth]], [[Iron Maiden]], [[The Rolling Stones]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[Scorpions (band)|Scorpions]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Aerosmith]], [[Elton John]], [[Deep Purple]], [[Metallica]], [[Slayer]], [[Megadeth]], among various other heavy metal groups performed live for the first time in India.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.efi-news.com/2011/08/metallica-in-india.html |title=Metallica in India - EF News International |access-date=16 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509054908/http://www.efi-news.com/2011/08/metallica-in-india.html |archive-date=9 May 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nRecent restrictions on live music in Bangalore's bars has affected the rock music culture of the city but is slowly recovering with pubs like Kyra, B Flat and Legends of Rock hosting more live bands.<ref>[http://www.hindu.com/2008/08/04/stories/2008080461100400.htm Karnataka \u2013 The Hindu]</ref> Festivals like [[Rock 'n India]], Rock Ethos, Great Indian Rock and more recently Wrath Fest at Raipur and Deccan Rock continue to take place in Bangalore, a popular destination for international acts like [[Iron Maiden]], [[Lamb of God (band)|Lamb of God]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[Scorpions (band)|Scorpions]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Aerosmith]], [[Megadeth]], [[Elton John]], [[Metallica]] and [[Deep Purple]].\n\n=== Chennai scene ===\nAnother major Indian rock festival is the June Rock Out, organised by the Unwind Centre in [[Adyar (Tamil Nadu)|Adyar]], [[Chennai]].\nThere are also other smaller rock/metal festivals happening regularly in Bangalore and Chennai, like \"Euphony\", the \"September Underground\", \"Last Band Standing\", and the weekly \"Live 101.\" The Bands Association of Chennai (BAC) is an organisation which actively promotes the cause of original music by Chennai bands such as Requiem Injustice, Grasshopper Green and Namma Ooru Boy Band (NOBB).\n\n=== Delhi scene ===\n[[Delhi]]'s music circuit has seen its share of ups and downs, but has held on largely due to the local presence of ''[[Rock Street Journal]]''. Delhi being the operational home of the Allahabad-based magazine, local bands have benefited by the proximity to India's first dedicated to stories and features based around rock and metal. The Great Indian Rock festival was mostly held in Delhi, now foraying into [[Kolkata]], [[Mumbai]] and [[Bangalore]], [[North-East India]] and [[Pune]] has exposed the upcoming musicians of India to a wider variety of musicians.<ref>[http://gnews.com/music-education-is-hitting-the-high-notes-in-bangalore-03200933095517/ Bangalore - G-News] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101124002108/http://gnews.com/music-education-is-hitting-the-high-notes-in-bangalore-03200933095517/ |date=24 November 2010 }}</ref> Notable bands from Delhi include Orange Street, [[Parikrama (band)|Parikrama]], Hundred Octane, [[Indian Ocean (band)|Indian Ocean]], [[Them Clones]], [[Menwhopause]], [[Bandish]], [[Advaita]], Faridkot, [[AntarDhvani]], [[Punkh]],<ref>http://www.mtv.com/artists/punkh/</ref><ref>http://www.nme.in/punkh-set-to-soar-with-new-album/</ref> [[Midival Punditz]], [[Undying Inc.]], [[Mrigya (band)|Mrigya]], [[Guillotine (band)|Guillotine]], [[The Iyer Project (band)]].\n\n=== Hyderabad scene ===\nIn Hyderabad bands like Sledge, Wreckage, Native Tongue has paved for upcoming bands by taking it to the nationals. They have won major rock and metal competitions such as campus rock idols 2004, 2005 and 2006 and headlining gigs across all major IT festivals in India taking charge of the Indian rock scene.\n\n=== Indore scene ===\n[[File:Nicotine Metal Band Indore.jpg|thumb|[[Nicotine (band)|Nicotine]] playing at 'Pedal To The Metal', TDS, Indore, India in 2014.]]\n\nThe [[Indore]] scene (in Central India) initially ignored by the mainstream Rock/Metal fraternity has been emerging as the 'Dark Horse' of Indian Rock and Metal Scene since the mid-2000s. Though [[Metal]] dominates the scene, the city has produced bands from all kinds of the genre (Classic Rock, Alternative, Hard Rock, Death Metal).\n\n[[Nicotine (band)]] which was formed in December 2006, is widely credited for being the pioneers of Metal music, not just in the Indore but in Central India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaper.dnaindia.com/story.aspx?id=27256&boxid=11558&ed_date=2013-06-26&ed_code=820076&ed_page=4|title=All hail the headbangers, They are in Indore's Hall of Fame|work=DNA E-Paper, Daily News & Analysis, Mumbai, India, dnaindia.com|accessdate=26 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320055640/http://epaper.dnaindia.com/story.aspx?id=27256&boxid=11558&ed_date=2013-06-26&ed_code=820076&ed_page=4|archive-date=20 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkthroughindia.com/hot-trends/the-10-famous-rock-bands-of-india/|title=The 10 Famous Rock Bands of India|work=walkthroughindia.com|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liveinstyle.com/nightlife/party-calendar/thursday-live-metal-mania-feat-dirge-and-nicotine-hard-rock-cafe-hyderabad|title=Metal Mania feat Nicotine & Dirge at Hard Rock Cafe, Hyderabad|work=liveinstyle.com|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trendingtop5.com/interview-nicotine-top-metal-rock-band-india/|title=An interview with Nicotine, One of the top Metal bands of India|work=trendingtop5.com|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref>\nZero Gravity, another Metal band from the city, released their full-length album called 'Holocaust Awaits' in 2014.<ref>https://www.discogs.com/Zero-Gravity-Holocaust-Awaits-/release/7431887</ref>\n\n[[Nicotine (band)|Nicotine]], Grim Reapers and Bliss are the only 3 bands to have qualified from the Central Zone of the 'Campus Rock Idols' Competition.\nCeaseless Juncture and Perception as Reality are some of the existing active bands. There were bands like Avalanche, Auxiliary Triangle, Assault, Overdrive, Blindfolds which are now disbanded but won competitions outside the city.\nThough it is an independent scene, major bands from outside the city like BLAKC, Zygnema, [[Demonic Resurrection]], Undying Inc, Albatross, etc. have performed in Indore.\n\n=== Kerala scene ===\nThe state of Kerala gave India one of the first and successful rock bands ever - [[13AD (band)|13 A.D]].\nKerala has produced some of the finest bands and musicians : [[Motherjane]], [[Avial (band)|Avial]], [[The Down Troddence]], [[Thaikkudam Bridge]], [[Evergreen (band)|Evergreen]], [[Manoj George|ManojGeorge4Strings]], [[Sumit (Guitarist)]], [[Sanjeev Thomas (Guitarist)]], [[Baiju Dharmajan]], [[Rex Vijayan]] to name a few.<ref>[[Avial (band)|Avial]]</ref>\n\n=== Calcutta Scene ===\n{{See also|Rock music of West Bengal}}\nBands from Kolkata that pioneered original music in English include [[Krosswindz]], Cassini's Division, Skinny Alley, The Supersonics, [[Five Little Indians]],and Span. There is also a massive regional rock scene and also some bands formed locally with international views in Kolkata that includes bands like [[Fossils (band)|Fossils]], [[Cactus (Indian band)|Cactus]], [[Chandrabindoo (band)|Chandrabindoo]], [[Krosswindz]], [[Bhoomi (band)|Bhoomi]], [[Lakkhichhara (band)|Lakkhichhara]], [[Alienz]], [[Cross Theory - India (Indian Band)|Cross Theory - India]], [[Fakira (band)|Fakira]], [[AGNISH (band)|AGNISH]], [[PRITHIBI (band)|PRITHIBI]], [[METALLOIDZ - INDIA (India band)|METALLOIDZ - INDIA]].\n\nIn [[Calcutta]], the underground Metal Bands organise an Event called The Pit at Tapan Theatre in Kalighat. In 2009, 3 editions of The Pit were successfully organised. It is being seen now that more events are being organised, like the metal events held by KOSMA ( Kolkata Old School Metal Association). Other fests include 'Abomination', 'Order Of The Heretical Trident Festival', 'Kolkata Open Air'. [[Bengali language|Bengali]] metal gigs attract huge crowds and are sponsored by various organisations. Kolkata also hosts an annual musical festival, The NH7 Weekender since 2013.<ref>[http://www.telegraphindia.com/1090430/jsp/entertainment/story_10894415.jsp The Telegraph \u2013 Calcutta]</ref>\n\n[[Moheener Ghoraguli]], a [[Bengali language|Bengali]] independent music group from [[Kolkata]], is arguably India's and [[Bengal]]'s first popular rock band.<ref>{{cite news |title=Song of the stallion|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-06-21/kolkata/28166934_1_composers-song-author-and-friend |work= The Times of India|date=21 June 2009 }}</ref><ref>[[Moheener Ghoraguli]]</ref>\n\n=== Mumbai scene ===\n{{multiple image\n | align     = left\n | direction = vertical\n | footer    = [[Bhayanak Maut]] performing at the 2010 Independence Rock XXV (top) and [[Demonic Resurrection]] performing live at Brutal Assault 2010. (bottom)\n | image1    = Bhayanak-Maut.jpg\n | width1    = 200\n | image2    = Demonic Resurrection.jpg\n | width2    = 200\n}}\nSome of the most notable contemporary rock bands from Mumbai are [[Pentagram (Indian band)|Pentagram]], Tough on Tobacco, [[Bhayanak Maut]], [[Demonic Resurrection]], Split, Sridhar/Thayil, [[Scribe (band)|Scribe]], and Goddess Gagged. The recent reunion of Indian rock pioneers [[Indus Creed]] was received with great enthusiasm,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/index.aspx?page=article&sectid=135&contentid=2010100520101005023954211a4c8f328 |title=Archived copy |access-date=28 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714133216/http://www.mumbaimirror.com/index.aspx?page=article&sectid=135&contentid=2010100520101005023954211a4c8f328 |archive-date=14 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> especially with regard to their plans to produce a new album in 2011.\n\nMumbai's longest-running festival has been the [[Independence Rock Festival]]. 2010 saw I-Rock, as it is popularly known, celebrate its 25th year. Independence Rock XXV paid tribute to the city that has hosted the festival by featuring a spate of local bands. The recently reunited Indus Creed headlined the festival, which included other local favourites like Bhayanak Maut, Scribe, Demonic Resurrection and Pralay, as well as stalwart musicians like Dhruv Ghanekar, Warren Mendonsa, Loy Mendonsa, Ehsaan Noorani, Farhad Wadia (the festival's founder and promoter), Ravi Iyer, Chandresh Kudwa, Shazneen Arethna and Sidd Coutto.\n\n=== Pune scene ===\nA relatively recent entry into the Indian Rock circuit is the city of Pune has been the home of bands over the years and off late there has been a new surge with notable genre-defining acts like Silver, Strange Brew, Jazz Mates, Nothing as Now and more. The live music scene of the twin cities Mumbai and Pune has been on a steep rise since 2005 with major International acts like [[Meshuggah]], [[Tesseract (band)|Tesseract]], [[Satyricon (band)|Satyricon]], Freak Kitchen, [[Sahg]]. Pune plays host to an annual musical festival, The NH7 Weekender, which takes place in the month of November and showcases international (mostly British) acts like [[Imogen Heap]], [[The Magic Numbers]], [[Asian Dub Foundation]] and [[Reverend Soundsystem]] to name a few.\n\n=== Ranchi scene ===\n[[File:John receiving the Best Drummer award at Hornbill Festival in 2017..jpg|thumb|right|[[Highway 69 (band) | Highway 69's drummer]] receiving the Best Drummer award from [[Uday Benegal]] at Hornbill International Rock Contest 2017 in [[Nagaland]].]]\nHailing from a small place quite unknown to the rest of the country, the bands of Ranchi from Jharkhand state had to face discrimination and hardships. Over the years, this city has produced some of the finest rock and metal music bands but they have always gone unnoticed because of being from a small town. In the 1990s, bands like Genesis, Kaalmantra and Sparsh<ref name=\"The Times of India for 'Sparsh'\">{{cite web |title=Ranchi rock band to perform today|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/pune/Ranchi-rock-band-to-perform-today/articleshow/2639039.cms|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref> have been considered as the pioneers to rock and metal music in Jharkhand. The city has had various music festivals being organized since the 2000s and a few of them are still organized today with the biggest one being Thunderstrock Festival<ref name=\"The Telegraph for 'Thunderstrock Festival'\">{{cite web |title=Rock concert next month|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/jharkhand/rock-concert-next-month/cid/1310535|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref> and other notable festivals are like Rock Jatra and Rhapsody. The band Sparsh was aired live on CNN-IBN<ref name=\"YouTube for 'Sparsh'\">{{cite web |title=Sparsh on CNN-IBN|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4Ckosjl-7iw|publisher=YouTube}}</ref> cheering up for the [[India national cricket team]] during the [[2011 Cricket World Cup]]. The band 4 Degrees of Freedom<ref name=\"Rolling Stones India for HIRC 2013\">{{cite web |title=Hornbill International Rock Contest 2013|url=https://rollingstoneindia.com/review-hornbill-international-rock-contest-2013/|publisher=Rolling Stones India}}</ref> were the finalists of Hornbill International Rock Contest 2013, followed by [[Highway 69 (band)]] being twice the finalists at Hornbill International Rock Contest for 2017, 2018 along with their drummer winning the best drummer award in 2017 and Vikrit and Existence also being the finalists in 2018. The bands of Ranchi have been touring and performing across the country with currently [[Highway 69 (band)]] being the most notable one as it has performed extensively all over the country and has evolved with a huge fan base, followed by other bands like Reciprocal<ref name=\"The Avenue Mail\">{{cite web |title=Local rock bands ready to rock for voters\u2019 awareness in Ranchi|url=https://www.avenuemail.in/jamshedpur/local-rock-bands-ready-to-rock-for-voters-awareness-in-ranchi/132565/|publisher=The Avenue Mail}}</ref>, Existence, Vikrit, Iris 13 etc. Other active and notable bands from the 2010s were Genesis, Kaalmantra, Sparsh, 4 Degrees of Freedom, Conflicting Resonance etc.\n\n== Independent record labels ==\nMainstream record labels in India often ignore rock, with a few exceptions. Album sales range between a few hundred copies to a few thousand. They are rarely, if at all, affiliated to the Indian music industry, and sales are not usually monitored. Songs of Bollywood usually gain more popularity as compared to the songs of bands. This is a huge set back. Bands also fail to sell their songs throughout the country even after making it available to major music stores, this is only due to lack of interest of people in rock bands. There are only a few bands that have become successful in selling their songs throughout the country. People who enjoy rock get the songs of their favorite bands, just by a click from any music website (sometimes their songs are uploaded by website administrators just after the day of release, this is illegal as per copyright law, but even then no action is taken). Hence, overall sales become less than expected. Bands in India mostly perform live shows with low priced tickets (as low as Rs. 100 or even less). Probably, the growing and the upcoming generation will have interest in Indian Rock and Metal. But care has to be taken to retain the copyright of the music.\n\nThe future looks encouraging thanks to entities such as Green Ozone, [[DogmaTone]] Records, [[Cochym]] and [[Eastern Fare Music Foundation]], [[Infestdead Records]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tntmagazine.in/tnt-y-news/northeast-gets-its-first-metal-label-signs-savage-uk/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827041640/http://tntmagazine.in/tnt-y-news/northeast-gets-its-first-metal-label-signs-savage-uk/ |archive-date=27 August 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>http://www.metal-rules.com/metalnews/2012/08/23/india-gets-a-new-metal-label-signs-nwobhm-legend-savage-uk/</ref> that are dedicated to promoting and supporting Indian rock.\n\n==Documentary on Indian rock==\n\nIn 2008, music journalist Abhimanyu Kukreja directed Rockumentary - Becoming of Indian rock that was produced by NewsX and had a national TV release. The documentary is arguably the first of its kind on Indian rock that showcases the evolution of rock music in India starting from the 1960s. The documentary features popular and classic Indian bands like The Great Bear, High, The Great Society, Shiva, Indus Creed, Millennium and Parikrama. The documentary is available for free viewing on YouTube.<ref>{{cite web|title=Documentary by Abhimanyu Kukreja|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XSjSS1Zw58o|publisher=Newsx}}</ref> ''\n\n[[Leaving Home \u2013 the Life & Music of Indian Ocean]]'' (2010) directed by [[Jaideep Varma]] was about fusion rock band, [[Indian Ocean (band)|Indian Ocean]]. Thus it became the first band ever in India to be subject of a documentary.<ref name=ndtv>{{cite web | title = Indian Ocean co-founder Susmit Sen quits band |work= NDTV | url = http://movies.ndtv.com/music/indian-ocean-co-founder-susmit-sen-quits-band-612287 |date=12 June 2013| accessdate = 2014-11-17 }}</ref> At the [[58th National Film Awards]], the documentary went on to win the [[National Film Award for Best Arts/Cultural Film|Award for Best Arts/Cultural Film]].<ref name=\"58thaward\">{{cite web|url=http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm58NFAAward.aspx|title=58th National Film Awards|publisher=[[International Film Festival of India]]|accessdate=29 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414003922/http://iffi.nic.in/Dff2011/Frm58NFAAward.aspx|archive-date=14 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"58thawardPDF\">{{cite web|url=http://dff.nic.in/2011/58_NFA.pdf|title=58th National Film Awards (PDF)|publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]]|accessdate=29 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Issues faced==\nAn all-girl rock band [[Pragash Band]] from Srinagar, Kashmir decided to call it quits after constant hate mails and death threats on the internet, apart from the severe criticism and opposition from the religious leaders of Kashmir and other hardliner political parties.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Demonic Resurrection]]\n*[[Pin Drop Violence]]\n*[[Kryptos (band)]]\n*[[Nicotine (Metal Band)]]\n*[[Inner Sanctum (band)]]\n*[[Scribe (band)]]\n*[[Rusty Moe]]\n*[[Bhayanak Maut]]\n*[[Asian Underground]]\n*[[Rock music of West Bengal]] popularly known as Bangla rock\n*[[Psychedelic music]]\n*[[Psychedelic rock]]\n*[[Raga rock]]\n*[[The Vinyl Records]]\n*[[Life in a... Metro]]\n*[[Rock On!!]]\n*[[Highway 69 (band)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite web|title=KAAV-MyOPUSRADIO |url=http://www.myopusradio.com/platformnews/article/big-fish-for-october-kaav|accessdate=10 October 2012}}\n* {{cite web|title=KAAV-INDIAN EXPRESS |url=http://epaper.indianexpress.com/50382/Indian-Express/04-August-2012#page/21/3|accessdate=10 October 2012}}\n* {{cite web|title=KAAV-INDIANROCKMP3|url=http://www.indianrockmp3.com/2012/09/24/a-fine-debut-with-a-unique-sound/|accessdate=10 October 2012}}\n* {{cite news|title=KARNATRIIX-THE HINDU|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/music/article3785202.ece|accessdate=10 October 2012 | location=Chennai, India|work=The Hindu|first=Saraswathy|last=Nagarajan|date=17 August 2012}}\n* {{cite web|title=BAIJUDHARMAJAN-Timesofindia|url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=MIRRORNEW&BaseHref=BGMIR/2012/08/07&PageLabel=20&EntityId=Ar01901&ViewMode=HTML|accessdate=10 October 2012}}\n* {{cite news|title=BAIJUDHARMAJAN-THE HINDU|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/music/article3550720.ece|accessdate=10 October 2012 | location=Chennai, India|work=The Hindu|date=20 June 2012}}\n* {{cite web|title=BAIJUDHARMAJAN-ibnlive|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/crossing-over-to-a-new-beginning/261533-60-122.html|accessdate=10 October 2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{dmoz|/Regional/Asia/India/Arts_and_Entertainment/Music/Bands_and_Artists/}}\n\n{{World rock}}\n\n[[Category:Indian rock music| ]]\n", "name_user": "Tarun Paul Kachhap", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRanchi scene", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_rock"}
{"title_page": "Highway 69 (band)", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian metal band}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Highway 69\n| image           = Highway 69 - Group Photo.jpg\n| caption         = Members of Highway 69. From left to right: [[Alvin Rozario]], John Raj Swami, Binit Barla and Tarang Kerketta.\n| alt             = Group photo of the members in Highway 69 (band).\n| landscape       = yes\n| background      = group_or_band\n| origin          = [[Ranchi]], [[Jharkhand]], [[India]].\n| genre           = {{hlist|[[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]}}\n| years_active    = 2012\u2013present\n| associated_acts = [[Alvin Rozario]]\n| current_members =\n* Tarang Kerketta (''Dagu'')\n* [[Alvin Rozario]]\n* Binit Barla\n* John Raj Swami\n| past_members    =\n* Nikhil Dhanraj\n* Anugraha Sonal Johnson Mundu\n* Dheeraj Edward\n}}\n\n'''Highway 69''' is an Indian [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band. The band was formed in 2012 in [[Ranchi]] by vocalist Tarang Kerketta and guitarist [[Alvin Rozario]], and has been based in [[Ranchi]] ever-since it's formation. The band has been the winners of numerous battle of band titles across their country and is known for their fast tempos, instrumental and aggressive style of playing. The band has performed twice as the finalists at Hornbill International Rock Contest of [[Hornbill Festival]] in [[Nagaland]] for the year 2017<ref>{{cite web|title=Musical route to national stage|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/states/jharkhand/musical-route-to-national-stage/cid/1342721|website=The Telegraph|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> and 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nine bands to vie for Hornbill Rock Contest finale today|url=https://www.easternmirrornagaland.com/nine-bands-to-vie-for-hornbill-rock-contest-finale-today/|website=Eastern Mirror Nagaland|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Their drummer has also bagged the title of the 'Best Drummer' in the year 2017 at this festival and was felicitated by [[Uday Benegal]] from the [[Indus Creed]] which is a band considered to be the pioneers of the Indian rock music.\n\nHailing from a small place quite unknown to the rest of the country, the band had to face discrimination and hardships in their path to fame. Their artistry and love for music guided them through tough times, on course to become an upcoming popular metal band from [[East India]]. Highway 69 performs extensively all over the country and is evolving with a huge fan base. Currently, the band is working on its debut album.\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation and early years (2012\u20132013)===\n[[File:Highway 69 at BIT Mesra Deoghar campus during Utthaan 2012.jpg|thumb|Highway 69 after doing their first show together as a band at Utthaan fest of BIT Mesra (Deoghar campus) in October 2012.\n(From left: Binit Barla, Tarang Kerketta, [[Alvin Rozario]] and Dheeraj Edward.)]]\nHighway 69 was formed in [[Ranchi]], [[Jharkhand]] in mid-2012 with the founding members being Tarang Kerketta and [[Alvin Rozario]]. Back then, Tarang used to live in [[Jamshedpur]] which is a city approximately 120 km from Ranchi. He was the vocalist of a metal-band based in Jamshedpur called Atript while Alvin was the guitarist for a metal-band in Ranchi called Destiny. Both of them met for the first time during a local battle of the band competition in Ranchi. It is considered that it was the initial place where both of them decided on forming a band of their own.\n\nThe band Highway 69 was started with Tarang on the vocals and Alvin on the guitars, along with that two local musicians named Binit Barla and Dheeraj Edward. Binit used to play bass for Alvin's show while Alvin and Dheeraj were bandmates in their metal band named Destiny. When Alvin and Tarang were forming a band and we're looking for band members, this is when Alvin suggested the names Binit and Dheeraj with whom he had already been performing. Hence the line-up was formed and the band started to practice together and composed their first song called 'Disturbed' and covered other popular metal songs. They went on to participate in a battle of bands competition organized at [[Birla Institute of Technology (Deoghar)]] by Utthaan where the band won the competition along with that Alvin was awarded the best guitarist in the competition. As it was the year-end of 2012, then went on to do few local gigs in Ranchi and Jamshedpur. They also had a major achievement in their early years by winning the Wheels competition organized by TATA Steel in Jamshedpur.\n\n===''Dheeraj quits, Johnson joins the band'' and [[Thunderstrock Festival]] (2013-2014)===\nDheeraj and Alvin both use to be bandmates in their previous metal band. Both had high expectation from their band but weren't able to find that same spirit in that band so they left to form Highway 69. But even before completing one year as the drummer for Highway 69, Dheeraj decided to quit the band citing difficulty in managing his time between the band and his higher studies.\n\n[[File:Highway 69 at IIM Bangalore during Unmaad 2014.jpg|thumb|left|Highway 69 performing at Rockolesseum of Unmaad, the cultural festival of IIM Bangalore]]\nDheeraj was replaced by Anugraha Sonal Johnson Mundu, a local musician who belonged to Alvin's neighbourhood. He joined the band and the band continued with him. With the new line-up, the band won the battle of bands competitions at [[St. Xavier's School, Ranchi]], [[National Institute of Foundry and Forge Technology]] Ranchi, made their appearance in the Avalanche of [[Srijan]] at [[Indian School of Mines, Dhanbad]] and in Rockolesseum of Unmaad, the cultural festival of [[IIM Bangalore]]. Performing in Bangalore became their very first metropolitan show as a band which also required travelling of approximately 1,900 km from their hometown. The Bangalore show became the place where the band got the exposure of various other bands and musicians who were the part of that fest like [[Blackstratblues]], [[Karsh Kale]], [[Farhan Akhtar]] and many others. The band also performed at Detox, which was an initiative by the Government of Jharkhand to promote the local rock & metal music culture. They shared the stage with [[Demonic Resurrection]], [[Girish and The Chronicles]] and other local bands from the city.\n\nLater during mid-2014, Tarang Kerketta took the initiative of starting an inactive rock & metal music festival from their city called [[Thunderstrock Festival]]. It was a charitable music festival started in 2008 with the initiative of promoting the local music scene as well as to donate the funds generated from it to the people in need. Tarang is generally credited in bringing this stagnant music festival back to life again in 2014 with giving the stage to the local bands like Death Note (now Reciprocal), Destiny (band in which Alvin and Dheeraj used to play earlier), Error 404, Virus (John, the drummer of this band later joins Highway 69), Genesis, Highway 69 and Head Motif all the way from [[Darjeeling]], [[West Bengal]].\n\n===Replacement of drummers and winning competitions across India (2015-2018)===\n[[File:Tarang Kerketta, Pepsi MTV Indies - Ranchi Rocks, in 2015.jpg|thumb|Tarang Kerketta performing at Pepsi MTV Indies - Ranchi Rocks: Chapter 1, in 2015]]\nAfter a year since Dheeraj left the band, he again approached the band for joining it. He was considered in the band's line-up once again and eventually, Johnson had to leave who earlier came as the replacement in Dheeraj's place. With Dheeraj once again in the line-up, the band went for participating at i-Rock of Jinks-Pranav at [[National Institute of Foundry and Forge Technology]], Ranchi, Thundermarch at [[National Institute of Technology, Silchar]] and Avalanche of [[Srijan]] at [[Indian Institute of Technology (Indian School of Mines), Dhanbad]]. The band won the competitions at [[NIFFT]] Ranchi and IIT (ISM) Dhanbad but couldn't secure any position at [[NIT Silchar]] (Later in 2016, the band was again shortlisted for the finals at NIT Silchar but they couldn't go to perform and in 2018, they were selected for the third time and this time they even won the competition). The band also headlined the Pepsi MTV Indies - Ranchi Rocks: Chapter 1 in 2015 which had the local bands of Ranchi along with that the headliner band from Bangalore named Live Banned.\n\n[[File:John receiving the Best Drummer award at Hornbill Festival in 2017..jpg|thumb|left|John receiving the Best Drummer award from Uday Benegal of Indus Creed (band) at Hornbill International Rock Contest in 2017.]]\nLater in the year 2015, Dheeraj again decided to leave the band as he wasn't able to continue with regular practice and cope up with Highway 69's regular participating in events which required a lot of travelling throughout the country. So they finally decided on having a permanent drummer who will be committed towards the band. During this time, the band practised with various drummers from [[Ranchi]], [[Jamshedpur]] and even [[Kolkata]] but ultimately settled for John Raj Swami, who was a drummer for a local metal band called Virus who was in the line-up of [[Thunderstrock Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Bipolar Shadows all set to perform at Thunderstrock Festival in Ranchi|url=https://etchronicle.com/bipolar-shadows-all-set-to-perform-at-thunderstrock-festival-in-ranchi/|website=ET Chronicle|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> 2014, which is a festival initiated by Highway 69's vocalist. The band was already familiar with the playing style of John as they have shared the stage in various competitions and music festivals across India. The band went for practice with him and did a couple of few shows in Ranchi and were quite impressed with his playing style and even John agreed in joining the band as their permanent replacement for a drummer. The growing confusion over who'll continue the band as a drummer was finally sorted out. This gave the band it's ample time to practice and compose new songs. John came as a perfect replacement but tensions grew in mid-2017 when due to personal misunderstandings within the band, he was asked to leave the band. But later in the same year itself, he again joined the band and has been with the band ever since. John is quite popular amongst the audience and other fellow musicians because of his aggressive style of drumming along with going shirtless when performing on-stage.\n\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = vertical\n | footer    = John and Alvin during their performance at Culfest of NIT Jamshedpur in 2016. (top) and Highway 69 after completing their performance at Spring Fest of IIT Kharagpur in 2017. (bottom)\n | image1    = John and Alvin during their performance at NIT Jamshedpur in 2016.jpg\n | width1    = 210\n | image2    = Highway 69 at IIT Kharagpur during Spring Fest 2017.jpg\n | width2    = 210\n}}\n\nWith the new drummer in hand who is regular in practice, the band could finally look forward to participating at some of the biggest and most popular battles of the bands' competition in India. During the span of 2015\u20132018, the band went to participate in festivals across India of which they won the competitions like Fuego - KIIT Fest of [[Kalinga Institute of Industrial Technology]], [[Bhubaneswar]], Blizzard of Rock - Chaos of [[Indian Institute of Management Ahmedabad]], Distortion - Culfest of [[National Institute of Technology, Jamshedpur]], Rocktaves - Oasis of [[Birla Institute of Technology and Science, Pilani]],<ref>{{cite web|title=BITS PILANI OASIS ROCK EVENT: ROCKTAVES|url=https://atkt.in/articles/bits-pilani-oasis-rock-event-rocktaves/|website=ATKT.in|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Searock of [[Waves (festival) ]] at [[Birla Institute of Technology and Science, Pilani \u2013 Goa Campus]], Till Deaf Do We Part of [[Pearl (cultural festival)]] at [[Birla Institute of Technology and Science, Pilani \u2013 Hyderabad Campus]], Resonance of [[Festember]] at [[National Institute of Technology, Tiruchirappalli]],<ref>{{cite web|title=METAL BAND HIGHWAY 69 WREAK HAVOC AT FESTEMBER|url=https://atkt.in/articles/highway-69-trichy/|website=ATKT.in|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Synchronicity of [[Antaragni]] at [[Indian Institute of Technology Kanpur]], Decibelz of Xpressions at [[Xavier Institute of Management, Bhubaneswar]] and Thundermarch of Incandescene at [[National Institute of Technology, Silchar]]. The band won the runner-up positions at Wildfire of [[Spring Fest]] at [[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]], Strawberry Fields at [[National Law School of India University]], [[Bangalore]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Resigned from the job because Boss did not grant holiday|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/news/latest-ranchi-news-040533-2381266.html|website=Dainik Bhaskar|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Livewire of [[Mood Indigo (festival)]] at [[Indian Institute of Technology Bombay]],<ref>{{cite web|title=IIT Bombay's annual cultural festival Mood Indigo kicks off its Livewire nite|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BdAawjfHexr/?utm_source=ig_web_button_share_sheet|website=Instagram handle of Rolling Stones (India)|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Decibels of [[Saarang]] at [[Indian Institute of Technology Madras]], Rock-o-Phonix of [[Alcheringa (festival)]] at [[Indian Institute of Technology Guwahati]] and have been twice declared the finalists at Hornbill International Rock Contest of [[Hornbill Festival]] at Nagaland in 2017<ref>{{cite web|title=Hornbill International Rock Contest: Nine bands to battle it out in grand finale on Friday|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/north-east-india/nagaland/hornbill-international-rock-contest-nine-bands-to-battle-it-out-in-grand-finale-on-friday-4972972/|website=Indian Express|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dimapur to host Hornbill International Rock Contest 2017|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/north-east-india/nagaland/dimapur-to-host-hornbill-international-rock-contest-2017/|website=Indian Express|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> and 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bands making it to the finale included...Highway 69 (Ranchi, Jharkhand)|url=http://www.nagalandpost.com/perfect-strangers-wins-hirc-2018/186716.html|website=Nagaland Post|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> John has been awarded as the best drummer at Hornbill Festival in 2017. During their span of covering all the major music competitions across India, the band started to attain national recognization in the music scene and a good amount of fan following as well as positive reception and appreciation from fellow musicians and promoters at the events.\n\nIn the mid-2017, there was some misunderstanding within the band due to which John was removed from the band and in his replacement, a drummer from [[Jamshedpur]] called Nikhil Dhanraj played the drums for Highway 69. With Nikhil, the band did a couple of shows with participation in the competition held at [[National Institute of Technology, Tiruchirappalli]], [[Tamil Nadu]] and a music master class by Highway 69 at [[Chakradharpur]], [[Jharkhand]]. Within a short span of John's absence, he was again included in the line-up. Also in the same year, the band was shortlisted for the first time in the Eastern-leg of Wacken Metal Battle organized by [[Bangalore Open Air]] alongside Astitiva (now Existence), Reciprocal from Ranchi and [[Chronic Xorn]] from Kolkata but due to the unavailability of their bassist; they did not go for the competition.\n\nAlong with the competitions, the timeline of 2015-2018 was also spent in composing new original songs by the band. The band went unto compose their originals like Beyond Imagination, Don't be the Prisoners, Hope and Origin. Apart from taking part in competitions, they headlined in music festivals of [[Jamshedpur]], [[Ranchi]] and [[Kolkata]] which eventually helped them gain the pace of a popular upcoming metal band in their own state. Having spent a long-time in competitions, the year 2018 was marked as the last year to participate in competitions.\n\n=== Headlining & judging shows, upcoming debut album (2019\u2013present)===\n[[File:Highway 69 after completing their show at Jalpaiguri in 2019..jpg|thumb|left|A group photo with the audience after completing the show at Jalpaiguri in 2019.]]\nDuring the mid-2018, when Tarang started the work for that year's [[Thunderstrock Festival]], he took on-board Tarun Paul Kachhap to manage the promotions of the festival and eventually he made Tarun as the manager for Highway 69. Also by the end of 2018 when the band was returning from Hornbill Festival<ref>{{cite web|title=Ranchi bands Highway 69 and Vikrit in the finals|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/jharkhand/ranchi/news/ranchi-rock-band-highway-69-and-distorted-to-the-final-of-contest-035603-3389144.html|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref> in Nagaland they decided to give an end to participating in music competitions and work in their debut album and give preference to booked shows. With having a long-list of competitions that the band has won, they have been booked as the judges for the competitions in which they themselves once used to be the participants. The band was booked to judge Fuego of KIIT Fest 2019 in [[Kalinga Institute of Industrial Technology]], [[Bhubaneswar]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Highway 69 as the judges for Fuego.|url=https://www.facebook.com/kiitfest/photos/a.754450924636786/2076640085751190/|website=Facebook page of KIIT Fest|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Avalanche of [[Srijan]] 2019 in [[Indian Institute of Technology (Indian School of Mines), Dhanbad]] and twice at Rhapsody of Bitotsav 2019 and 2020 in [[Birla Institute of Technology, Mesra]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The local metal band of Ranchi, Highway 69 performed in the Fusion Arena|url=https://bitmesra.ac.in/naps/11813-2/|website=NAPS of BIT Mesra|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> They even got headliner shows in [[Jorhat]], twice in [[Jalpaiguri]], opening for [[Jubin Nautiyal]], a Bollywood singer at [[Srijan]] of [[Indian Institute of Technology (Indian School of Mines), Dhanbad]], Bitotsav of [[Birla Institute of Technology, Mesra]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Plethora of events enthuse participants at BITOTSAV 2020|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2020/state-editions/plethora-of-events-enthuse-participants-at-bitotsav-2020.html|website=The Pioneer|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> and shows in Ranchi.<ref>{{cite web|title=State to celebrate its 19th year of foundation on November 15|url=https://www.dailypioneer.com/2019/state-editions/state-to-celebrate-its-19th-year-of-foundation-on-november-15.html|website=The Pioneer|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> Despite their decision of 2018, which meant to not take part in any competitions, the band went to register for Wacken Metal Battle which is organized by [[Bangalore Open Air]]. It is India's only dedicated Heavy metal open-air music festival which takes place yearly in [[Bangalore]] in collaboration with [[Wacken Open Air]]. The winning band gets an opportunity to play at Wacken Open Air in Germany which is one of the largest heavy metal festivals in the world. The band had earlier registered for the competition in 2017 but couldn't go to perform due to their bassist's unavailability. So they once again gave a try by participating in the competition in 2020 and were shortlisted for the Eastern India-leg of Wacken Metal Battle alongside other [[West Bengal]]-based bands. Highway 69 could not win the competition but the band shared the stage with some really great bands in the competition and witnessed the performance of headliners like [[Chronic Xorn]] and [[Kryptos]].\n\nThe band went for recording their debut album in 2018-2019 but were not impressed with the final recording, mixing and mastering done by the studio. This caused a huge loss for the band also in their album release dates. Currently, all the band members live in different places with Alvin in [[Ranchi]], Binit in [[Khelari]] and John in [[Khunti]] of [[Jharkhand]] state while Tarang lives in [[Angul]] of [[Odisha]] state of India. Despite living in different places, the band generally meets in weekdays for their band practice which requires all the members to take out time and travel to Ranchi (except Alvin who lives in Ranchi). Also with the loss suffered in their album recording, the band has cancelled the plan of recording its album and is currently recording three singles at music studios of [[Kolkata]]. Due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]], their recording dates have been postponed but the band has targeted to release these three singles along with its music videos in the year 2020 itself.\n\n==Band members==\n<!--Do not change the order of the members, as they are in order of instrument to reflect the timeline.-->\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Current members'''\n* Tarang Kerketta \u2013 vocals <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Alvin Rozario]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n* Binit Barla \u2013 bass, backing vocals <small>(2012\u2013present)</small>\n* John Raj Swami \u2013 drums <small>(2015\u2013present)</small>\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Former members'''\n* Dheeraj Edward \u2013 drums <small>(2012\u20132013 & 2015)</small>\n* Anugraha Sonal Johnson Mundu \u2013 drums <small>(2014)</small>\n* Nikhil Dhanraj \u2013 drums <small>(2017)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Timeline===\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:25\nPlotArea = left:90 bottom:80 top:10 right:10\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:10/01/2012 till:{{#time: m/d/Y}}\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:3\nScaleMajor = increment:2 start:2013\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:2013\n\nColors =\n id:vocals value:red    legend:Vocals\n id:guitar value:green  legend:Guitar,_backing_vocals\n id:bass   value:blue   legend:Bass,_backing_vocals\n id:drums