6\n|Wildfire of [[Spring Fest]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]], [[West Bengal]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2016\n|Blizzard of Rock of Chaos\n|[[Indian Institute of Management Ahmedabad]], [[Gujarat]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2016\n|Thunder of Radio Dhoom\n|[[Ranchi]], [[Jharkhand]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2016\n|Strawberry Fields\n|[[National Law School of India University]], [[Karnataka]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Resonance of [[Festember]]\n|[[National Institute of Technology, Tiruchirappalli]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Thunder of Radio Dhoom\n|[[Ranchi]], [[Jharkhand]]\n|{{won}}\n|Best Vocalist and Best Drummer\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|B-School of Rock of [[Unmaad]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Management Bangalore]], Karnataka\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Wildfire of [[Spring Fest]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Kharagpur]], [[West Bengal]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Wacken Metal Battle of [[Wacken Open Air]], hosted by [[Bangalore Open Air]]\n|[[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]]\n|\n|''Finalists of Eastern India''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Synchronicity of [[Antaragni]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Kanpur]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n|1st Runner Up\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Till Deaf Do We Part of [[Pearl (cultural festival)]]\n|[[Birla Institute of Technology and Science, Pilani \u2013 Hyderabad Campus]], [[Telangana]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Decibelz of Xpressions\n|[[Xavier Institute of Management, Bhubaneswar]], [[Odisha]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Hornbill International Rock Contest\n|[[Hornbill Festival]], [[Dimapur]], [[Nagaland]]\n|\n|''Finalists'' along with Best Drummer\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2017\n|Livewire of [[Mood Indigo (festival)]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Bombay]], [[Maharashtra]]\n|2nd Runner Up\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2018\n|Rock-O-Phonix of [[Alcheringa (festival)]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Guwahati]], [[Assam]\n|\n|''Finalists'' along with Best Stage Presence and Drummer\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2018\n|Decibels of [[Saarang]]\n|[[Indian Institute of Technology Madras]], [[Tamil Nadu]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2018\n|Thundermarch of Incandescene\n|[[National Institute of Technology, Silchar]], [[Assam]]\n|{{won}}\n|\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2018\n|Hornbill International Rock Contest\n|[[Hornbill Festival]], [[Dimapur]], [[Nagaland]]\n|\n|''Finalists''\n|-\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2020\n|Wacken Metal Battle of [[Wacken Open Air]], hosted by [[Bangalore Open Air]]\n|TopCat CCU, [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]]\n|\n|''Finalists of Eastern India''\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Metallica}}\n[[Category:Indian rock music]]\n[[Category:Indian rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Indian heavy metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Jharkhand]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2012]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Indian musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical quintets]]\n[[Category:Articles which contain graphical timelines]]\n", "name_user": "Tarun Paul Kachhap", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHeadlining & judging shows, upcoming debut album (2019\u2013present)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Highway_69_(band)"}
{"title_page": "Nguy\u1ec5n Sinh S\u1eafc", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Nguy\u1ec5n Sinh S\u1eafc\n| image         = T\u01b0\u1ee3ng Nguy\u1ec5n Sinh S\u1eafc.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Statue of Nguy\u1ec5n Sinh S\u1eafc\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = 1862\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = 1929\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Nguy\u1ec5n Sinh S\u1eafc''' ([[ch\u1eef H\u00e1n]]: \u962e\u751f\u8272, [[Kim Li\u00ean, Ngh\u1ec7 An|Kim Li\u00ean]] village in [[Nam \u0110\u00e0n District]] of [[Ngh\u1ec7 An]], 1862\u20131929) was the father of [[Ho Chi Minh]].<ref>Taylor ''Goddess on the Rise: Pilgrimage and Popular Religion in Vietnam'' 2004 Page 195 \"Two of the most recently constructed memorials in this religious tradition celebrate the lives of Nguy\u1ec5n Sinh S\u1eafc (1863\u20131929), the father of Ho Chi Minh, and [[T\u00f4n \u0110\u1ee9c Th\u1eafng]] (1888\u20131980), who succeeded Ho Chi Minh as president of socialist Vietnam\"</ref>\n\nHis wife, and the mother of Ho Chi Minh, was Ho\u00e0ng Th\u1ecb Loan (1868\u20131901), the daughter of his adoptive father and teacher. He passed the Confucian c\u1eed nh\u00e2n examination in 1894 and in 1901 gained a second-rank (pho bang) position.<ref>Sophie Quinn-Judge ''Ho Chi Minh: the missing years, 1919\u20131941'' 2003 Page 328 \"Father of Ho Chi Minh, from Kim Lien village in Nam Dan district of Nghe An. Married Hoang Thi Loan, the daughter of his teacher and adopted father. In 1894 passed the cu nhan examination, then in 1901 gained a second-rank (pho bang) \"</ref> He was a magistrate in the Binh Khe district ([[Qui Nh\u01a1n]]), until he was demoted for abuse of power after a landlord whom he had ordered to be beaten died shortly after receiving a caning.<ref>Pierre Brocheux ''Ho Chi Minh: A Biography 2007'' Page 4 \"9 As vice magistrate, Sac became known as a defender of the lowly and poor against the high and \"wicked\" \u2013 whether ... served as interpreter between the demonstrators and the French Resident Superieur). Nguyen Sinh Sac's luck ran out in 1910, when his temper got him into serious trouble. ... Sac then ordered the landlord to be beaten with a wicker switch, and the man died two months later.</ref> Ho Chi Minh's parents' house is now preserved as the [[Kim Li\u00ean museum]]; some charge that a [[personality cult]] has developed around S\u1eafc.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sac, Nguyen Sinh}}\n[[Category:Vietnamese government officials]]\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ho Chi Minh]]\n[[Category:People from Ngh\u1ec7 An Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Nguy\u1ec5n Sinh S\u1eafc\n| image         = T\u01b0\u1ee3ng Nguy\u1ec5n Sinh S\u1eafc.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Statue of Nguy\u1ec5n Sinh S\u1eafc\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = 1862\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = 1929\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Nguy\u1ec5n Sinh S\u1eafc''' ([[ch\u1eef H\u00e1n]]: \u962e\u751f\u8272, [[Kim Li\u00ean]] village in [[Nam \u0110\u00e0n District]] of [[Ngh\u1ec7 An]], 1862\u20131929) was the father of [[Ho Chi Minh]].<ref>Taylor ''Goddess on the Rise: Pilgrimage and Popular Religion in Vietnam'' 2004 Page 195 \"Two of the most recently constructed memorials in this religious tradition celebrate the lives of Nguy\u1ec5n Sinh S\u1eafc (1863\u20131929), the father of Ho Chi Minh, and [[T\u00f4n \u0110\u1ee9c Th\u1eafng]] (1888\u20131980), who succeeded Ho Chi Minh as president of socialist Vietnam\"</ref>\n\nHis wife, and the mother of Ho Chi Minh, was Ho\u00e0ng Th\u1ecb Loan (1868\u20131901), the daughter of his adoptive father and teacher. He passed the Confucian c\u1eed nh\u00e2n examination in 1894 and in 1901 gained a second-rank (pho bang) position.<ref>Sophie Quinn-Judge ''Ho Chi Minh: the missing years, 1919\u20131941'' 2003 Page 328 \"Father of Ho Chi Minh, from Kim Lien village in Nam Dan district of Nghe An. Married Hoang Thi Loan, the daughter of his teacher and adopted father. In 1894 passed the cu nhan examination, then in 1901 gained a second-rank (pho bang) \"</ref> He was a magistrate in the Binh Khe district ([[Qui Nh\u01a1n]]), until he was demoted for abuse of power after a landlord whom he had ordered to be beaten died shortly after receiving a caning.<ref>Pierre Brocheux ''Ho Chi Minh: A Biography 2007'' Page 4 \"9 As vice magistrate, Sac became known as a defender of the lowly and poor against the high and \"wicked\" \u2013 whether ... served as interpreter between the demonstrators and the French Resident Superieur). Nguyen Sinh Sac's luck ran out in 1910, when his temper got him into serious trouble. ... Sac then ordered the landlord to be beaten with a wicker switch, and the man died two months later.</ref> Ho Chi Minh's parents' house is now preserved as the [[Kim Li\u00ean museum]]; some charge that a [[personality cult]] has developed around S\u1eafc.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sac, Nguyen Sinh}}\n[[Category:Vietnamese government officials]]\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1929 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ho Chi Minh]]\n[[Category:People from Ngh\u1ec7 An Province]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toKim Li\u00ean(link changed toKim Li\u00ean, Ngh\u1ec7 An) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nguy%E1%BB%85n_Sinh_S%E1%BA%AFc"}
{"title_page": "Tourism in Vietnam", "text_new": "[[File:HoiAnOldQuarter.jpg|thumb|311.992x311.992px|[[H\u1ed9i An]] a trading port dating from the [[List of cities by time of continuous habitation|15th to the 19th century]].]]\n[[File:Golden Bridge (Vietnam).jpg|thumb|The [[Golden Bridge (Vietnam)|Golden Bridge]] at [[B\u00e0 N\u00e0 Hills|Bana Hills]]]]\n[[File:Cable car station going Fansipan.jpg|thumb|A Cable Car station located in Sapa, [[Fansipan]]: the highest mountain in the [[Indochina|Indochinese Peninsula]].]]\n[[File:Son Doong Cave DB (3).jpg|thumb|The [[Hang S\u01a1n \u0110o\u00f2ng]] is the largest known cave passage in the world by volume. It is so large it contains its own [[Subterranean river|subterranean]] Forest and ecosystem.]]\n[[File:Marble Mountain Gate, Da Nang.jpg|thumb|The Gate leading to the [[Marble Mountains (Vietnam)|Marble Mountains]] a popular tourist destination.]]\n[[File:Ban Gioc - Detian Falls2.jpg|thumb|[[Ban Gioc\u2013Detian Falls|Ban Gioc Falls]] Giant Waterfalls located in Northern Vietnam. ]]\n[[File:BaiDinh Dien TamThe.JPG|alt=|thumb|[[B\u00e1i \u0110\u00ednh Temple]] a popular site for Buddhist pilgrimages from across Vietnam.]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n[[File:Halong bay vietnam.JPG|alt=|thumb|[[H\u1ea1 Long Bay]]]]\n[[File:Hue Vietnam Citadel-of-Hu\u1ebf-01.jpg|thumb|[[Imperial City, Hu\u1ebf]] the former imperial capital of [[Vietnam]].]]\n'''Tourism in Vietnam''' is a component of the modern [[Economy of Vietnam|Vietnamese economy]]. In 2019, [[Vietnam]] received 18 million international arrivals, up from 2.1 million in the year 2000. The Vietnam National Administration of Tourism is following a long-term plan to diversify the tourism industry, which brings foreign exchange into the country.<ref name=cp>[http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/profiles/Vietnam.pdf Vietnam country profile]. [[Library of Congress]] [[Federal Research Division]] (December 2005). ''This article incorporates text from this source, which is in the [[public domain]].''</ref>\n\nTourist arrivals in Vietnam have continued to rise in recent years. In 2008, Vietnam received 4.218 million international tourists, in 2009 the number was 3.8 million, down 11%. In 2012, Vietnam received 6.84 million tourists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vietnamtourism.gov.vn/english/index.php?cat=012041&itemid=6308|title=Vietnam National Administration of Tourism|author=TITC|publisher=|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref> This was a 13% increase from 2011 figure of 6 million international visitors, which was itself a rise of 2 million visitors relative to 2010 arrivals. In 2016, Vietnam welcomed 10 million international visitors which represented a 26% increase from the previous year.<ref name=vnat2011>{{cite web|title=International visitors to Vietnam in December and 12 months of 2011|url=http://www.vietnamtourism.gov.vn/english/index.php?cat=012040&itemid=5143|work=Vietnam National Administration of Tourism|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Statistics for 2010|url=http://www.gso.gov.vn/default.aspx?tabid=621&ItemID=10835|work=General Statistics Office|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Tourism in the economy==\nTourism is important in Vietnam. For [[backpacking (travel)|backpackers]], culture and [[nature]] lovers, beach-lovers, military soldiers and veterans, Vietnam has become a new tourist destination in Southeast Asia. Local and international tour operators offer tours to ethnic minority groups, walking and bicycle tours, photography tours, kayak trips and multi-country trips in particular with neighboring [[Cambodia]], [[Laos]] and Thailand. Foreign tourists have been able to travel freely in the country since 1997.\n\nThe [[economy of Vietnam]] has transformed from an agrarian to a service economy. More than a third of gross domestic product is generated by services, which include the hotel and catering industry and transportation. The manufacturing and construction (28 percent), agriculture and fisheries (20 percent) and mining (10 percent) have much smaller shares.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gtai.de/ext/anlagen/PubAnlage_6108.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-06-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719034804/http://www.gtai.de/ext/anlagen/PubAnlage_6108.pdf |archivedate=19 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>{{failed verification|date=June 2019}}\n\nTourism contributes 4.5 percent to gross domestic product (as of 2007). After heavy industry and urban development, most foreign investment in Vietnam has been concentrated in tourism, especially in hotel projects .<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gtai.de/ext/anlagen/PubAnlage_5861.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-06-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719034908/http://www.gtai.de/ext/anlagen/PubAnlage_5861.pdf |archivedate=19 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nAccording to usual report of World Tourism and Travel Council, tourism contributed 6.6 percent to GDP equal VND 279,287 billion (03/2016) which has important contribution promoting development of related sectors such as transportation, entertainment, cuisine etc.\n\nVietnam has recently started tourist slogans, known as \"'''Vietnam Timeless Charm'''\".<ref>http://vietnamtourism.gov.vn/english/index.php/items/4294</ref>\n\n==Tourism statistics==\n\n===International visitors===\nData source: Ministry of Culture, Sport & Tourism<ref>{{cite web|title=Tourism Statistics|url=http://vietnamtourism.gov.vn/english/index.php/items/13551|work=Vietnam National Administration of Tourism|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year!!Tourist<br/>Arrivals!!Change\n|-\n|3/2020|| align=\"right\" |3,686,779||1.9% <ref>{{cite web|title=Tourism Statistics|url=http://vietnamtourism.gov.vn/english/index.php/statistic/international|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2019|| align=\"right\" |18,008,591||16.2% <ref>{{cite web|title=Tourism Statistics|url=http://vietnamtourism.gov.vn/english/index.php/statistic/international|accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|2018||align=\"right\"|15,497,791||19.9% <ref>{{cite web|title=Tourism Statistics|url=http://vietnamtourism.gov.vn/index.php/items/28014|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2017 ||align=\"right\"|12,922,151||29.1%<ref>{{cite web|title=Tourism Statistics |url=http://vietnamtourism.gov.vn/english/index.php/items/12453|work=Vietnam National Administration of Tourism|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016||align=\"right\"|10,012,735||26%\n|-\n|2015||align=\"right\"|7,943,651||0.9%\n|-\n|2014||align=\"right\"|7,874,312||4%\n|-\n|2013||align=\"right\"|7,572,352||10.60%\n|-\n|2012||align=\"right\"|6,847,678||10.8%\n|-\n|2011||align=\"right\"|6,014,032||19.1%\n|-\n|2010||align=\"right\"|5,049,855||34.8%\n|-\n|2009||align=\"right\"|3,772,359||\u221210.9%\n|-\n|2008||align=\"right\"|4,253,740||0.6%\n|-\n|2007||align=\"right\"|4,171,564||16%\n|-\n|2006||align=\"right\"|3,583,486||3%\n|-\n|2005||align=\"right\"|3,467,757||18.4%\n|-\n|2004||align=\"right\"|2,927,876||20.5%\n|-\n|2003||align=\"right\"|2,429,600||\u22127.6%\n|-\n|2002||align=\"right\"|2,628,200||12.8%\n|-\n|2001||align=\"right\"|2,330,800||8.9%\n|-\n|2000||align=\"right\"|2,140,100||20.0%\n|-\n|1999||align=\"right\"|1,781,800||17.2%\n|-\n|1998||align=\"right\"|1,520,100||\u221211.4%\n|-\n|1997||align=\"right\"|1,715,600||6.7%\n|-\n|1996||align=\"right\"|1,607,200||18.9%\n|-\n|1995||align=\"right\"|1,351,300||&nbsp;\n|}\n\n===Top 29 International Visitors in Vietnam===\nData Source: Ministry of Culture, Sport & Tourism<ref name=vnat2011 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://vietnamtourism.gov.vn/english/index.php/items/9968 |title=International visitors to Viet Nam in December and 12 months of 2018 |publisher=Vietnamtourism.gov.vn |date= |accessdate=2017-06-28}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Rank||Country||3/2020||2019||2018 || 2017 || 2016 || 2015 || 2014 || 2013 || 2012 || 2011\n|-\n|1||  {{flagcountry|China}